Question:
An 18-year-old medical student decides he is going to get buff, so starts consuming protein shakes. Whilst drinking a shake after a massive session of squats in the gym, he contemplates the process of digestion. He recalls that one of the enzymes involved in protein digestion (a proteolytic enzyme) in the stomach is pepsin and it's inactive precursor (zymogen) is pepsinogen. But he can't remember which cells in the stomach secrete pepsinogen. He asks a fellow medical student who knows everything as she uses PeerWise everyday.

 

Which cells does she tell him are responsible?
Explanation:
Chief cells (found in the body of the stomach) are responsible for secretion of pepsinogen, which is converted into the active proteolytic enzyme pepsin.

 

Consumption of protein stimulates the production of gastrin, secreted by G cells. Gastrin then stimulates the secretion of both intrinsic factor and hydrochloric acid from parietal cells. The hydrochloric acid catalyses the conversion of pesinogen to pepsin. The acidic environment created and pepsin are both important for the hydrolysis of proteins. Intrinsic factor is responsible for assisting absorption of vitamin B12 found in proteinaceous foods such as meat, fish and eggs. D cells (found in the antrum of the stomach) are stimulated by Gastrin and secrete somatostatin, a hormone which inhibits Gastrin excretion from G cells and hydrochloric acid from parietal cells (a negative feedback mechanism presenting the stomach becoming too acidic).

 

Leydig cells are testosterone producing cells found in the testicles. They are important for getting buff but have little direct influence on digestion.

 

Random mnemonic: I remember that chief cells secrete pepsinogen and are found in the body of the stomach by picturing the image of a native American chief drinking pepsi, which goes into his body.  

 

Pepsi is the ancient Greek word for digestion.

 

Apparently the drink "Pepsi" is so named as it was initially marketed as a digestive aid (although the sources for this are dubious), other dubious sources claim that Pepsi is called Pepsi because Pepsin is involved or was involved in it's production (again, this is from dodgy internet sources, not necessarily true). The rest of the information in this question is true though! Sources include: " Marieb, Human anatomy and Physiology, 6th edition" and "Faller, The human body: an introduction to structure and function, 13th edition".

Question: An 18 year old female  has had a horse riding accident and is having difficulty breathing. Following examination her doctor discovers that she has damaged the nerves  supplying her diaphragm. What is this nerve?

OptionD: Angle between the right internal jugular vein and the right sublavian vein
Explanation: The thoracic duct is the only visible duct in dissection. It starts at the cisterna chyli located on the right side, anterior to the vertebrae and posterior to the oesophagus, crosses at the 5th of 6th vertebrae to the right side to finally drain into the angle between the left internal jugular vein and the left subclavian vein.

Question: You are placing ECG electrodes on a patient that has suspected heart problems. Where would you place V4 chest lead?
OptionA: left margin of sternum in 4th intercostal space
OptionE: right margin of sternum in 4th intercostal space
Explanation:
The six chest leads (V1-V6) make up the remainder of the conventional 12-lead EKG. These are unipolar leads that record the potential difference between a central terminal (can be considered as zero potential) and electrodes at each of six positions on the chest wall. QRS complexes recorded in leads V1 and V2 are normally inverted as the wave of depolarization moves away from these leads that are on the right side of the chest.


Lead Position of exploring electrode
V1 4th intercostal (between the ribs) space just to the right of sternum
V2 4th intercostal space just to the left of sternum
V3 Midway between V2 and V4
V4 5th intercostal space at the left midclavicular (mid-collar bone) line
V5 left anterior axillary (armpit) line horizontally to the left of V4
V6 midaxillary line horizontally to the left of V4 and V5

Question: What is the pulmonary ligament?
OptionA: The only connection of the parietal pleura and the diaphragm.
OptionB: The ligament which support the aorta during systole.
OptionC: The reflection of the mediastinal parietal pleura below the lung root on each side.
OptionD: The ligament which support the pulmonary artery during systole.
Explanation:
The pulmonary ligament is not a true ligament but rather the reflection of the mediastinal parietal pleura below the lung root on each side. In this area, the pleura is thrown out into a loose fold that projects medially and connects with the contralateral pleura in the region between the aorta and oesophagus.

Inferiorly, it ends with a free margin. The parietal and visceral layers are in very close apposition within the fold and there is continuity with the bottom of each lung root which lies superiorly.

Hence, in a manner akin to the pleural recesses, the pulmonary ligaments provides a potential space for the expansion of lung tissue. In this case, the expansion is required for:

inferior movement of the lung root with inspiration expansion of the pulmonary vein

Occasionally, an aberrant pulmonary artery originating from the aorta may be found in the pulmonary ligament.

Question: Connective tissue is made up of two key components. Ground substance is one, what is the other ?

A 26-year-old man reports numbness and tingling in his hands for the last 3 weeks. The numbness began during a 4 week cycling trip, he returned 1 week ago. On examination there is reduced or altered sensation in his little fingers, medial side of his ring fingers and the medial volar surface of both hands.

 

Which nerve is affected?
Explanation:
This man has a bilateral compressive neuropathy of his ulnar nerves. Likely to be caused in this case by compression of the ulnar nerve by the handle bars at the anatomic location of Guyon's canal at the base of the hand. Compression of the ulnar nerve can occur anywhere along it's course (from the shoulder to the hand) resulting in neuropathy, the most common location of compression is at the elbow.

 

Changing how he grips his handle bars (taking the weight off of his medial palm) should allow his symptoms to gradually resolve.

Question: An increase in end-diastolic volume leads to:
OptionA: An increase in stroke volume according to Starling law and a decrease in stroke volume according to Law of Laplace
OptionB: An decrease in stroke volume according to Starling law and a decrease in stroke volume according to Law of Laplace
OptionC: An increase in stroke volume according to Starling law and a increase in stroke volume according to Law of Laplace
OptionD: An decrease in stroke volume according to Starling law and a increase in stroke volume according to Law of Laplace
OptionE: Only Starling law is related to end-diastolic volume and it leads to an increase in stroke volume
Explanation:
As the end diastolic volume increases, the radius of the ventricle increases and a smaller component of the wall tension is angled towards the cavity generating less pressure which leads to a decrease in stroke volume ( law of Laplace).

As the end-diastolic volume increases, the actin-myosin lateral spacing is decreasing increasing the number of cross-bridges which leads to a more powerful contraction and an increase in stroke volume.

Question: What influences the afterload experienced by the heart?
OptionE: Afterload can be applied just to skeletal muscle
Explanation: According to law of Laplace, both arterial pressure and ventricle radius determine the afterload. This explains why blood ejection is easier as the ejection phase progresses. As the ventricle is contracting, the radius decreases and higher component of the wall tension is angled towards the cavity decreasing the afterload ( i.e the load against the heart must work in order to pump blood).

Question: Towards the end of the plateau phase of the ventricular cardiomyocyte the L-type Ca channels begin to close. Although the influx of Ca 2+ through L-type Ca channels falls the plateau still persists for a short period of time. Why?
OptionA: Inward rectified K+ channels start to close too
OptionC: Outward K+ channels start to close too
OptionE: Voltage-gated Na channels open and Na influx balances the K+ efflux
Explanation: The Na/Ca exchanger pumps 3 Na in for each 2 Ca pumped out. As a consequence it has a depolarizing effect which combined with the reduced Ca influx through L-type Ca channels is able to keep the plateau for a brief period of time before the opening of delayed rectified K+ channel produce the repolarization. Inward rectified K+ are open only around the equilibrium potential of K+ while transient outward K+ channel begin only to close after the repolarization by voltage-gated K+ channel was initiated

Question:
You are a junior doctor on a busy Saturday night working in A&E.  Jason a 18 year old male is rushed in to see you, he's been attacked by a savage gang of local girls  outside Bunker and Walkabout. They  didn't like the fact Jason (a university student) was out in Cardiff  on a Saturday night.  Jason injuries seem to have been caused by punches but also a knife. Jason protected his thorax with this arm whilst  his hand grasped the phone, so his dad could hear everything that happened in the attack .  His right arm is cover in blood from several lesions.  When asked to do some simple movements  tests you see he has wrist drop and claw hand. 

 

What has been damaged in the attack  ?
OptionC: The right ulnar and medial nerves
Explanation:
The injuries are only to Jason's right fore arm. So discount the left sided option. 

Ulnar nerve damage causes claw hand. 

Radial nerve damage causes wrist drop. 

 

Disclaimer: Jason woke up and it was all a dream.

Question: Because of the gravity the pressure in the arteries below the heart increases. However the blood pressure in the aorta remains the same. Therefore blood flows from aorta (MAP=95mmHg) to arteries in legs (185mmHg) against a pressure gradient. How is this possible?
OptionA: Blood always flows against a pressure gradient
OptionB: Blood flows due to an energy gradient
OptionC: Blood doesn't flow in the arteries in the legs why a person is standing
Explanation: Blood flows due to an energy gradient as predicted by Bernoulli's equation The blood in the aorta has a higher potential energy which makes the energy gradient favourable to blood flowing in the arteries. The perfusion pressure=pressure arteries-pressure in the veins and remains constant because the arteries and veins are affected to the same degree by gravity but this is  not a reason for blood flowing from the aorta to the terminal arteries

Question: Mrs jones (60 years of age) has been feeling breathless and a bit Dizzy, when her GP listened to her chest her heart beat was irregular. An ECG was performed, and revealed that the PR interval started in the normal range but got longer with each heart beat until a P wave failed to elicit a QRS complex, the cycle then began again. What does the ECG indicate?
Explanation:
Heart block is a condition where the AV node or purkinje fibres fail to transmit or delay an action potential.

In 1st degree heart block there is a delay of conduction.

There are 2 types of second degree heart block Mobitz type 1 and Mobitz type 2. In Mobitz type 1 the PR interval lengthens until no QRS wave is elicited by the P wave. In in Mobitz type 2 occasionally the P wave fails to cause a QRS complex but there isn't an elongation of the PR interval.

3rd degree heart block is when no action potential passes through the AV node into the ventricles and they have to establish their own often irregular rhythm.

Question: The influx of what ion causes the 'funny current' during depolarisation of the Sino Atrial node?
OptionE: A balance between influx of Ca++ and efflux of K+
Explanation:
Pacemaking is a basic physiological process, and the cellular mechanisms involved in this function have always attracted the keen attention of investigators. The “funny” (If) current, originally described in sinoatrial node myocytes as an inward current activated on hyperpolarization to the diastolic range of voltages, has properties suitable for generating repetitive activity and for modulating spontaneous rate. The degree of activation of the funny current determines, at the end of an action potential, the steepness of phase 4 depolarization; hence, the frequency of action potential firing. Because If is controlled by intracellular cAMP and is thus activated and inhibited by β-adrenergic and muscarinic M2 receptor stimulation, respectively, it represents a basic physiological mechanism mediating autonomic regulation of heart rate. Given the complexity of the cellular processes involved in rhythmic activity, an exact quantification of the extent to which If and other mechanisms contribute to pacemaking is still a debated issue; nonetheless, a wealth of information collected since the current was first described more than 30 years ago clearly agrees to identify If as a major player in both generation of spontaneous activity and rate control. If- dependent pacemaking has recently advanced from a basic, physiologically relevant concept, as originally described, to a practical concept that has several potentially useful clinical applications and can be valuable in therapeutically relevant conditions. Typically, given their exclusive role in pacemaking, f-channels are ideal targets of drugs aiming to pharmacological control of cardiac rate. Molecules able to bind specifically to and block f-channels can thus be used as pharmacological tools for heart rate reduction with little or no adverse cardiovascular side effects. Indeed a selective f-channel inhibitor, ivabradine, is today commercially available as a tool in the treatment of stable chronic angina. Also, several loss-of-function mutations of HCN4 (hyperpolarization-activated, cyclic-nucleotide gated 4), the major constitutive subunit of f-channels in pacemaker cells, are known today to cause rhythm disturbances, such as for example inherited sinus bradycardia. Finally, gene- or cell-based methods for in situ delivery of f-channels to silent or defective cardiac muscle represent novel approaches for the development of biological pacemakers eventually able to replace electronic devices.

 

Note: A balance between influx of Ca++ and efflux of K+ results in the plateau stage of the AV node.

Question: Where the viscosity is at the minimum?
OptionA: In aorta because of the high pressure
OptionC: In capillaries because of the bolus flow
OptionD: In arteries because of tank treading movement of red blood cells
OptionE: In aorta because of the bolus flow
Explanation:
The axial streaming of the RBC leaves a cell-deficient layer near the arterial wall (marginal layer). The viscosity decreases near the arterial wall where the shear stresses are highest leading to an overall decrease in blood viscosity.

However in the capillaries, since RBC diameter is almost equivalent with the capillary diameter , RBC flow in a layer and the blood between them is driven by the circular current derived from the tank treading of RBC. This eliminates the internal friction associated with laminar flow and therefore viscosity is the lowest

Question:
A 19-year-old medical student presents with pain and swelling at the base of his right thumb. He reports an amorous encounter on a MedSoc social with a fellow medical student, with whom he returned to his halls of residence. Due to the narrow beds, alcohol excess and obscure mid-coital positioning he fell onto his extended wrist, which resulted in severe pain.  

There is exquisite tenderness on palpation of the anatomical snuff box of his right wrist. He is told by the doctor that his wrist x-ray shows a fracture of a carpal bone.

 

Which bone is most likely to be fractured?
Explanation:
The scaphoid is the most commonly fractured carpal bone. The usual mechanism of injury is a fall onto an extended wrist, typical history and examination findings include: pain and swelling at the base of the thumb and tenderness on palpation of the anatomical snuff box*.

 

The history of presenting complaint in this question is reminiscent of a mnemonic for remembering the carpal bones: Some Lovers Try Positions That They Can't Handle  = Scaphoid Lunate Triquetrum Pisiform Trapezium Trapezoid Capitate Hamate. 

 

*the anatomical snuff box is the depression between the extensor pollicis longus and extensor pollicis brevis tendons at the base of the thumb. This recess is so named for it's use of holding snuff (ground tobacco) prior to nasal insufflation. 

 

Jason

Question: In tetrodotoxin poisoning, which ion channel is blocked?
Explanation: TTX is a neurotoxin that binds to the extracellular side of a Voltage Gated Sodium Channel. This stops action potentials being generated which is potentially life threatening if not immediately treated.

Question: Jamie Roberts is playing against Australia on Saturday in the first Welsh autumn test match.  He has studying medicine here at Cardiff university. One of the older year students tell you of a rumour that once playing for uni he tackled someone so hard it dislocated their glenohumeral joint.  At A&E after relocation of the humerus, The F1 doc wants to check the auxiliary nerve function to see  where the dislocation damaged it. What should the doctor do to check the auxiliary nerve?
OptionA: See if the patient has claw hands
OptionB: Ask the patient to try and abduct the injured shoulder against resistance all the way to right angles with the body
OptionD: test small abduction of the upper limb under 20 degrees.
OptionE: order an MRI and see if damage can be seen on the scan.
Explanation:
The auxiliary nerve innervates the deltoid. This muscle is the main abductor of the shoulder joint from 18 to 90 degrees (from 0 to 18 by supraspinatus). Injury can result in a reduction in shoulder abduction.

 

So a test can be applied to a patient with injury of axillary nerve by trying to abduct the injured shoulder against resistance

Question: A pregnant woman is undergoing screening to see if there is a possibility that her child will have Down's syndrome. People with Down's syndrome have an extra chromosome 21. What happens during the formation of gametes to cause this?
Explanation:
Aneuploidy is defined as having a chromosome number that is not a multiple of the haploid number for the species.

 

Disjunction is the separation of chromatids or chromosomes during anaphase.

 

Nondisjunction is when two chromosomes or chromatids do not separate.

 

Nondisjunction leads to one daughter cell having too many chromosomes and the other having too few (in Down's syndrome the gamete has an extra chromosome 21), these daughter cells are aneuploid.

Question: Which of these bones is not a carpal bone
Explanation: The malleus is an auditory ossicle - a bone found in your middle ear. The carpal bones are the scapoid, lunate, triquetrum, pisiform, trapezium, trapezoid, capitate and hamate - they are your wrist bones.

Question: Roughly, according to NHS guidelines, how many proportions of oily fish should you have a week as part of a balanced diet?

Question:
There are 3 different sets of exons within the variable region of an immunoglobulin DNA sequence. After DNA recombination by an individual B cell a a smaller functional gene sequence for a specific variable region is produced.

 

The types of exons in the heavy and light chain variable region is different. What are the exons in a light chain variable region and how many of each type of exon are present?
Explanation:
There three sets of exons in the DNA sequence for the variable region of an immunoglobulin. These sets are called the Variable (V), the Diversity (D) and the Joining (J) exons. During somatic recombination the DNA sequence is cut down to just one of each segment.

 

A Light chain variable region has one V and J exon

 

A heavy chain varibale region has one V, D and J exon.

Question: Which type of actin polymer is present in the sliding filament theory, in relation to muscle contraction?
Explanation: Actin monomers (G actin) polymerize to form actin filaments (F actin). The first step is the formation of dimers and trimers, which then grow by the addition of monomers to both ends.

Question: You are a junior doctor working in a busy A&E department when a 26-year old male presents with pain during inspiration and breathlessness. Traumatic Pneumothorax - follows a penetrating chest trauma such as a stab wound, gunshot injury or a fractured rib

Question: Which one of the following is not a nucleoside?

Question: What is the function of an occluding junction?
OptionA: to bind cells together and prevent diffusion of molecules between adjacent cells
OptionB: to allow direct communication between attached cells
OptionC: to mechanically attach the cells to one another
OptionD: to allow just sodium ions to travel between epithelial cells
OptionE: to allow just potassium ions to travel between epithelial cells

Question: Jeremy needs a simple 3 lead ECG, he is quite overweight and his mean electrical axis has moved to ~15 degrees. Which ECG lead with correct placing of electrodes will give the ECG with the most clear P wave?
OptionA: Lead 2, positive electrode on right arm, negative electrode on left ankle.
OptionB: Lead 1, negative electrode on right arm, positive electrode on left arm.
OptionC: Lead 3, negative electrode on left arm, positive electrode on left ankle.
OptionD: Lead 1, positive electrode on right arm, negative electrode on the left arm.
OptionE: Lead 2, negative electrode on right arm, positive electrode on left ankle.
Explanation: The P wave is caused by the depolarisation of the atria, a positive action potential spreads across the atria and toads the apex of the heart (it will then travel through the AV node and across the ventricles causing the QRS complex). As the mean electrical axis is nearest to 0 degrees - the angle of Lead 1 this will give the largest P wave. Lead 1 has the negative electrode on the right arm and the positive electrode on the left arm.

The ulnar nerve innervates the medial anterior surface of the palm, the anterior surface of the little finger and the medial edge of the ring finger.

Question: What is the outer most layer of the pericardium?

Question: In the heart,  stimulation of the epicardial plexus (sympathetic innervation) causes an increase in conduction velocity (through the atrioventricular node).  What other effects may occur?
OptionA: Negative chronotropic effect and positive inotropic effect.
OptionB: Positive chronotropic effect and negative inotropic effect.
OptionC: Positive chronotropic effect and positive inotropic effect.
OptionD: Negative chronotropic effect and negative inotropic effect.
Explanation: The sympathetic nervous system results in a "fight or flight" response.  This causes an increase in heart rate/tachycardia (positive chronotropic effect) at the sinoatrial node and an increase in force (positive inotropic effect) at the ventricular muscle walls,  as well as an increase in conduction velocity at the atrioventricular node.
Tags: Nervous system, cardiac cycle, Cardiology, Cardiovascular System

Question: Which of the following is NOT innervated by the radial nerve?

Explanation: Complex III pumps 2H+ per NADH which can release 2 electrons. Therefore H+:e=1:1

Question: Which eukaryotic initiation factor is able to recognize and bind to the methylated guanosine gap of the mRNA?
Explanation: eIF-4 recognizes and binds to methylated cap of the mRNA. Therefore the 40S ribosomal subunit can star scanning the mRNA in the 5'-3' direction.

Question: Which antibody is the most efficient at activating the complement system?
Which protein is considered licensing factor for DNA replication?
Explanation: Cdc6 binds to the ORC (origin recognition complex) and promotes the loading  of the helicase. As soon as S-CDK promotes phosphorylation of the prereplication complex the phosphorilated cdc6 is ubiquinated for destruction to prevent replication occuring at the same point. Therefore Cdc6 is a licesing factor for DNA replication (i.e. it can't occur without it).

Question: The blood pressure is controlled by aortic arch and carotid sinus baroreceptors. Aortic arch baroreceptors lead to an increase in action potential frequency in vagus nerve and the carotid sinus baroreceptors activate glossopharyngeal nerve. Where do the visceral sensory input from this nerve terminate?
Explanation: NTS

Question: A patient with seizures comes to the hospital. What IV drug would you administer?
Explanation: GABA is an inhibitory neurotransmitter. An agonist behaves like GABA and inhibits the CNS stopping the seizures.

Question: What is the difference/similarity between the ulnar claw and hand of benediction?
OptionA: Both are caused by damage to the Ulnar nerve
OptionB: One is caused by damage to the ulnar nerve, the other the median nerve
OptionC: One is caused by damage to the ulnar, the other radial nerve
OptionD: The terms are synonymous-they refer to the same injury
Explanation: Though they look very similar, the hand of benediction is caused by median nerve damage, and the ulnar claw by ulnar nerve damage

Question: In Adherens junctions, what do the cadherin transmembrane proteins bind to extracellularly?
Explanation: The extracellular part of the cadherins protein joins to the adjacent cadherins protein on the cell it is forming the junction with. The intracellular part joints to the own cell's catenin that joins to the actin filament of the cell.

Question: What does the alae nasi muscle do?
Explanation: Flaring of the nostrils is of a minor importance during more extreme exercise as it increases the rate of inspiration and expiration.

Question: A normally very fit patient comes into the clinic complaining of a shortness of breath during more extreme exercise. The consultant believes that she may have some soft tissue damage to one of her accessory muscles of inspiration. During a test it appears that the sternum is not raising as expected during inspiration. What muscle is most likely a cause of the patients shortness of breath?
Explanation:
The sternomastoid muscles raise the sternum.

 

The Scalene Muscles raise rib I and rib II. (attach to the scalene tubercle)

Question: Telomeres are nucleoprotein complexes that are essential for cell viability.  They consist of tandem repeats of short oligonucleotides which are said to be G-rich.  What is this repeated sequence in humans?
Explanation:
Medical Biochemistry Fourth Edition

 

Page 421.

Question: What is the name of the sheath that surrounds each individual axon in a large peripheral nerve cell?
Explanation: Endoneurium surrounds each axon, perineurium surrounds each fasicle (bundle of axons), epineurium surrounds the entire nerve

Question: What percentage of bone cells are osteocytes roughly?
Explanation: http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1VGupEWZAqUC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=percentage+bone+cells+osteocytes&source=bl&ots=rklpO5lVNs&sig=MWAqXW1aQu-S4HA7guhEmp2ZlI8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=SnpeVOL5KKTA7Abgr4HIAw&ved=0CDQQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=percentage%20bone%20cells%20osteocytes&f=false

Question:
A 57 year old male was admitted to intensive care after complaining of fatigue, loss of appetite and vomiting. An abdominal examination was performed which revealed signs of abdominal swelling. The patient also appeared jaundiced. The consultant requested a blood test for aspartate aminotransferase (AST). The results of the blood test showed very high levels of AST (more than 10 times the normal).

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
The blood test for AST is usually used to detect liver damage. An AST test is usually ordered along with several other tests to evaluate a person who has signs and symptoms of a liver disorder such as fatigue and vomiting (as described in the question). Normally levels of AST in the blood are low and very high levels of AST are  usually due to acute hepatitis.

Hepatitis is an inflammation of the liver that is most commonly caused by viruses but may also be due to chemicals, drugs, alcohol, inherited diseases, or autoimmune disease.

AST is an enzyme found in tissue of the heart, skeletal muscle, liver and brain and is used in diagnostic purposes to detect liver disease (Medical Biochemistry p61)

Prostate cancer, bone disease and lymphoma can be discounted from the list of answers because their symptoms do not match those of the patient.

The symptoms of acute pancreatitis are similar to those of acute hepatitis, but AST is not found in the liver so elevated levels of this enzyme would not indicate pancreatitis. Abnormally high levels of amylase and/or lipase would indicate pancreatitis.

Question: Which of these vitamins is not fat soluble?
Explanation: C is water soluble and is found in fruit and veg, as opposed to animal fat and oily fish as the other vitamins listed are found in.

Question: A slow of prolonged depolarization is known as accommodation, this may result in an increase in the threshold potential. What may be the possible cause of this prolonged depolarization?
OptionB: inactivation of potassium ion voltage gated channel
OptionC: Inactivation of sodium ion voltage gated channel
OptionE: activation of Calcium ion voltage gated channel
Explanation: Sodium ion voltage gated channel is inactivated therefore, sodium ions cannot be transported into cell therefore depolarization occurs slowly, thus making it harder for an action potential to be initiated.

Question: Randal is doing some microscope work and he examines different forms of cartilage, hyaline and elastic cartilage in particular. What is the main difference that he will notice between the two cartilage samples?
OptionA: The size of the fibres of  two cartilage samples
OptionB: The respective shapes of the fibres of two cartilage samples
OptionD: Collagen fibres found in one and not the other
OptionE: Elastic fibres found in one and not the other
Explanation: Elastic cartilage contains elastic fibres and Hyaline cartilage does not; it's obvious in its name. Quite an easy question.

Question: What is the proximal attachment of the Subclavius muscle?
OptionD: Junction of 1st rib and its costal cartilage
OptionE: Inferior surface of middle third of clavicle
Explanation:
Proximal means nearer to trunk or point of origin e.g. the elbow is proximal to the wrist, and the proximal part of an artery is its beginning. 

Subclavius anchors and depresses the clavicle.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of Thorax, Anatomy of the upper limb, Thorax, Upper limb

Question: At rest, what is the approximate potassium concentration inside a cell?
Explanation: Potassium concentration is high inside the cell at about 150mM, compared to 5mM in ECF.

Question: A student reads out a definition saying that x is  "the separation of charge across the membrane that generates an electrical force that generates movement". Which of these terms is he/she likely discussing?
Explanation: E is the separation if charge across the membrane and generates an electrical force that combines with the concentration gradient to produce the electrochemical gradient

Question: A 57 year old man comes into the clinic complaining of chronic acid influx. He states that he has never suffered from the condition before. Its revealed that he began experiencing this symptom after a incident at work where he strained himself whilst lifting a very heavy object. He also complains of dull pains in his chest. What is the most likely cause of his symptoms?
OptionA: Rupture of an artery in the proximal third of the duodenum.
OptionC: A tear in the arcuate ligament of his diaphragm
Explanation: Hiatus hernia is the term used to describe a condition where part of the stomach pushes up into the lower chest through a defect in the diaphragm. The diaphragm is the large flat muscle that separates the lungs from the abdomen, which helps us to breathe. Not everyone with a hiatus hernia develops symptoms. However, if you have a hiatus hernia you more prone to reflux acid into your gullet (oesophagus), which can cause heartburn and other symptoms. If symptoms do occur, treatment with acid-suppressing medication usually works

Question: How does interpheron interfere with viral infection?
OptionA: Upregulates the transcription of protein kinase R which leads to phosphorylation of the factor eIf4 which brings the amino acid to the ribosome and therefore inhibiting translation
OptionB: Promotes the synthesis of 2-5 oligoadenylateswhich activate a nuclease that degrade RNAs
OptionE: Binds to viruses  and prevents them from entering the cells
Explanation: Just B.

Question: Which of the following statements is true
OptionA: RNA polymerase II synthesizes all kinds of RNA
OptionD: RNA polymerase III synthesizes small nuclear RNA
OptionE: RNA polymerase II synthesizes tRNA and rRNA
Explanation: In Albert's cell biology at the transcription chapter everything is explained really well.

Question: Which of these is an example of an amphibolic pathway?
Explanation: An amphibolic reaction is one where catabolism and anabolism both occur. In the Kreb's cycle, oxaloacetate and CoA condense to form citrate, this is anabolism. Whereas Isocitrate is broken doen to Beta ketoglutinate, this is catabolism.

Question:
A 23 year old female presents at her local GP surgery complaining of bloating, prolonged fatigue, recurrent stomach pain and constipation. The GP requests a stool sample and blood test. The results of the stool sample reveal steatorrhoea (fatty stools) and the blood test reveals the presence of the IgA (immunoglobin A) form of tTGA (tissue transglutaminase) antibody. The GP refers the patient to a gastroenterologist.

What diagnosis does the GP suggest based on the symptoms and test results?
Explanation:
Coeliac disease is a hereditary chronic intestinal disorder of absorption caused by intolerance to gluten. Gluten is seen as a foreign invader and is attacked by the immune system.This immune system response in celiac disease involves the production of antibodies directed against an enzyme normally present in the intestines called tissue transglutaminase (tTG).In celiac disease, the body produces two types of antibodies that attack tTG, one of which is immunoglobulin A (IgA).

The diagnosis is unlikely to be appendicitis because it would not explain the presence of fatty stools and prolonged fatigue, appendicitis is also not an autoimmune disease so tTG antibodies will not be present.

In most cases gall stones would not cause any symptoms.

The symptoms of lactose intolerance and irritable bowel syndrome are similar to coeliac disease but the tTG antibody test is specific to coeliac disease and rules out any of the other diseases

Question: Which vitamin is used to make NAD from those listed below?
Explanation: Niacin-a water soluble vitamin-is used to make NAD.

Question: What clotting factor is fibrinogen?
Explanation: See Haemostasis lecture-there are 13 clotting factors listed in the powerpoint

Question: What type of inherited disorder is haemorrhagic telangiectasia?
Explanation: haemorrhagic telangiectasia is a vascular defect that is autosomal dominant

Question: Which of the following is not a terminal branch of the brachial plexus?
Explanation: The subclavius comes off from the upper trunk; others are terminal branches.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: Which of these is the correct definition of a foramen?
Explanation:
A to E are respectively; 

Crest, Trochanter, Foramen, Fossa, Groove

Question: What is the normal value for the costophrenic angle?
Explanation: The costophrenic angles are the places where the lungs meet the ribs. Each costophrenic angle can normally be seen as on chest x-ray as a sharply-pointed, downward indentation (dark) between each hemi-diaphragm (white) and the adjacent chest wall (white). A small portion of each lung normally reaches into the costophrenic angle. The normal angle usually measures thirty degrees.

Question: A patient receives surgery for cancer treatment and unfortunately had some of his/her axillary nodes excised. The patent is told that there thoracodorsal nerve has been damaged by the surgery. What physical disability is the patient most likely to suffer from?
OptionB: Weakened ability to abduct and laterally rotate the arm
OptionC: Weakened ability to adduct and medially rotate the arm
Explanation: The thoracodorsal nerve innervates the latissimus dorsi, which extends, medially rotates and adducts the humerus. Therefore any damage to this nerve may affect these functions.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: Tim arrives at A&E with mucosal blisters which are fragile and easily rupture. A diagnosis of the autoimmune disease Pemphigus vulgaris is then made. What epidermal structure is affected in this disease?
Explanation: The epidermal structure that's affected by Pemphigus vulgaris is the desmosomes.

Question: Why are the oblique and horizontal fissures of the lungs important?
OptionD: To identify the apex of the lungs
Explanation: Orientation of fissures determines where to listen to lung sounds from each lobe.

Question: The production of thrombin form prothrombin is activated by which coagulation factor? Also what is its name?
Explanation: X(a) - (the a stands for activated) produces thrombin from prothrombin. It is the product of both the Extrinsic and Intrinsic pathways. The Intrinsic cascade begins with platelets coming into contact with collagen and degranulating. The process of degranulation releases substances such as ADP, serotonin, thromboxane ect. These substances attract more platelets to the area of injury. The intrinsic pathway realise on the activation of factor XII (Hageman factor). The extrinsic pathway realise on Tissue Factor secreted by the smooth muscle cells (which are normally separated from the blood by a layer of simple squamous endothelium. The tissue factor combines with factor VII (Proconvertin or autoprothrombin I) and proteases activating VII via proteolytic cleavage of a single peptide bond. This VIIa then activates X (autoprothrombin III) which is the start product (after the addition of Ca++) of the Final Common pathway.

Question: A 4 month pregnant women turns up to the GP with an infection. The doctor explains to her about the antibodies her body is making to protect the fetus. Which immunoglobuline molecule is more likely to be mentioned ?
Explanation: IgG antibody is the one that travels from the mothers blood supply into the fetus to protect it in case of an infection.

Question: As a junior Dr you see a female patient in A &E she is 63 and moved to the UK from Nigeria with her family a few years ago. She is a muslim and dresses very modestly. She has had a fall and fractured her wrist. What vitamin deficiency would you check for and what how would that deficiency contribute to her symptoms?
OptionB: Vitamin C, needed for maintaining healthy connective tissue
OptionC: Vitamin D, deficiency can lead to osteoporosis.
Explanation:
NHS choices says there is evidence to suggest too much Vitamin A can contribute to osteoporosis (not too little). Vitamin C does help keep connective tissue healthy, but the information provided doesn't suggest vitamin C deficiency as strongly as it suggests vitamin D.

 

Most of our vitamin D is produced in our body and its synthesis requires certain wavelengths of UV light. This patient from Nigeria is likely to have dark skin and if her skin is also always well covered due to modest dress she will not receive enough sunlight to synthesise enough vitamin D. Vitamin D deficiency can lead to osteoporosis, the patients age (at 63 she is probably postmenopausal) and sex also predispose her to osteoporosis.

Question: What is the root innervation of the Pectoralis Minor?
Explanation: The corresponding muscles are A-Serratus Anterior, B-Pectoralis Minor, C-Pectoralis Major, D-Latissimus Dorsi and E-Diaphragm/heart

Question: Which out of these five words listed is not used to describe a group of axillary nodes?
Explanation: See e learning on the upper limb. The five groups are humeral, pectoral, subscapular, central and apical

Question: What is the innervation of the axillary nerve?
Explanation: The spinal roots of the axillary nerve are C5 and C6

Question: A patient is taken into A and E complaining of severe discomfort, showing acute signs of tremors, hyper salvation and parenthesia of the lips, with cyanosis. You find out that he/she was at a famous Japanese restaurant just less than an hour ago, has no chronic outstanding illnesses, was previously fit and healthy and you also can see that the patient is entering the early signs of respiratory distress. What is the most likely diagnosis, given the circumstances?
Explanation: Flax Poisoning usually is caused by skin exposure to the plant and skin irritations are characteristics unnoticed by the patient. A myocardial infarction is unlikely to cause parenthesia of the lips, as is MS which is linked to genetic/environmental factors not described in the text. Cyanide poisoning if acute usually kills very quickly while the history fits the case that the patient is likely suffering from pufferfish poisoning that usually causes lip parenthesia and decline in bodily function.

Question: What is the phase of reduced excitability called after an action potential has passed, in which a stronger stimulus than normal is required to elicit another action potential?
Explanation:
The absolute refractory period is the interval of 0.5-1.0ms following an action potential in which it is impossible to elicit a second action potential.

Whereas, the relative refractory period follows the absolute refractory period and lasts around 5ms. In this time frame, it is possible to elicit a second action potential if the stimulus is stronger than normal.

Question: A patient comes into the clinic complaining of night blindness. It is revealed that he is a vegetarian and eats excessive amounts of nuts as a source of protein. Nuts are a excellent source of vitamin E. The consultant suggests that this is the most likely cause of his night blindness. Why?
OptionA: Vitamin A absorption has been inhibited by excessive vitamin E in his system.
OptionB: Vitamin B5 absorption has been inhibited by excessive vitamin E in his system.
OptionC: Vitamin B12 absorption has been inhibited by excessive vitamin E in his system.
OptionD: Vitamin K absorption has been inhibited by excessive vitamin E in his system.
OptionE: Vitamin D absorption has been inhibited by excessive vitamin E in his system.
Explanation:
vitamin A absorption can be reduced by excess vitamin E consumption.

Retinol is how Vitamin A is transported around the body.

Many of the cells in the retina are “rods” or “cones”. Circulating retinol-retinol binding protein complex is required in the formation of rhodopsin (which is cis-retinal bound to the vision protein opsin), a membrane protein of the rod cell photoreceptors in the retina. In response to light energy the cis-retinal in rhodopsin is converted to trans-retinal; the altered shape of the molecule triggers a nerve impulse from the retina
which is perceived as light in black and white vision. Cone cells, in contrast, are important for colour vision and for bright light vision; they contain retinal-based chromophores that respond to specific wavelengths of light. The immediate time after seeing a flash of bright light involves a period of active rhodopsin synthesis and requires a relatively high level of vitamin A in the retina. “Night blindness” is one of the first detectable signs of vitamin A deficiency. In this condition the blood supplying rod cells contains insufficient cis-retinal to rapidly replace the trans-retinal formed after exposure to bright light and the resulting condition is called night blindness. If unchecked, the next stage in this process is xeropthalmia, which occurs when the soft, lubricated membrane of the eye transforms into a dry, keratinised epithelium. Xeropthalmia results in total blindness and while this condition is not found in the UK population, it is a common cause of blindness in developing countries, particularly amongst children

Question: Winston, a 67-year old patient presents at his GP surgery complaining of regurgitation and heart burn. His BMI is 33 and he has pain whilst swallowing (odynophagia). Winston has a diet high in saturated fat and smokes 35 cigarettes a day. Based on the information above, what is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) is a condition where acid from the stomach leaks out into the oesophagus. If the lower oesophageal sphincter (LOS) remains relaxed for long periods or if the abdominal pressure exceeds that in the thorax, the stomach contents may enter the oesophagus. The LOS is a ring of muscle towards the bottom of the oesophagus which acts as a valve, remaining closed when food is not being swallowed and opening to permit entry of the bolus (food ball) into the stomach.

Treatments for GORD include lifestyle advice, antacids such as sodium bicarbonate (neutralise the acidic chyme) and drugs such as ranitidine and omeprazole, that inhibit gastric acid secretion.

Risk factors for GORD include being overweight or obese, eating large amounts of fatty foods, being pregnant and having a hiatus hernia

Question: Winston, a 67-year old patient recently diagnosed with severe gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) was found to have a hiatus hernia. What are the two types of hiatus hernia?
Explanation:
hiatus hernia - condition in which the proximal region of the stomach herniates through the opening in the diaphragm through which the oesophagus passes intro the thoracic cavity (the oesophageal hiatus)

Sliding hiatus hernia - the gastro-oesophageal junction slides up into the thoracic cavity (80% of cases)

Rolling hiatus hernia - the gastro-oesophageal junction remains in place but a part of the stomach herniates into the chest next to the oesophagus (20% of cases).

Question: A 19 year old student is admitted into the A&E with a chest wound. The doctor informs him he has a torn thoracic duct and lymph enters the pleural cavity. What medical condition is likely to be mentioned by the doctor?
Explanation: Chyle is a pale white or yellow lymph fluid in the thoracic duct containing fat absorbed by the intestines.

Question: When Ca++ levels in blood plasma decrease a hormone is released. This hormone stimulates Intestinal reabsorption of Ca++, prevents Ca++ excretion in the Kidneys and increases bone absorption and freeing of Ca++ by osteoclasts in bone. What is this Hormone?
Explanation: PTA stimulates bone reabsorption and decreases calcium excretion directly. It also increases 1,25 - dihydroxycholecalciferal (The activated from of Vitamin D) concentration in the blood which increases uptake of Ca++ in the small intestine.

Question: A 22 year old student had a motorcycle accident and landed on his shoulder. When admitted to the A&I he hears the doctors referring to the position of his limb as a "waiter's tip position". Which nerves of the brachial plexus are injured?
Explanation: Injuries to the superior parts of the brachial plexus (C5 and C6) usually result from an excessive increase in the angle between the neck and the shoulder. These injuries can occur in a person thrown from a motorcycle or a horse. The "waiter's tip position" represents a position in which the limb hangs by the side in medial rotation.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb, Nervous system

Question: The ligamentum arteriosum is a remnant of the fetal ductus arteriosum. What structures does it connect to ?
OptionA: Right pulmonary artery and the thoracic aorta
OptionB: Brachiocephalic trunk and the arch of the aorta
OptionC: Left pulmonary artery and the arch of the aorta
OptionD: Left common carotid artery and the left subclavian artery
Explanation: The ligamentum arteriosum passes from the root of the left pulmonary artery to the inferior surface of the arch of the aorta.

Question: A rugby player is admitted into the A&E with a fracture at the medial epicondyle of the humerus. What is the most likely nerve to be damaged ?
Explanation: The ulnar nerve passes posteriorly to the medial epicondyle.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question:
During a ward round shadowing a gastroenterolgy consultant you meet Stanley, a 55 year old patient suffering from Barrett's oesophagus. The consultant explains that he successfully diagnosed Stanley by upper GI endoscopy. He performed a biopsy with the endoscope and sent the sample to the pathology lab where Professor Dave Wilson determined that Barrett's oesophagus cells were present.

What was the change in cell type that Dave observed?
OptionA: stratified squamous epithelium to simple squamous epithelium
OptionB: simple columnar epithelium to a gastric type of glandular epithelium
OptionC: simple squamous epithelium to a gastric type of glandular epithelium
OptionD: stratified squamous epithelium to a gastric type of glandular epithelium
OptionE: pseudostratified columnar epithelium to a gastric type of glandular epithelium
Explanation:
The oesophagus is lined by non-keratinizing stratified squamous epithelium. The average epithelial thickness is 500-800 micro metres but this is difficult to measure because the lower border is irregular. The function of the epithelial lining of the upper respiratory tract is to moisten the passing inhaled air and to remove any inhaled particulates. 

Barrett's oesophagus is a condition where the constant reflux of acid gastric secretions occurs in the lower oesophagus causing inflammation and pain. Over time the stratified squamous epithelium changes form to a gastric type of glandular epithelium. This replacement of one differentiated cell type with another is an example of metaplasia.

Question: Charlotte, a 30 year old patient with aplastic anaemia (a severe form of anaemia where stem cells cannot generate mature blood cells) prevents at her local GP surgery with joint pain, abdominal pain and a grey skin colour. She complains of feeling tired all the time and says she has been losing weight although her diet and exercise routines have not changed. Charlotte has frequent blood transfusions to manage her anaemia. What condition is she most likely to be suffering with?
Explanation:
Haemochromatosis is the build up of iron in the body leading to iron overload. The excess iron is harmful because it deposits in tissues and organs which can lead to liver and heart failure.

Primary haemochromatosis is caused by inherited genetic defects. Haemochromatosis that is not inherited is called secondary and is most common in people with severe anaemia who have frequent blood transfusions.

Question: Wendy, a 32 year old mother of three presents at her GP surgery with fecal incontinence. She recently gave birth to her third child, weighing 9lb 4oz, and explains that the problem only started after the birth. The GP informs Wendy that she has most likely suffered nerve or muscle injury because of the delivery of a large baby. What muscle/muscles is he most likely to mention she has damaged?
Explanation:
The rectum opens to the exterior via the anal canal, which has both external and internal sphincters. The internal sphincter is not under voluntary control and is supplied by both parasympathetic and sympathetic nerves. The external anal sphincter is composed of skeletal muscle and is supplied by the pudenal nerve and is under voluntary learned control. The anal sphincter muscles won't open properly and close properly if the nerves that control them are damaged. 

Rectal sphincter muscles and colon sphincter muscles don't exist. The pyloric sphincter separates the stomach from the duodenum.

Question:
Brandon, a 21 year old patient is seen by his family practitioner because of constipation, nausea and itching around the anus. He explains that whilst at university he struggles to eat a balanced diet and often resorts to ready meals and Domino's pizza after a night out. The GP examines the anus visually and performs a digital rectal examination when he discovers the presence of haemorrhoids. 

What dietary advice is the GP likely to give Brandon to help alleviate his symptoms?
Explanation:
Humans are unable to digest dietary fibre so it remains in the intestine, adding bulk to food residues. The fibre exerts a hygroscopic effect, absorbing water so that stools with a high fibre content tend to be bulkier and softer making them easier to expel. Dietary fibre consists largely of indigestible cellulose. Good sources of dietary fibre are fruit and vegetables and wholegrain cereals.

Haemorroids (commonly known as piles) are swollen blood vessels in or around the anus and rectum. They are very common in elderly people and during pregnancy.

Dietary fibre has a pivotal role in preventing haemorrhoids and is very important to the passage of food through the large intestine. A shorter mouth-to-anus transit time is believed to reduce the risk of developing carcinoma of the large intestine and rectum. It reduces the time bacterial toxins and potential harmful metabolites are in contact with the gut wall.

Human Physiology, Pocock and Richards, p620

Question: 12 year old Harriet has been admitted to the paediatric ward for planned surgery to remove her appendix. The surgeon suspects she has appendicitis because she has complained of constant and severe pain in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen and has a temperature of 38.5C. During the laparoscopic appendectomy, the surgeon points to to a structure to which the appendix attaches and asks you to identify it. What part of the large intestine is the surgeon pointing to?
Explanation:
The appendix extends from the posteromedial aspect of the caecum inferior to the ileocecal junction. 

Essential Clinical Anatomy p156

Question: A doctor has to prescribe a drug which requires to decrease an intracellular concentration of a product formed inside the cell. Which is the most likely type of enzyme inhibitor the drug will use ?
Explanation: If the requirement is to decrease the intracellular concentration of the product, then the inhibitor must be non-competitive. Increasing the concentration of substrate does not affect a non-competitive inhibitor. However, if it was a competitive inhibitor as unused substrate accumulates it will compete with a competitive inhibitor, and the final result will be a more or less normal rate of formation of product, but with a larger pool of substrate.

Question: It is currently common practice to provide women with folate supplements during pregnancy and is suggested that supplements should be taken during the preconception.  This is to reduce the risk of the infant developing what?
Explanation: Medical Physiology Fourth Edition Page 134

Question: Where does the foregut region end, if it begins from the oesophagus?
Explanation: The foregut from the oesophagus to the 2nd part of the duodenum

Question: Which of these parts is not part of the Midgut of the GI tract?
OptionE: The proximal two thirds of the transverse colon
Explanation: The descending colon is part of the hindgut

Question: Where in the GI tract is the Vitamin B12/IF complex absorbed by endocytosis?
Explanation: See Pocock 616-Cubulin recognises this complex and it is absorbed in the lower part of the ileum by endocytosis via enterocytes.

Question: During delivery a baby's upper limb is pulled excessively and an injury to the brachial plexus occurs. The doctor refers to it as Klumpke paralysis. What are the roots more likely to be damaged in this condition?
Explanation: During delivery a baby's upper limb is pulled excessively and an injury to the inferior part of the brachial plexus occurs at the C8 and T1 roots levels. This condition is called Klumpke paralysis and because of the damage of the C8 and T1 roots the short muscles of the hand are also affected (claw hand).
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb, Nervous system

Question: Which ligament holds the liver to the inferior surface of the diaphragm?
Explanation: The coronary ligament holds the liver to the inferior surface of the diaphragm.

Question:
Gary, a 66 year old patient presents at his GP surgery with pain in the epigastric abdominal region directly below the sternum. He explains that the pain comes and goes but it occasionally gets worse after eating. He has recently lost his job and admits to feeling very anxious about how he will pay the bills and support his wife. The GP refers Gary to the hospital for an endoscopy and collects a stool sample to send off to the lab. 3 weeks later and the results from the stool sample confirm the presence of H.pylori bacterium. 

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation: Peptic ulcers are open lesions of the mucosa of the pyloric canal or the duodenum. People experiencing severe chronic anxiety are prone to developing peptic ulcers. Gastric acid secretion rates are higher between meals which overwhelms the bicarbonate normally produced by the duodenum and reduces the effectiveness of the mucous lining. The most common cause of ulcers is infection of the stomach by Helicobacter pylori. Helicobacter pylori are bacteria that erode the protective mucous lining of the stomach and make it more vulnerable to the effects of gastric acid and pepsin produced by the stomach. Epithelial cells and the lamina propria (thin layer of loose connective tissue that lies beneath the epithelium and together with the epithelium constitutes the mucosa) die leading to the formation of a shallow ulcer.

Question: In healthy individuals, where in the GI tract is trypsinogen converted to trypsin ?
Explanation: Trypsinogen is activated by the brush border enzymes and converted into trypsin in the duodenum. In people who have pancreatitis, trypsinogen is activated inside the acini cell.

Question: A 52 year old man presents to the GP with various symptoms including pain, difficulty walking and mental confusion/speech difficulties. The doctor thinks the patient has the Beriberi disease. What vitamin deficiency causes this disease?
Explanation: Beriberi is a disease in which the body does not have enough thiamine (vitamin B1).

Question: After a hard night on the town consuming an excessive number of vodka shots,19 year old Jason started to head home to his student residences when unfortunately he began to experience feelings of nausea. This was shortly followed by retching and the autonomic responses of copious watery salivation (waterbrash), sweating, dizziness and tachycardia (heart rate that exceeds the normal range). He quickly crouched behind a bin and vomited the contents of his stomach and duodenum onto the pavement. Luckily for Jason his vomiting reflex had kicked in to prevent the inhalation of his vomitus (vomited material). What area of the brain coordinates the vomiting (emesis) reflex?
Explanation:
Vomiting consists of three stages: Nausea, Retching, Vomiting

Vomiting is thought to have evolved as a defensive mechanism whereby potentially toxic substances are removed from the body.

Afferent neuron (neurons carrying signals TOWARDS the CNS) impulses arrive at the brain stem from many parts of the body including the pharynx and other areas of the GI tract.There are two medullary centres of vomiting in the brain known as the sensory chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) and the integrative vomiting centre.The integrative vomiting centre is activated by afferent impulses from around the body resulting in a reflexive activation. 

The CTZ  is sensitive to a variety of chemical agents including general anaesthetics and opiates. When activated the CTZ relays stimuli to the integrative vomiting centre which produces the actual act of emesis. 

The motor impulses responsible for the action of vomiting are transmitted from the medulla via the trigeminal, facia, glossopharyngeal, vagus and hypoglossal nerves.

During the act of vomiting the larynx is closed and the soft palate rises to close off the nasopharynx which prevents inhalation of vomited material. The stomach and pyloric sphincter relax, the duodenum contracts which forces the intestinal contents into the stomach. The diaphragm and abdominal wall then contract, lower oesophageal sphincter relaxes and the pylorus closes. This causes a rise in intragastric pressure leading to the expulsion of the gastric contents.

Question: During your rotation on the gastroenterology ward you are asked to examine 51 year old Arthur, a patient suffering from cirrhosis of the liver. Arthur has severe ascites (an accumulation of fluid) causing visible abdominal distention. In what space has this fluid accumulated?
Explanation: The space between the visceral and parietal layers of the peritoneum (the peritoneal cavity) normally contains very little free fluid but in certain diseases like cirrhosis of the liver, this space may become expanded by an abnormal accumulation of fluid.

Question: During the enzyme practical a student has to draw 2 double reciprocal plots: the first one represents a normal enzyme activity and the second one shows the enzyme activity with a competitive inhibitor. What will the student notice when he compares the two graphs?
OptionB: An apparent increase in Vmax in the second graph.
OptionC: An apparent increase in Km in the second graph.
OptionD: An apparent decrease in Km in the second graph.
OptionE: An apparent decrease in Vmax in the second graph.
Explanation: When a competitive inhibitor is added the slope of the graph increases while the Y-intercept stays the same. Hence, there will be an apparent increase in Km but no effect on Vmax.

Question: What range % of cardiac output usually supplies the kidneys in a normal adult human?
Explanation: The textbooks and web articles will give a range roughly between these two values; the question was part of one of the e-learning documents.

Question: A man walks into A & E complaining of diffuse and colicky abdominal pain around the umbilicus area of the abdomen. After a few hours, the pain becomes more constant in the right iliac fossa and the patient is recommended to undergo surgery. What condition is likely he/she suffering from?
Explanation: The patient's first pain experiences is a type of referred pain as the visceral sensory fibres are stimulated due to inflammation of the appendix,  and enter the spinal cord at T10, the umbilicus region. This pain is colic and later when the appendix makes contact with and irritates the parietal peritoneum in the right iliac fossa, which is innervated by somatic sensory nerves. This produces a more prominent constant focal pain. Disorders of the bowel or pelvis may cause similar symptoms.

Question: A 43 year old woman goes to the supermarket and selects her food according to the NHS "eatwell plate". What is the minimum number of portions for oily fish/per week recommended by the NHS guidelines ?
OptionC: Oily fish is not recommended by the NHS
Explanation: NHS guidelines recommends a minimum of 2 portions of oily fish per week. Salmon, mackerel, sardines, trout and herring are all examples of oily fish. This type of fish is high in long-chain omega-3 fatty acids, which may help prevent heart disease, and also a good source of vitamin D.

Question: A rugby player experiences a painful shoulder injury resulting from what appears to be excessive extension of the humerus from scoring a try. An x-ray reveals that the injury is indeed an anterior dislocation of the glenohumeral joint, but the patient begins to suffer shoulder muscle wastage weeks after the injury, with extreme weakness abducting the arm and experiences loss of sensation in the regimental band area of the shoulder. Which nerve has the patient most likely damaged and thus which muscle is most likely suffering from extreme muscle wastage and reducing the player's shoulder strength?
Explanation: A  glenohumeral dislocation is most likely to damage the axillary nerve, and can cause paralysis of the deltoid, loss of cutaneous sensation in the regimental badge area and severe weakness in the abduction of the arm, which past 15 degrees, is performed by the deltoid, a muscle innervated by axillary nerve. The patient's initial 15 degree abduction, performed by the supraspinatus, would be more likely unaffected.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: Which of these is true about the cubital fossa for most humans?
OptionA: The radial nerve is the only nerve to pass through it
OptionB: The brachial artery continues after the fossa to bifurcate into two separate vessels in the mid-part of the radial shaft
OptionC: The cubital fossa is not often used for venepuncture
OptionD: The brachial artery bifurcates in the fossa into two separate vessels
OptionE: It is formed with the medial border of the pronator teres muscle as the lateral border of the fossa and lateral brachioradialis muscle as the medial border if the fossa
Explanation:
A-Both the radial and median nerve pass through the fossa

B-See D

C-The cubital fossa is a common site for venepuncture

D-In most people, the brachial artery bifurcates into the radial and ulnar arteries

E-Other way round-It is formed with the lateral border of the pronator teres muscle as the medial border of the fossa and medial brachioradialis muscle as the lateral border of the fossa
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: A woman comes in to the surgery complaining of breathlessness and reduced cognitive ability. It is revealed through testing that she is vitamin B12 deficient despite the fact she eats a balanced diet and takes vitamin supplements. The consultant sends off for some genetic testing due to a family history of dementia and anaemia. The results show that she has a nonsense mutation in the coding strand of one of the exons which code for the protein that protects dietary vitamin B12 from high p.H as it travels through the stomach. What is the name of the protein that is defective?
What type of Connective Tissue is found in Tendons and Ligaments?
Explanation: In this type of connective tissue, collagen fibres are densely packed and arranged in parallel. This type of tissue is found in ligaments (which link bone to bone at joints) and tendons (connections between bones or cartilage and muscle). This tissue can withstand high tension and forces and is able to stretch a little. Hyaline Cartilage and Fibrocartilage are types of cartilage, a specialised connective tissue surrounding the surfaces of bones.

Question: Which of these is not one of the sections of the duodenum?
Explanation: The 4 sections are, in order of pyloric end to jejunal end, superior, descending, inferior and ascending.

Question: In the Central Nervous System, axons are insulated by myelin sheaths formed by....??
Explanation: Myelin is formed by oligodendrocytes in the CNS and by Schwann Cells in the PNS

Question: Megan is 8 years old. Her mum has taken her to see the GP because recently she has started wetting the bed, something she hasn't done since she was very young. She is always thirsty, complains of being tired all the time, and is underweight. What autoimmune condition might she have and why does this cause lethargy, and weight loss?
OptionA: Type 2 diabetes, glucose is excreted in urine so there is never enough energy available.
OptionB: Coeliac disease, poor absorption of food and lack of iron means patients become underweight and lethargic
OptionD: Type 1 diabetes, lack of insulin means she cannot take up and conserve glucose derived from the products of digestion.
Explanation:
Megan's increased need to drink and pee combined with her other symptoms suggests she might have type 1 diabetes, this means her body cannot make insulin. Without insulin her body is unable to take glucose up from the blood, this means her tissues (importantly her liver) cannot absorb glucose after a meal so cannot store energy. This leads to weight loss as glucose can't be taken up and stored as fat, and amino acids are used as an alternative fuel source reducing muscle mass. Lethargy occurs as her energy stores are depleted.

 

She is unlikely to have type 2 diabetes due to her age, and excretion of glucose in urine is a result of uncorrected high blood glucose not cause for low blood sugar and energy.

 

Coeliac disease and hypothyroidism do not usually cause excess urination.

Question: A patient is told, after suffering a humeral shaft fracture, that there radial nerve is severely damaged, with the diagnosing doctor asking the observing medical students to explain to the curious patient which spinal dermatomes are effected. What are the root innervations of the radial nerve?
Explanation: Though the radial nerve is part of the posterior cord, it receives, via the interconnections at the divisions rage of the brachial plexus, innervation from the superior, middle and inferior trunks, thus receiving all roots of the brachial plexus.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: Which of these is false about the brachial artery?
OptionA: It lies medial to the biceps tendon
OptionB: It commences at the lower border of teres major
OptionC: It can be palpated through most of its course
OptionD: It branches into the radial and ulnar arteries in the forearm
OptionE: It lies lateral to the cephalic vein
Explanation: The artery lies medial to the cephalic vein in the upper arm
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: What causes the separation of charge across a cell membrane, thus creating an electrical force?
Explanation: The electrical potential is also know as the membrane potential and is caused by the different distributions of ions across the cell membrane e.g. during resting state, the inside of the cell is said to be more negative compared to the outside due to the action of the Na+/K+ pump, the slight permeability of the membrane to K+ ions and the large organic anions present in the cell cytoplasm.

Question: In an average adult human, how many generations of bronchi does one have making up their conducting zone in their respiratory system?
Explanation: The first 16 generations make up the conducting zone (from the primary bronchus to the terminal bronchioles), while generations 17 to 23 (respiratory bronchioles to the alveolar sacs) make up the transitional and respiratory zones in an average person.

Question: What is the difference between the anatomical and the physiological dead space?
OptionB: Anatomical refers to the air breathed in that does not mix with air in the alveoli, physiological refers to the air breathed in that does not take part in gas exchange
OptionC: Anatomical refers to the air breathed in that does not take part in gas exchange, physiological refers to the air breathed in that does not mix with air in the alveoli
OptionD: Anatomical refers to the air breathed in that does mix with air in alveoli, physiological refers to the air breathed in that does not take part in gas exchange
OptionE: Anatomical refers to the air breathed in that does take part in gas exchange, physiological refers to the air breathed in that does mix with air in the alveoli
Explanation: B is the correct answer and the terms are referenced in Pocock Page 429; the key difference is that anatomical refers to the alveoli where as physiological refers to gas exchange

Question: What are the three cell shapes found in epithelial tissue?
Explanation:
epithelial cells are classified into three main cell groups according to their shape

these groups are squamous, cuboidal, columnar

Human Histology p37

Question: What epithelial cell type functions as a mediator of filtration and diffusion?
Explanation:
only one cell thick so allows for movement of small molecules, oxygen and carbon dioxide can diffuse freely across the epithelia, ions utilise protein channels to move across the cell

simple squamous epithelium is found in locations where rapid diffusion or filtration takes place. In the kidney, simple squamous epithelium lines the Bowman’s capsule and the glomerulus.

simple squamous epithelium also makes up the alveoli in the lungs, where rapid gas exchange occurs, as oxygen enters the bloodstream through alveolar blood vessels and carbon dioxide exits as waste.

Question: Mr Griffiths has a lower motor neurone lesion and has come to visit his neurologist for a review of his symptoms. The consultant neurologist says you (a medical student) sit in on the consultation, at the start of the consultation he asks you to name the main symptoms associated with lower motor neurone lesions.
OptionA: Spasticity, focal weakness, fascilculations, muscle wasting, exaggerated reflexes, absent plantar reflex
OptionB: Flaccid focal weakness, fasciculations, muscle wasting, weak or absent reflexes, absent or normal plantar reflex.
OptionC: Spastic pyramidal weakness, absence of fasciculations, no muscle wasting, exaggerated reflexes, toes point up in plantar reflex
OptionD: Flaccid pyramidal weakness, fasciculations, muscle wasting, absence of reflexes, toes go up in plantar reflex
OptionE: Spastic focal weakness, absence of fasciculations, no muscle wasting, absence of reflexes, absence of plantar reflex
Explanation:
Lesions in upper motor neurone symptoms:

- high muscle tone (spasticity)

- pyramidal pattern of weakness

- lack of fasciculations

- no muscle wasting

- exaggerated reflexes

- abnormal plantar reflex (toes point up instead of down)

 

Lower motor neurone lesion symptoms:

- loss of muscle tone (flaccidity)

- focal pattern of weakness (often starting at the peripharies)

- fasciculations

- muscle wasting

 - weak or absent reflexes

- absent or normal plantar reflex

Question: Which set of complement pathway factors are ALL anaphylatoxins?
Explanation: C3 convertase converts C3 to C3a and C3b; C3a, along with C4a and C5a forms the inflammatory response, while C3b binds to and coats pathogens, making them easier for phagocytes to identify and ingest. This process is called opsonisation. C3b also binds to immune complexes to facilitate their removal by the spleen, and triggers the production of terminal components for the MAC response.

Question: What type of structure does IgA have?
Explanation:
IgM-Pentameric

IgA-Dimeric

IgG, IgD, IgE-Monomeric

Question: Where does the coracobrachialis originate from?
Explanation: CORACObrachialis originates from the CORACOid process as the name of the muscle suggests
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: The biceps brachii muscle flexes the elbow and the shoulder. What other action does it complete?
Explanation: Biceps brachii is a flexor and also supinates the forearm
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: What is calculated using the Nernst Equation?
Which pathway involves the initiation of complement proteins by antibodies?
Explanation: The Classical Pathway is activated by antibody-antigen complexes on pathogen surfaces, Lectin Pathway is activated by Lectin binding to a carbohydrate molecule (Mannose) on pathogen surfaces and Alternative Pathway is activated by C3 reacting directly with pathogen surfaces and all of these pathways converge to produce C3 convertase.

Question: Which enzyme is responsible for catalysing the link reaction?
Explanation: Pyruvate dehydrogenase catalyses the link reaction, which is the conversion of pyruvate to acetyl CoA.

Question: Identify the tissue type
Explanation:
squamous epithelial cells are arranged in layers upon a basement membrane, only one layer is in contact with the basement membrane the other layers adhere to each other 

this image shows non-keratinised stratified squamous epithelium which would be found in the oesophagus, anal canal, vagina, cornea and oral cavity

Question: Identify the INCORRECT statement
OptionA: epithelia are classified by the number of cell layers
OptionB: only stratified epithelia contain two or more rows of cell nuclei
OptionC: microvilli increase the surface area of the epithelial cells
Explanation: pseudostratified epithelium can also contain two or more rows of cell nuclei, but all cells are in contact with the basement membrane

Question: Identify the CORRECT statement
OptionA: epithelia are classified by the shape of the cells in the basal cell layer
OptionC: there are five major classes of simple epithelia
OptionD: epithelia are classified by the number of cell layers
OptionE: pseudostratified epithelia can be found almost exclusively in the bladder
Explanation:
epithelia are avascular and innervated

there are FOUR major classes of simple epithelia: squamous, cuboidal, columnar, pseudostratified

pseudostratified epithelia are found almost exclusively in the larger respiratory airways: nasal cavity, trachea, bronchi etc
