Question: ATP synthase exists in the matrix side of the inner mitochondrial membrane. It consists of two parts; F1 and F0. F1 consists of a 'Binding change mechanism' for the synthesis of ATP. This has 3 aB subunits and one central y unit. y must rotate x degrees in order to reject an ATP, synthesise an ATP and bind an ADP and Pi. What is x?
Explanation: the central y unit must rotate 120 degrees in order to do all of the above. The energy from the proton-motive free energy is not used to synthesise ATP from ADP and Pi but it is used for its release into the matrix.

Question: Which of these cranial nerves contains only motor fibers?
Explanation:
The Abducens nerve (VI) provides only motor innervation to the lateral rectus muscle of the eyeball; this muscle brings the pupil away from the midline of the body. This and CN IV, CN XI and CN XII are the only cranial nerves that have only motor fibres

A-Only sensory fibres; this, CN II and CN VIII are the only cranial nerves that provide only sensory fibres

B-Only sensory fibres to the cochlea and vestibular apparatus

C-Moto, Sensory and Parasympathetic fibers 

D-Sensory and Motor fibers

Question: Which of the following aponeuroses makes up the rectus sheath?
OptionE: External Oblique, Internal Oblique and Transversalis Abdominis
Explanation: The aponeurotic rectus sheath encloses the two vertical abdominal muscles and is a layering of all three vertical muscles' aponeuroses.

Question: From which of the following does the cremasteric fascia arise from?
OptionE: External Oblique, Internal Oblique and Transversalis Fascia
Explanation:
Externa Spermatic Fascia-from External Oblique Muscle

Cremasteric Fascia-from Internal Oblique Muscle

Internal Spermatic Fascia-from Transversalis Fascia

Question: Which of the following is true about the ANS?
OptionA: The pre-ganglionic neurones are longer in the Parasympathetic System and Shorter in the sympathetic Nervous System when comparing.
OptionB: The pre-ganglionic neurones are longer in the Sympathetic System and Shorter in the Parasympathetic Nervous System when comparing
OptionC: The pre-ganglionic neurones in the Sympathetic System are the same length as those in the Parasympathetic Nervous System when comparing
OptionD: Only the Parasympathetic NS has Nicotinic Receptors
OptionE: The sympathetic Nervous system always has Noradrenaline as the Post-ganglionic neurotransmitter
Explanation: A is the only correct one out of the first three; both the sympathetic and parasympathetic system have nicotinic receptors at the beginning of their post-ganglionic neurone, while though Noradrenaline is mostly used as the neurotransmitter, acetylcholine is used in some exceptions such as sweat glands.

Question:
Which muscle has the functions of extorsion ( external rotation), elevation and abduction? 

 

(Clue it is supplied by the occulomotor nerve)
Explanation:
Superior oblique -  intorts, depresses and abducts (supplied by Trochlear Nerve)

Superior rectus- intorts, elevates and adducts (Supplied by Occulomotor)

Inferior rectus- extorts, depresses and adducts (Supplied by occulomotor)

Question:
Lesions to the visual pathway can cause decreased vision in the eyes. The diagram above shows a bitemporal hemianopia. 

 

Where could the lesion have occured to cause this?
OptionC: In the midline of the optic chiasm
Explanation: If you compress the chiasm the fibers from the nasal side of the retina cross to the opposite optic tract. These fibers convey impulses from the temporal half of the image from both eyes. As shown above by the shaded area.

Question: Which hormone stimulates the secretion of pancreatic juice?
Explanation: All three hormones contribute to the secretion of pancreatic juice. Gastrin causes the pancreatic juice (along with bile) to be secreted into the duodenum. Secretin is secreted by S cells and stimulates duct cells to secrete bicarbonate-rich fluid. CCK is secreted by I cells and stimulates acinar cells to produce enzyme-rich secretion and potentiates the secretion of bicarbonate-rich fluid by duct cells. CCK's activity is enhanced by secretin

Question: At what vertebra level can the rectosigmoid junction be found?
Explanation: Found at vertebrae level S3 where the sigmoid colon becomes the rectum.

Question: Name which of the following is true about the arterial supply of the pancreas?
OptionD: Via the Coeliac trunk and Superior Mesenteric Artery
OptionE: Via the Superior Mesenteric and Inferior Mesenteric Arteries
Explanation: The Coeliac trunk provides branches via branches of the Splenic and Common Hepatic Arteries (most notably the gastroduodenal artery of the Common hepatic artery), while the superior mesenteric artery supplies a few pancreaticoduodenal arteries to the pancreas.

Question:
A 17-year-old female was cycling without a helmet when she fell and hit her head. In the
emergency room, she was not conscious and was receiving ventilator assistance. Her blood gases:
PO2 = 52 mm Hg,
PCO2 = 75 mm Hg, pH = 7.15, and
HCO3− = 31 mM

 

The majority of the CO2 was being transported as...?
Explanation:
The normal HCO3- concentration should be 20-25mM

The raised HCO3- suggests that additional CO2 was bound - also 70% of CO2 in the blood is transported by bicarbonate ions.

Question: How many connexins are needed to form a connexon?
Explanation: A connexon requires 6 connexin monomers to be formed and thus form a gap junction in one cell membrane.

Question: Which of these is not one of the locations of the preganglionic neurone cell bodies of the Parasympathetic Nervous System?
Explanation: The parasympathetic outflows from the CNS include the General Visceral Efferent Cranial Nuclei of CNs III, VII, IX and X, and Sacral spinal cord vertebra of S2 to S4.

Question: How many tastes are we able to detect?
Explanation: Sweet, Sour, Salt, Bitter and Umami-innervation via CN VII, CN IX and CNX

Question: Which of the following cranial nerves supplies the intrinsic muscles of the tongue?
Explanation: The intrinsic muscles of the tongue are innervated by the hypoglossal nerve-CN XII

Question: What taste(s) depend on the release of ion channels as opposed to activation of G protein secondary messenger cascade system?
Explanation: Salt depends on Na + channels, while sour depends on H+ channels; both ion channels cause depolarisation of tongue cells and neurotransmitter release. All the three others (bitter, sweet and umami) are activated by G protein secondary messenger systems.

Question: Which of these nerves does not originate from the superior trunk of the brachial plexus?
Explanation: All these nerves originate from the superior trunk, arising from C5 and C6, except for the Thoracodorsal nerve that originates from the middle trunk.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: What is the correct number of cervical vertebrae?
Explanation: There are 7 cervical vertebrae, 12 thoracic, 5 lumbar, 5 sacral and 3 to 4 coccygeal. Note that there are not 8 vertebrae;  when C8 is used as a root, it refers to spinal nerves arising from the space between C7 and T1 vertebrae.

Question: Which vertebrae have bifid spinous processes?
Explanation: Only the normal cervical vertebrae (C3 to C7) have bifid spinous processes.

Question: Where is the 'fossa ovalis' located?
Explanation: Fossa ovalis is a depression in the right atrium

Question:
A patient comes into the surgery and from his history you know he has poor renal function. He admits to have taken too many antiacid tablets. 

 

His blood PH is 7.5 (High)

The concentration of HCO3- in his blood is 30mM (High). 

 

You conclude his that he has metabolic alkalosis. How is his body likely compensate for this?
OptionB: Decreased excretion of HCO3- and an increase H+ secretion
OptionC: Decreased respiration so an increase in PCO2
Explanation:
C -  Metabolic alkosis is caused by a rise in plasma HCO3- because kidneys cannot remove the excess due to poor renal function. So the lungs compensate by decreasing respiration to raise PCO2 which will then form carbonic acid thus decreasing PH. 

 

A - occurs in metabolic acidosis 

 

B- occurs in Respiratory acidosis to remove hydrogen ions via the Na+H+ exchange int the proximal tubule.

Question: Ammonium ions are genereated from glutamine and secreted via the Na+/H+ exchanger in which part of the nephron?
Explanation: E - This is where 2/3 of filtrate is reabsorbed including sodium in exchange for NH4+ which will reduce the acidity of the blood plasma.

Question: What was the most supported explanation of the Black Report of 1980?
Explanation: E is made up and the others were all suggested explanation for the link between between class and disease. Materialist was the most supported, particularly by the Acheson Report of 1997. The materialist explanation revolves around socio-economic differences is society, such as poor housing, low income and poor employment conditions.

Question:
How confident is everyone feeling for the exams?

(5-very; 1-not at all)
Which cranial nerve contains both sensory and motor fibres?
Which Immunoglobulin(s) is dimeric?
Explanation: IgA is the only main dimeric immunoglobulin and is found in mucosal areas and is in salivary secretion, tears and breast milk. IgM is pentameric and the three others (D, E and G ) are monomeric.

Question: A patient appears in the surgery with chronic constipation. The doctor comments this May have occurred due to low fibre intake. What is the recommended intake of fibre each day?
Explanation: Straight from the lecture slides on nutrition, 18g is the RDA, the average intake is 12g

Question: Which rotator cuff muscle has the main action of lateral rotation and is supplied by the Axillary nerve?
Explanation:
A- medial rotation and adduction. Suprascapular nerve

B -  Initiates abduction. Suprascapular nerve

D - NOT IN ROTATOR CUFF

E -  lateral rotation but supplied by SUPRASCAPULAR NERVE

Question: What complement pathway is activated by antigen antibody complex?
Explanation:
Lectin is activated when a MBL binds to mannose a bacterium. 

Alternative is a spontaneous C3 hydrolysis into the formation of C3b

Question: What did people revise for the mocks?
Which of the following is the long arm of the chromosome?
Explanation: P arm is the short arm and Q arm is the long arm; the others are made up

Question: What is the correct karotype for a female individual with Turner's Syndrome?
Explanation:
C-Monosomy X- Turner's Syndrome

A-Trisomy 21-Down's Syndrome

B-deletion of 5p arm-Cri du Chat Syndrome

D-Normal Female

E-Triploid Female

Question: You encounter a wounded patient who has experienced a brutal anterior dislocation of the glenohumeral joint. You see a more senior doctor take care of the patient and are told that the patient has damaged a major upper limb nerve. Given the injury, which nerve is this likely to be?
Explanation: Due to traction, a glenohumeral dislocation is most likely to damage the axillary nerve and prevent abduction of the arm above 15 degrees. A humeral fracture will most likely damage the radial nerve.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: Matthew is complaining of breathlessness and a dull ache in the right chest region. He is sent for further testing by his GP, including an X-ray. What do the below results suggest that Matthew may have?
Explanation:
Pulmonary Effusion - made up

Subdural Effusion - affecting the subdural space

Cerebral Oedema - affecting the brain

Macular Oedema - affecting the eyes

 

Plural Effusion - a build-up of fluid between a lung and the chest wall. The X-ray indications: blunting of costophrenic angles and fluid level meniscus
Tags: Anatomy of Thorax, Lung function, Radiology

Question: Which of the statments below about the Glycemic index are INCORRECT?
OptionA: A Glycemic response for a particular food is the same for every person
OptionB: A high value suggest the food releases glucose rapidly into the blood.
OptionC: It is only used for foods containing carbohydrates
OptionD: A specific food's GI may vary with time (e.g changes in ripeness of fruit)
OptionE: It measures the relative ability of carbohydrates to increase blood glucose
Explanation:
Glycemic response varies between people due to differences in insulin production e.g diabetes

 

All the rest are correct

Question: Which hormone causes HCO3- ions to be secreted into the duodenum?
Explanation: Secretin causes HCO3- ions to be secreted when chyme is present in the duodenum. This lowers the acidic pH of the chyme.
Tags: Gastrointestinal System, Hormones, Physiology, hormonal control, Digestion

Question: From lateral to medial, what is the correct order of the superficial muscles of the forearm?
OptionA: Brachioradialis, Pronator Teres, Flexor Carpi Radialis, Palmaris Longus, Flexor Carpi Ulnas
OptionB: Brachioradialis, Flexor Carpi Radialis, Pronator Teres, Palmaris Longus, Flexor Carpi Ulnaris
OptionC: Brachioradialis, Flexor Carpi Radialis, Palmaris Longus, Pronator Teres, Flexor Carpi Ulnaris
OptionD: Brachioradialis, Palmaris Longus, Flexor Carpi Radialis, Pronator Teres, Flexor Carpi Ulnaris
OptionE: Brachioradialis, Palmaris Longus, Pronator Teres, Flexor Carpi Radialis, Flexor Carpi Ulnaris
Explanation: A is the correct order; the palmaris longus forms the palmar aponeurosis at its end while the pronator teres and brachioradialis making the borders of the cubital fossa.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: What muscle(s) forms the 2nd most superficial layer of the forearm?
OptionD: Flexor digitorum profundus and Flexor Pollicis Longus
Explanation: D makes up the third layer while Flexor digitorum superficialis is the 2nd layer, under brachioradialis, pronator teres, flexor carpi radialis, palmaris longus and flexor carpi ulnaris.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: What muscle(s) make up the 4th most superficial layer of the forearm?
OptionA: Flexor Pollicis Longus and Flexor Digitorum Profundus
Explanation: Part of the fibres of the Pronator teres muscle make up both the first and fourth layers of the forearm; the deep pronator quadratus, located distally in the arm, act to pronate the forearm and both make up the 4th layer.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: Which of the below are not Essential Fatty Acids ( must be ingested as we cannot synthesize ourselves)?
Explanation:
Linoleic Acid -  Omega 6

Alpha - Linolenic - Omega 3

Gammo Linolenic is also Omega 6 but it is conditionally essential under developmental or diseased conditions.

Question:
Hypoprothrombinoema is a bleeding disorder associated with the deficiency of a particular vitamin. 

 

Which vitamin is deficient in hypoprothrombinoema?
Explanation:
A - Night blindness

C- Scurvy

D - Rickets in children and Ostmalacia (Affects bone growth)

E Hemolytic anaemia the break down of Red Blood cell membranes 

 

K- is a vitamin needs for blood clotting hence a deficiency in vitamin K causes bleeding disorders.

Question: Which 3 immunoglobulins are classed as the MAJOR immunoglobulins?
Explanation: IgG, IgA and IgM are classed as the major immunoglobulins, making IgE and IgD minor immunoglobulins.

Question: What is the function(s) of basophils?
OptionC: Destroy parasites and participate in allergic reactions.
Explanation:
A - Neutrophils 

B - B Lymphocytes

C - Eosinophils

Question: What ion is ceruloplasmin a transport protein for?
Which of the following processes are NOT activated in a typical complement system response?
Explanation:
The complement system is triggered by one of 3 biochemical pathways (classical, alternative, or lectin) and leads to an amplification of the immune response which includes:

-Opsonization (increased phagocytosis of antigens)

-Chemotaxis (attraction of more neutrophils and macrophages)
-Cell Lysis (causation of cells to self destruct)

-Agglutination (binding of pathogens together to reduce their harmful effects)

Diapedesis is just when white blood cells move out of the circularatory system through a capillary wall to a site of infection (usually accompanies inflammation).

Question: Which of the following cranial nerves does not have a parasympathetic role?
Explanation: Only the oculomotor (CNIII), the facial (CNVII), the glossopharyngeal CN(IX) and the vagus (CNX) have parasympathetic fibres.

Question: Which one of these hormones is NOT produced in the anterior pituitary?
Explanation:
Growth Hormone, Prolactin, TSH (thyroid stimulating hormone), ACTH (adrencorticotropic hormone), MSH (melanocyte stimulating hormone), LH (lutenizing hormone) and FSH (follicle stimulating hormone) are all produced in the anterior pituitary.

Whereas Oxytocin and ADH (anti-diuretic hormone) are produced in the posterior pituitary.

Question: Which muscle forms the border between the urogenital triangle and the anal triangle?
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of pelvis and perineum

Question:
The hypothalamus receive sensory input from the environment. This then causes the release of a hormone(s) that travel to the anterior pituitary. These hormone(s) then stimulate the release of a hormone from the anterior pituitary.

 

Which hormones from the hypothalamus control the release of Growth Hormone in the anterior pituitary?
Explanation:
GHRH (growth hormone releasing hormone) stimulate the release of growth hormone.

Somatostatin inhibits the release of growth hormone in the anterior pituitary.

Dopamine stimulates the release of Prolactin.

GnRH (gonadotrophin releasing hormone) stimulates the release of LH and FSH.

Question: Which of these forms the inferior boundary of the Epiploic foramen?
Explanation:
The epiploic foramen, that connect the greater and lesser sacs, has boundaries of 

Superior-Caudate lobe of the Liver

Inferior-First part of the Duodenum

Anterior-Hepatoduodenal Ligament/Portal Triad

Posterior-Peritoneum of Inferior Vena Cava

Question:
This is a histological slide of thick skin.

How would you classify this epithelium??
Explanation:
Thick skin is stratified squamous keratinised epithelium as the skin come under a lot of biomechanics forces as it acts as a barrier to pathogens for our body and so must be strong.

Another telling point that this is keratinised epithelium is that the top cells (labeled S in this slide) have no nucleus.

Question: Which of the following cranial nerves contains ONLY sensory fibres?
Explanation:
Parasympathetic-CN III, VII, IX and X

Motor-CN III, IV, V, VI, VII, IX, X, XI and XII

Sensory-CN I, II, V, VII, VIII, IX and X

Question:
This is a histological slide of the trachea. 

How would you classify the epithelium here?

For extra, Identify A, B, C, D and the Red Arrow (answers will be in the explanation)
Explanation:
This is pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium. 

This question was on the extra web pages Dr. Wilson has put on learning central for us.

For reference:

A - Basal Cells

B - Cilia

C - Goblet Cell

D - Connective Tissue

Red Arrow - Basal bodies to which the cilia are bound

Question: What type of epithelium primarily lines the anus?
Explanation: The anus, along with the urethra, mouth and oesophagus among other things, is lined with mainly stratified squamous non keratinising epithelium.

Question: Which of the following is not a boundary of the quadrangular space?
Explanation:
For the quadrangular space, from which the posterior circumflex humeral vessels and axillary nerve emerge, the boundaries are

superior-Teres Minor

inferior-Teres Major

medial-long head of triceps

lateral-surgical neck of humerus
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb

Question: A chest X-ray of a patient with a pleural effusion is shown below. The fluid removed had a milky white appearance. Using this information, determine the most likely cause of this particular pleural effusion.
OptionA: a leak of serous fluid into the pleural cavity
OptionB: rupture of a serous membrane after a chest injury
Explanation:
A - hydrothorax, serous fluid is typically pale yellow or transparent and is secreted from serous glands, serous secretions are typically watery 

B - the rupture of a serous membrane causes blood to spill into the pleural space which is called a haemothorax

C - laceration of the thoracic duct would cause lymphatic fluid (chyle) to leak into the pleural cavity

D - urinothorax, rare case of pleural effusion

E - accumulation of fluid in pericardial space

 

chyle contains high levels of triglycerides which causes its milky white appearance

Question: Where can one find the fibrous pericardium and its contents?
Explanation: The fibrous pericardium is found in the inferior mediastinum, in its middle aspect (the middle mediastinum); the anterior lies in front and the posterior lies behind, covering the 8 thoracic vertebrae posteriorly.

Question: What is the wide number of neural fibres called, which connects the right and left hemispheres of the brain and facilitates communication between them?
Which of the following binds to vitamin B12 to protect it from attack by the low pH in gastric juice?
Explanation:
Haptocorrin is released in saliva and binds to B12 to protect from low pH

Transconalamin II binds B12 to allow it to be absorbed

 

The others do not contribute to vitamin B12 absorption

Question: Anteriorly between which vertebrae will you find the cisternae chyli?
Explanation: The thoracic duct begins at the upper end of the cisternae chyli, located anteriorly to the space between the first and 2nd lumbar vertebrae. The thoracic duct arises from the upper cisternae chyli, closer to the L1/ T12 level.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of Abdomen, Anatomy of Thorax

Question: Where are Peyer's Patches typically found?
OptionC: In the sinusoidal capillaries of the liver
OptionD: In the terminal part of the Ileum
Explanation: Peyer's patches, aggregates of lymphoid follicles containing lymphoid cells, are found mainly in the final part of the ileum before it reaches the ileocecal junction. These patches primarily secrete IgA to stop the absorption of foreign antibodies among other things.

Question: Which of the following cranial nerves does not pass through the jugular foramen?
Explanation: Cranial nerves XI to XI pass through the jugular foramen with the internal jugular vein and the inferior petrosal sinus.

Question: What nerve, from the following, passes through the internal acoustic meatus?
Explanation:
A-Olfactory foramen in cribiform plate of ethmoid bone

B-Optic canal with Ophthalmic artery

C-Superior Orbital fissure with Oculomotor nerve, Trochlear nerve and Abducens Nerve and Superior Ophthalmic Vein

D-Internal acoustic meatus with vestibulocochlear nerve

E-Jugular Foramen with Vagus Nerve, Spinal Accessory Nerve and Internal Jugular Vein

Question: What activates the intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade?
Explanation:
Intrinsic is stimulated by collagen and Extrinsic is stimulated by tissue factors and trauma to the tissue. 

 

They both have the common reactions of converting factor X to Xa which catalyses the conversion of Prothrombin to Thrombin which results in rapid proteolysis of Fibrogen to Fibrin. Fibrin monomers polymerize forming the clot.

Question:
Iron is an important component of our diet. It is used in erythrocytes to bind Oxygen as well as in other biochemical process such as in the electron transport chain. However like many essential components of our diet, Iron can be harmful in excess. 

Excess Iron, Haemochromatosis, can be caused by diet, disease or genetic defect.

Which hormone when damaged, either by disease or due to a genetic defect, causes Haemochromatosis?
Explanation:
Hepcidin controls the storage of iron.

 

It was talked about in Dr Andrew Shore's plenary about Vitamins & Minerals.

Question:
You are on a placement in A&E and a patient arrives who is having trouble stopping their nosebleed. After taking a brief history, you find out that the patient does not eat a very balanced diet and has a horrid dislike for any vegetable, particularly green leafy vegetables. They have noticed that their gums have been bleeding and that they have been getting more bruises lately.

You take a blood test. You find that the patient has low plasma levels of a vitamin. 

Which vitamin, if deficient, would cause these symptoms?
Explanation:
Vitamin K is involved in the coagulation cascade of blood clotting as it is essential for synthesis of Prothrombin.

Prothrombin cleaves Fibrinogen to Fibrin.

Fibrin can then bind together, forming long polymer chains that form a fibrin mesh.

Question: A child presents with a fractured radius, while taking the history you find that the child has fractured quite a few bones previously. On examination you see that the child is small for their age, has bowed legs and curvature of the spine. What vitamin deficiency would you diagnose this child with?
Explanation: In children vitamin D leads to rickets. As vitamin D is necessary for calcium absorption, a lack of vitamin D leads to soft bones and stunted growth.

Question: what happens to the pH of the stomach on arrival of food?
Explanation: The pH of the stomach rises when food enters the stomach because the food acts a buffer for the stomach acid, it then subsequently falls.

Question: Some eye examinations, such as the dilated fundus examination, require a drug to be administered in the form of an eye drop, dilating the pupil and allowing a more accurate examination.  Which of the following drugs is most commonly used in this scenario?
Explanation:
Tropicamide - This is a mACh receptor antagonist, which blocks parasympathetic impulses, paralysing pupil constrictor response and the ciliary muscles, causing pupil dilation.  The effect of the drug is short-lived, so is most routinely used.

Phenylephrine - An adrenoceptor agonist which acts on sympathetic nervous system, causing dilation of pupil and peripheral vasoconstriction.  Not commonly used.

Tetracaine - Local anaesthetic which blocks voltage gated sodium channels in axons, causing loss of corneal reflex.

Cocaine - Both a local anesthetic and sympathomimetic, causing pupil dilation peripheral vasoconstriction and loss of corneal reflexes.  Not commonly used due to anaesthetic qualities.

Pilocarpine - mACh receptor agonist that causes pupil constrictor muscle contraction (causing pupil constriction) and opens the canal of Schlemm, causing the eye to often go bloodshot.

Question: A young man skiing alone in the Alps has a rather dangerous fall and lands, out of his skis feet first, into a rocky area. Mountain rescue arrives an hour or so later and the emergency physician is worried about vascular compromise to his right lower leg, from a few centimetres below his knee, as he discovers it was held in between two smooth but close together rocks since after the fall. The physician needs to take which pulse to help assess the damage?
Explanation: A and E are upper limb pulses and are not relevant to the right leg. The femoral pulse is at the mid-inguinal point (halfway between the pubic symphysis and ASIS), the popliteal pulse is at the popliteal fossa at the back of the knee. The posterior tibial pulse is found in the tarsal tunnel and gets the pulse of the posterior tibial artery. A poor or irregular pulse here would indicate lower vascular damage to the right leg/
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb

Question: A patient comes into A&E with an injured left knee. She was running an ultra marathon when she changed direction and felt a 'pop' in her knee. An MRI confirms what the orthopaedic consultant suspects is the likely diagnosis from the patient history and medical record-the patient tells the consultant that she has done this injury for the third time now. What is the most likely diagnosis and best treatment for the patient?
OptionA: ACL tear and non-operative therapy program of 6 to 8 weeks
OptionB: ACL tear and operative therapy program of 6 to 9 months
OptionC: PCL tear and operative therapy program of 6 to 9 months
OptionD: PCL tear and non-operative program of 6 to 8 weeks
OptionE: A stable patella fracture and non-perative therapy program of 6 to 8 weeks
Explanation:
The running knee injury here is most likely to be an ACL tear. A common mechanism of the injury here is twisting the knee as you change direction in running and is often accompanied by a 'pop' feeling in the knee. A PCL tear is more commonly caused by either a fall on a hyper flexed knee with the foot plantar flexed or a strike on the front of your tibia with your knee flexed. A patella fracture is commonly caused by following directly on your knee.

 

The first two options are both feasible treatments for an ACL tear. The extent of the damage is often determined by an MRI and usually, most first cases require no surgery. However, this runner has done this injury twice before, suggesting it is recurrent and that a non-surgical program is not sustainable in the future or being effective in this patient. Therefore surgery is more logical, despite the longer recovery time.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb

Question: A boy walks into A&E having suffered a laceration to the upper arm, and can see redness, swelling and flushed area in his skin. The doctor tells him that this is part of the acute inflammatory response. The boy wants to know what white blood cells do here. If the doctor begins from the start of her explanation of the acute inflammatory response, which of the following is she likely to talk about first?
Explanation: Neutrophils, as the most common white blood cell in the blood, accumulate at the site of injury and are allowed into the exudate fluid that enters the interstitial fluid via diapedesis, activated by P selectin and cytokines (via the complement system).

Question: What is the medial border of the femoral canal?
Explanation:
A-Medial

B-lateral

C-Anterior

D-Superior and the opening 

E-Posterior
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb

Question: Which nerve roots make up the Sciatic Nerve?
Explanation:
The Sciatic nerve has a Tibial Portion which innervates all muscles in the posterior compartment in the thigh, except the short head of biceps femoris, all muscles in the posterior compartment of the leg, and all muscles in the sole of the foot. 

 

The common fibular portion of the Sciatic nerve innervates the short head of biceps femurs, all muscles in the anterior and lateral compartments of the leg and extensor digitorum brevis.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb

Question: Increased tissue perfusion as more red blood cells pass though the tissue is a consequence of vasodilation during acute inflammation. Which one of the cardinal signs is this responsible for?
Explanation: Rubor - redness

Question: You encounter a patient diagnosed with barrett's oesophagus and they inquire into their condition with much curiosity. Which of the following terms are you most likely to mention here?
Explanation:
B-a change of one mature cell type with an other; barrett's oesophagus involves the cells of the oesophagus changing from stratified squamous to columnar epithelium via reflux

A-Increase in cell number

C-Increase in cell size

D-Decrease in cell size

E is made up

Question: There are multiple types of joints in the body. What type of synovial joint permits gliding or sliding movements?
Explanation: Plane. E.g. the Acromioclavicular joint

Question: Joints have a rich nerve supply provided by articular nerves. Hilton's law states that the nerves supplying a joint also supply the muscles moving the joint and the skin covering their distal attachments. The nerve of a joint transmits impulses which play a key role in which sense?
Explanation: Proprioception: The ability to sense stimuli arising within the body regarding position, motion, and equilibrium. Even if a person is blindfolded, he or she knows through proprioception if an arm is above the head or hanging by the side of the body. The sense of proprioception is disturbed in many neurological disorders. It can sometimes be improved through the use of sensory integration therapy, a type of specialized occupational therapy.

Question: A doctor is ending his shift in A&E. He hands over than a 10 year old boy came in after falling off his bike. An X-ray revealed that he had fractured the epiphyseal plate of his Fibula. Which part of the epiphyseal plate allows the bone to grow in length?
Explanation: On the diaphyseal side of the epiphyseal plate, cartilage is ossified, allowing the diaphysis to grow in length.

Question: What is the dominant component of dense regular connective tissue?
Explanation: Collagen type I

Question: What type of cartilage is not covered by a layer of dense connective tissue essential for the growth and maintenance of cartilage, the perichondrium?
Explanation: Articular cartilage lacks a perichondrium because it is subject to compression and any blood vessels would be occluded.The articular cartilage faces a joint cavity and does not need to integrate physically with any tissue on its superficial side.

Question: C fibres are sensory neurones located in the Periphery, and involved in the pain response. They are not myelinated and their conduction velocities are slow. Why is conducting pain information slowly an advantage?
OptionB: We can respond to the source of pain before the pain sensation becomes intense
OptionC: It prevents the pain sensation becoming intense
OptionD: The signal reaches our brains more slowly
OptionE: Prevents too much pain in a fight or flight situation
Explanation: It is beneficial for a signal to reach our brains more slowly.

Question: Tay-Sachs disease is a lysosomal storage disease. An enzyme defect causes which substance to accumulate?
Explanation: Myelin accumulates, causing neurones to become buried in lipid. This leads to a decline in function from about 6 months including sight, hearing and muscle function.

Question: The Haematocrit describes the proportion of the total blood volume occupied by which cells?
Explanation: Red blood cells/erythrocytes

Question: Part of the common pathway of the coagulation cascade involves Thrombin converting Fibrinogen into Fibrin. What molecules does Thrombin cleave, allowing Fibrin to form a stable clot?
Explanation:
Fibrinopeptide A cleavage from fibrinogen by thrombin allows Alpha strands of one fibrin molecule to enter the Gamma globular unit of another.

Fibrinopeptide B cleavage from fibrinogen by thrombin allows Beta strands of one fibrin molecule to enter the Beta globular unit of another.

This self assembling side to side aggregation forms a thick fibrin mesh.

Question: A patient comes into A&E having sustained a very minor laceration to the knee. He is bleeding very heavily from the wound - more than you would expect. The patient has no underlying vascular defects. One of your suspicions is that he may have a vitamin deficiency. What foods contain this vitamin needed for blood clotting?
Explanation: http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/vitamins-minerals/Pages/Vitamin-K.aspx

Question: You encounter a 14 year old girl who asks for advice about contraception. She ultimately asks you to provide her with the combined pill. In considering your response, which of these should not be a prime concern in making an assessment of the patient?
OptionA: That the patient is under the legal age of sexual intercourse in the UK
OptionB: Whether the patient can or cannot be persuaded to tell her parents/guardians first
OptionC: Whether the patient understands the advice you are giving and has mental capacity
OptionD: That the patient's health may suffer as a result of you refusing to provide her with contraception
OptionE: Whether the patient will begin or continue to have sexual intercourse regardless of whether you provide her with contraception or not
Explanation:
Though it is of course important that the patient is under the legal age of sex in the UK, the Fraser Guidelines of 1985 specify, in response to Mrs Gilick's court case to ensure parents would be informed of their children asking for contraceptive advice, the following;

1) The doctor must judge whether the patient is able to understand what the doctor is telling her

2) The doctor may be unable to persuade the patient to inform her parents or allow the doctor to inform her parents

3) The patient may be likely to have sex with or without the provided contraception

4) The patient's health may suffer as a result of not being provided with contraception 

5) It may be in the patient's best interests to be provided with contraception

 

This combined with Lord Scarman's clause of being Gilick Competent (the patent has sufficient mental capacity) mean that the patient, if insistent and in accordance with the 5 criteria above, should be provided with contraception, even if underage.
Tags: Pregnancy, Health Psychology, Clinical Skills, Sexual Health

Question: You encounter a patient with anogenital warts and discuss treatment options with them. They decline the offer of physical abrasion treatment but you discuss topical treatments and they accept this. The warts on the patient are quite large, but learning that the patient is pregnant, you are easily able to pick a suitable cream. Which cream is this most likely to be from this list?
Explanation:
B and E are made up

Podophyllotoxin is generally used to treat large clusters of smaller warts rather than larger ones. In most circumstances, imiquimod is used for larger warts and TCA for harder smaller ones, but TCA is recommended for use with pregnant women as it is considered the safest topical treatment to use in pregnancy. This treatment must be applied though by a health professional in a GUM clinic as it can damage healthy skin, but it does not have the mild side effects of Imiquimod.

Question: Which of the following is most likely to be indicated be observing colourless urine in a patient?
Explanation: A and D produce orange colour, B produces red, C produces green or blue. Diabetes Insipidus inhibits the actions of ADH/Vasopressin, hence causing excessive water excretion in urine.

Question: From which zone of the adrenal glands are androgens produced?
Explanation: E is made up; D is where adrenaline, noradrenaline and dopamine (in small amounts) are made; Zona Glomerulosa is where the mineralocorticoids are made, Fasiculata where the glucosteroids are made and Reticularis where the androgens are made.
Tags: Sexual Health, Hormones, hormonal control, Endocrinology

Question: What day of the menstrual cycle does Ovulation occur? The surge of which hormone causes ovulation?
Explanation: The oestrogen surge initiates changes in the output of gonadotrophins. At very high levels of oestrogen, the negative feedback effects are replaced by positive feedback that results in a sharp increase in both gonadothrophins, but especially LH. This constitutes the LH surge, which is responsible for the events occurring during the preovulatory phase and for ovulation itself.

Question: When the egg is fertilised, the Corpus Luteum continues to produce progesterone and oestrogen for a number of weeks before the Placenta takes over production of these hormones. When does the placenta start taking over, from when the egg is fertilised?
Explanation: Corpus Luteum continues to produce progesterone and oestrogen for 8 weeks before its function declines, due to decreased hCG levels.

Question: You are asked to do a Urinalysis test on a pregnant patient. Specifically, you are asked to check for raised Glucose levels, why might this be?
OptionE: The patient may have been fasting/starving for a prolonged period of time
Explanation:
A - Leukocytes may indicate UTI 

B- Nitrites are associated with infection, and organisms responsible for UTIs convert nitrate to nitrite 

C- Acidic pH may indicate kidney stones. Alkalinity may indicate certain bacteria

D- Glucose elevation may indicate abnormal blood sugar levels due to diabetes. Pregnancy can also raise blood sugar levels

E- Ketones are formed during abnormal excessive breakdown of fat during starvation/fasting

Question:
Gary presented with a profuse, creamy penile discharge of 3 days duration. He denies sexual intercourse with anyone except his girlfriend. A gram stain of pus obtained by a urethral swab demonstrates gram negative diplococci. 

 

What do you think Gary is most likely to need treatment for ?
Explanation:
Although the penile discharge is a common symptom to answers A, B and D; the presence of 5 or more WBCs per oil immersion field with intracellular gram negative diplococci indicates that the patient has Gonorrhea at a specificity of over 95%.

 

Uncomplicated urethral gonorrhea can be treated with antibiotics administered orally or intramuscularly. Something to look into is the increasing resistance to treatment in certain areas - South East Asia for example is known to be Penicillin resistant and thus Penicillin not considered as treatment in that area.

Question:
Changes between infertile and fertile cervical mucus are indicators of ovulation.

 

Katy Parkins, a 24 year old primary teacher, is curious as to why her vaginal discharge can sometimes have the appearance of raw egg white. What is this an indication of, when does it occur and what is it stimulated by ?
OptionA: The cervical mucus is continuously thin and watery until day 14, after which it becomes scanty and thick until menstruation - this is when Katy detects raw egg white resembling discharge. It indicates that this is a period of infertility and the thinning of cervical mucus is due to the Progesterone increase.
OptionB: The cervical mucus appears as raw egg white during the period where ovulation is approaching. This is known as "fertile mucus". These changes are stimulated by an increase in LH and indicate ovulation.
OptionC: The cervical mucus appears as raw egg white during the period where ovulation is approaching. The increase in Oestrogen pre-ovulation triggers these changes in the mucus until "peak mucus day". This cervical mucus consistency indicates a period of fertility where the mucus is thin and penetrable to sperm.
OptionD: The cervical mucus is continuously thin and watery until day 14, after which it becomes scanty and thick until menstruation - this is when Katy detects raw egg white resembling discharge. The increasing temperature thickens the mucus post ovulation.
Explanation:
A - Completely false - the cervical mucus resembles raw egg whites as a result to its increase in volume, fluidity and clarity in the period approaching ovulation - this is when it is thin. It is the rise in Oestrogen that stimulates these changes in the cervical mucus. Progesterone on the contrary is thought to increase the thickness of the cervical mucus thus decreasing fertility. 

 

B - False: Oestrogen rises are the stimuli for the changes in the cervical mucus. There is a peak mucus day that correlates with the peak secretion of Oestrogen, and occurs approximately one day before the LH surge (max 48 hours). This is when the cervical mucus is at its most penetrable - the raw egg white consistency indicates a period of fertility.

 

C- This is the correct answer. 

 

D- False - Again as in q.A with regards to timing of the raw egg white consistency. The temperature does increase post- ovulation and it is important to note this as it is also an important indicator used to determine whether in a period of fertility. I am unsure as to whether there is a relationship between the thickening of the mucus and the increase temperature, other than that they are both caused by the increase in Progesterone after ovulation.

 

"Just prior to ovulation, estrogen levels rise causing the cervix to swell and soften and the external os to dilate, allowing sperm better access to the uterus.4 Also during this time, the cervix secretes slippery, clear and stretchy mucus which exudes from the cervix into the vagina. This ‘fertile mucus’ facilitates the ability of sperm to travel from the vagina into the uterus and can help keep sperm alive for up to five days. After ovulation, progesterone causes the cervix to harden, close, and secrete thicker, cloudy, (or opaque) mucus which acts as a plug, preventing bacteria and sperm from entering the uterus. Further, when this thick mucus is present, fertilization is very unlikely."
Tags: Sexual Health, Hormones, Physiology, reproductive system

Question: What does the Graafian follicle contain?
Explanation: When activated, the first meiotic division is completed. When this happens, the primary follicle has matured into a secondary follicle. The second division then starts, and a Graafian follicle is formed. This contains a secondary oocyte. This second division is not completed, unless the ovum is fertilised.

Question: A Gynecoid pelvis has:

Question: When does the secondary oocyte complete meiosis II?

Question: You encounter a young girl at your sexual health clinic. She wants short term (over a few weeks to couple months) contraception for use with a single partner, whom she reasonably trusts, but wants the device(s) with the highest chances of not getting pregnant and one that will protect her against STIs. Which of the following option is best suited for the patient?
OptionC: Male Condoms for him with Oral Combined Pill for her
OptionD: Oral Combined Pill with female condoms for her
Explanation:
Cap or the Diaphragm is 92% to 96% effective but is prone to human error.

Female Condom is 95% effective and are prone to human error.

OCP is over 99% effective if taken correctly.

POP is over 99% effective if taken correctly.

Male Condoms are 98% effective and are prone to human error.

C and D are probably one of the best two option, but the male condom has a slightly higher prevention chance than the female condom, and as the patient wants the devices that will reduce her pregnancy chances to maximum and she trusts her partner, C is the better option.

E-Obturator Nerve
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb

Question: Your GI consultant presents to you a patient that has developed some Gastric ulcers. She tells you that they have ruled out the chances of a H.Pylori cause. The patient is of relatively normal weight and about 30, with no smoking history or alcohol misuse. Before you take a history, the consultant tells you that it is likely another extremely common cause of gastric ulcers, being...
Explanation: The inhibition of COX-1 enzymes via the action of non-specific NSAIDS. such as Ibuprofen and Aspirin,  results in a decrease in mucus lining is no longer being produced and the gastric lining is now vulnerable to gastric acid; this can result in gastric ulcers. Though you have not taken a history of the patient, NSAIDs are the second most common cause in the UK for gastric ulcers, after Helicobacter Pylori. Dr Green's lecture has the rough figures, with gastric carcinoma being 3rd most common and the other causes listed much rarer.

Question: A 40 year old patient  presents who complains of severe dyspepsia while lying down after eating a large meal. He is overweight, consumes more than 5 units of alcohol on average a day and is an ex-smoker of 2 pack-years. He has no major operative history, bar an appendectomy, and has no outstanding health concerns, bar having an obese reading on BMI and being unfit. Urea breath test comes out negative for H.Pylroi bacteria. What treatment should you offer him 1st line to treat his condition?
OptionA: Exercise and Weight-loss program with Diet Management
Explanation: The patient is likely complaining of GORD, a condition which should first be managed with lifestyle changes, which include cutting down on alcohol, caffeine, spicy foods and on meals sizes. This is usually first line therapy to treat the condition; if the question asked for relieving, an antacid such as Magnesium Hydroxide, would be a suitable answer, but this relieves symptoms, not the cause. PPI and H2 Receptor antagonists are 3rd and 2nd line treatment guidelines as they cause side effects such as diarrhoea and impotence. Most cases are lessened by simply reducing acid production through lifestyle changes.

Question: Where does the Pectoralis Major insert?
At what stage of development is an egg in during ovulation?
Explanation:
Seconday oocyte is a diploid cell which is arrested in metaphase 2 of the second meitotic division. Meiosis 2 is only completed when the sperm penetrates the egg. the egg is now an ovum.

 

Oogonium = the stem cel the eggs develop from

Primary oocyte = arrested in prophase 1 during follicular development

Question: What is the term for a fibroid found lying between the endometrium and the myometrium?
Explanation:
A: Within the myometrium

B: Between the endometrium and myometrium

C: Between the myometrium and parametrium

D: Floating freely but attached to the uterus

E: Made up
Tags: Anatomy of pelvis and perineum, Sexual Health, Case 2, reproductive system

Question: A 39 year old women goes to see her GP worried that she has reached the menopause prematurely.  Considering that oestrogen is no longer produced, if she is postmenopausal which would best describe the anterior pituitary gonadotrophin levels?
Explanation:
No oestrogen = no negative feedback inhibition of FSH & LH by oestrogen 

So FSH & LH levels are high in postmenopausal women

Question:
A 58 year old man presented to his GP with severe dyspepsia, he is an intelligent man who studied biosciences at Cardiff university. He is a bit rusty on his knowledge and asks you to explain the mechanism involved in acid secretion at the H+ K+ ATPase pump. 

 

You are put under pressure to remember your first year lectures with TJ... you need not panic as they all went in perfectly. 

 

What is the role of somatostatin receptors in the nervous and humoral mechanisms controlling gastric secretion (in a parietal cell)?
OptionA: Activate Gs to increase PKA and help switch off acid secretion
OptionB: Activate Gs to increase PKC and help switch off acid secretion
OptionC: Activate Gi to increase PKA and help switch off acid secretion
OptionD: Activate Gi to decrease PKA and help switch off acid secretion
OptionE: Activate Gq to decrease PKC and help switch off acid secretion
Explanation: Somatostatin inhibits adenylate cyclase, so there's a decrease in CAMP, so less protein kinase A is available to fuel the proton pump

Question:
A patient is admitted into the respiratory ward with a persistent cough, breathlessness, weightloss, high temperature, night sweats and weight loss. 

 

You notice he has been prescribed Rifampicin, what is the mechanism of action of this antibiotic?

 

(Bonus points for diagnosing his condition)
Explanation:
Rifampican- is used to treat TB by blocking bacterial RNA polymerase in the Mycobacterium tuberculosis so it can no longer multiply. 

http://www.drugbank.ca/drugs/DB01045

 

Beta Lactam antibiotics include Pencillin's and Cephalosporins

Protein inhibitors inclde Chloramphenicol, tetracyclines,macroclides

Folate synthesis inhibitor is Sulfonamide

Cell membrane inhibitor is Isoniazid ( only works on mycobacteria)

Question:
McCune-Albright syndrome causes a triad of symptoms including excess endocrine hormones, Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia and cutaneous hyperpigmentation. 

 

This condition causes early onset puberty, but what type of  pubertal abnormality is it?
Explanation:
Endocrine excess in McCune Albrights syndrome means there are high levels of oestrogen and growth hormone which causes premature thelarche and menarche. Therefore it is precocious (early onset) puberty however there isn't an abnormality with the gonadotrophs

 

Causes of gonadotrophin depedent precocious puberty include intracranial tumours. Also known as Central precocious puberty.

 

The last two delayed onset puberty

Causes of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism include genetic disorders suchs as Kallmans

Causes of hypergonadotrophis hypogonadism include klinefelters and turners syndroms

Question:
Whilst on placement at the Sexual Health clinic, you are approached by a young male who randomly asks you which components of your Nervous system are responsible for:

A) Inducing an erection   and:

B) Causing ejaculation.

 

Although slightly taken aback, what are the correct answers?
Explanation: From the anatomy booklet given in case 2, the Parasympathetic part of the ANS is responsible for inducing an erection, with the Sympathetic branch causing ejaculation.

Question: A 87 year old comes to the GP surgery complaining of frequent urination, particularly at night. Following a diabetes test, which returned normal, the doctor suggested Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH) may be the cause. BPH causes enlargement of a specific part of the prostate. The doctor asks you which part is this?
Explanation:
The transitional zone is the correct answer. This zone surrounds the prostatic urethra, therefore would cause the symptoms of frequency. Diabetes could also cause frequent urination but there would also be high volumes of urine too.

This is a question from page 8 of the Case 2 Anatomy booklet.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of pelvis and perineum

Question: You are in a sexual health clinic when a patient asks you to explain how you are affected by hepatitis; she wants to what kind of infection it is as her local GP explained that she had a DNA virus infection and was told it was hepatitis. Which hepatitis does this lady most likely have?
Explanation: Hepatitis B is the only DNA hepatitis virus; the others are caused by a RNA virus, with D along being able to occur following Hepatitis B infection.

Question: A cardiologist is explaining to a patient with hypertension the effects of Nitric Oxide on endothelium in blood vessels. She moves on to explain a substance which has a directly opposite function; which of the following is she most likely discussing?
Explanation: According to our lecture on endothelium health; H2O2 can act as both a relaxant and constrictor depending on circumstance, Angiotensin II is activated via Angiotensin I from catalysis of ACE from the lungs and acts as a vasoconstrictor that always increases NaCl and water rent ion and H+ secretion in the kidneys. This constricts blood vessels, compared to the opposite function of NO relaxing blood vessels.

Question: Atherosclerosis commonly occurs at bifurcations and curvatures in blood vessels and causes a number of changes to the endothelium. Which of these changes is most likely false in atherosclerosis?
OptionA: An increase in ROS and drop in eNOS at the site
OptionB: An increase in inflammation at the site via increased inflammatory signals
OptionC: A decrease in leukocyte adhesion, as foam cell numbers increase dramatically following oxLDL formation
OptionD: Monocyte adhesion, migration and differentiation into macrophages and then foam cells
OptionE: A decrease in endothelial cell repair due to disturbed blood flow
Explanation: C should be completely opposite; leukocyte adhesion increases due oi increased inflammatory signals raised by foam cells and other parts of the endothelium and atherosclerosis process.
Tags: Blood Cells, Blood Circulation, Cardiology, Cardiovascular System

Question: A patient, who is themselves a scientists, requires a GTN spray after some relatively light exercise. The patient knows that Ca2+ concentration is decreased in Smooth muscle cells as a result of the spray, but is unsure by which mechanism this occurs. He proposes the following theories; which of these is closest to the correct mechanism...
OptionA: An increase in Angiotensin II activates guanylyl cyclase that raises cAMP that activates PKC that lowers calcium concentration in the Smooth muscle cell
OptionB: An increase in Nitric oxide directly activates a GPCR that blocks calcium entry into the smooth muscle cell
OptionC: An increase in adenosine activates guanylyl cyclase that raises cGMP that activates PKA that lowers calcium concentration in the Smooth muscle cell
OptionD: A decrease in Angiotensin activity eventually lowers sympathetic output via limiting calcium influx via cAMP activity
OptionE: An increase in Nitric Oxide activates guanylyl cyclase that raises cGMP that activates PKC that lowers calcium concentration in the Smooth muscle cell
Explanation: None of the answers are the correct mechanism for GTN spray but answer E has only one mistake; PKG activation occurs rather than via PKC. The other answers all have multiple parts wrong or are completely made up (e.g. D).  The full mechanism is in Coffey's lecture
Tags: Biochemistry, Blood Circulation, Cardiology, Cardiovascular System, Pharmacology

Question: Which of the following is not an enterogastrone?
Explanation: Gastrin, secreted by G cells, is found in the stomach mainly; an enterogastrone is any hormone secreted by the mucosa of the duodenum in the lower gastrointestinal tract in response to dietary lipids that have some inhibitory action in the previous actions of stomach cells (Somatostatin, via D cells, inhibits Gastrin secretion).

Question: The NSAID-aspirin, which domain of the prostaglandin-H synthase does is block?
Explanation:
Blocks Cyclo-oxidase domain, so that PGG2 does not form to generate PGH2. 

PGH2 is needed for cell specific prostaglandin synthases/isomerases;

PGE2 GI Mucosa, renal function, uterine contraction, vasodilation

PGF2 Bronchoconstriction, uterine contraction

PGD2 Bronchoconstrictor, anti-platelet aggregation.

TXA2 Platelet aggregation, vasoconstriction

PGI2 Anti-platelet aggregation, vasodilator, endothelial, renal and CNS function. (tends to have opposing effect of TXA2)

Question:
Klinefelter Syndrome occurs when men are born with an extra X chromosome. 

 

Often patients will have low testosterone levels resulting in low libido, breast development, small testes and small muscle tone. 

 

They are likely to also have raised LH and FSH levels. 

 

What type of condition is this?
Explanation:
Kline felters is a Primary Hypogonadism and Hypergonadtropic Hypogonadism because the testes cannot produce enough testosterone therefore there will not be a negative feedback mechanism to control LH and FSH. Hence LH and FSH rise above normal. 

 

Androgen /hormone replacement therapy is the treatment

Question: The liver acinus is the functional unit of the liver parenchyma. A young GP is explaining a hepatocyte histology result to a hepatitis patient. He is being told that cells in one zone of the acinus is clearly infected; which part is he most likely discussing?
Explanation: Zone 1 is the periportal zone, Zone 2 is the Intermediate Zone and Zone 3 is the Centrilobular zone. Hepatocyte acinus is split into 3 concentric elliptical zones and in a hepatitis infection, Zone 1 is affected first as the cells in tho zone receive sinusoidal blood transport contents first, such as O2 and nutrients, so that these cells will receive the viral infection first.
Tags: Functions of different tissues, Gastrointestinal System, Case 3

Question: The pancrease produces many enzymes which are activated by trypsin. Which of these enzymes is not activated from specific zymogens by trypsin that is secreted by the pancreas?
Explanation: Alpha amylase is secreted by the pancrease in its active form; it is not activated by any other enzyme. Though trypsin activated the enzymes listed, it also has a positive feedback affect on itself in the intestinal lumen.

Question: An SAS officer currently has bradycardia as a result of serve hypothermia, whilst military training in the Alps. At night she is avoiding detection from a searching "enemy" convoy and has to make a run for it. She quickly injects a substance that causes rapid tachycardia. Which receptor does the heart respond to sympathetic stimulation via to increase the heart rate and which substance did she most likely inject into herself?
Explanation: Beta-1-adrenoreceptors are the correct receptor for sympathetic action on the heart; both adrenaline and isoproternol are viable options; in hospital medicine, adrenaline is used commonly for Anaphylactic shock, cardiogenic shock, cardiac arrest, while isoproternol is used commonly for bradycardia and AV block. Since this person is not suffering from an acute medical condition, she is best suffered by taking isopternol.
Tags: Cardiology, cardiac cycle, Cardiovascular System, case 4

Question: What is the dentate line?
OptionA: When the epithelia in the oesophagus changes from stratified squamous to simple columnar the the stomach.
OptionB: When the epithelia in the rectum changes from simple columnar to stratified squamous.

Question: Which of the below, along with histamine, cause endothelial cells to move selectins to their apical surface?
Explanation:
Histamine and interleukin induce endothelial cells to move selectins (cell adhesion proteins) to their apical surface (facing the blood). This allows neutrophils to bind via their selectin ligands and leads to the adhesion/activation/margination/transmigration process.

See Case 1 Dr Joshi Lectures on Inflammation

Question: Alcohol dependence and over-consumption begins via a mechanism first involving operant conditioning; which one of the following terms best describes how alcohol over-consumption can first develop?
Explanation: Positive Reinforcement, a feeling a euphoria that brings psychological rewards; negative reinforcement follows, that is using alcohol to lessen stress and anxiety.
