Question: A 75-year-old past shipyard worker receives chest x-ray as part of a routine medical work-up. The radiologist reports findings suggestive of an occupational lung disease. Which of the following descriptions is most consistent with this patient's probable findings?
OptionA: Hyperinflated lungs with a loss of lung markings
OptionB: Nodular calcium lesions in the apex of the lung
OptionC: Signet ring carcinoma in the upper respiratory tract
OptionE: Fibrocalcific parietal pleural plaques on the diaphragm
Explanation:
The history given is constant with asbestos exposure with past work in shipyards, somewhere was asbestos was previously and commonly used; thus presenting with fibrocalcific parietal pleural plaques on the diaphragm is expected of someone with asbestosis.

In early stages it can cause benign fibrocalcific parietal pleural plaques, predominantly of the posterio-lateral mid lung and diaphragm. It is common to discover these lesions in asymptomatic patients during routine chest x-rays. Later, it can result in fibrotic lung disease, mesothelioma or other lung malignancies such as bronchogenic carcinoma.

A-More typical presentation of emphysema

B-More typical presentation of latent tuberculosis 

C-Typical of adenocarcinoma 

D-Typical sarcoidosis appearance

Question: A 65-year-old gentleman has worked in a sand blasting factory for over 25 years. He presents to his GP  with dyspnoea that progressively is getting worse. His GP suggests he has a restrictive lung disease. Which of the following has most likely been the long-term mechanism of his disease development?
Explanation: This patient presents with a history of sand blasting and restrictive lung disease and is most likely got silicosis as in the environment of  chronic silica exposure, the alveolar macrophages will continuously phagocytose the silica particles, but cannot to destroy them. The result is dysfunction of the alveolar macrophages within the lung parenchyma. The exposure to silica also results in the development of an inflammatory response within the lung tissue that begins the development of parenchymal damage and fibrosis. Silica deposition can be seen as lightly birefringent (variation in refractive index) crystals under polarized light deposited within the lung tissue.
Tags: Lung function, Respiratory physiology, Case 5, Immunology, Inflammation

Question: Mr Thomas has Barrett's oesophagus in which the squamous epithelium lining his oesophagus is replaced by metaplastic columnar epithelium.  Which of the following does not describe epithelium in general?
Explanation:
Epithelium is avascular, innervated & regenerative. 

Principles of micro anatomy plenary PCS 1

Question: DNA damage can cause cell arrest at which two stages of the cell cycle?
Explanation:
This question refers to the cell-cycle checkpoints. There are three checkpoints: G1, G2 and M phase. The G1 checkpoint will arrest the cell before DNA replication (S phase) if there is already damage to the DNA. The cell may 'fix' the DNA at this point before continuing to S phase, but apoptosis will occur if the damage is too great. The G2 checkpoint will arrest the cell before division takes place (M phase) if any damage has occurred during DNA replication. 

The third checkpoint, M phase, will arrest the cell if the chromosomes are not attached to the mitotic spindle.

Question taken from small group worksheet on cell differentiation and stem cells, see Prof. Wilson's lectures for more info :)

Question: A patient comes to your clinic with the skin lesions suggestive of psoriasis. If these lesions were biopsied, all of the following would be expected except:
Explanation: Psoriasis is a systemic inflammatory condition with prominent skin findings that include all of the above bar C. Skin lesions in psoriasis are typically described as dark red plaques with silvery scale. Histological characteristics of psoriatic plaques include: increased thickness of stratum spinosum, decreased thickness of stratum granulosum, neutrophils in the stratum corneum, and infiltration of T cells and dendritic cells in plaques.

Question: A man walks into A&E looking sweating and complaining of "tight crushing chest pain". You take an ECG of this patient and you discover he is having a Myocardial infarction, you notice ST elevation in leads II, III and aVF. Which artery is would you suggest is blocked based on these results?
Explanation: Blockage to the right coronary artery shows changes in ECG leads II, III and aVF.

Question: A patient is found to have abnormally high levels of hormone secretion by the S endocrine cells in her duodenum. Which of the following would you most expect to find in this patient?
Explanation:
The S endocrine cells in the duodenum produce the hormone secretin, which increases pancreatic HCO3- secretion.

There are 3 types of enteroendocrine cells in the duodenum, and each of them secretes a hormone that acts on the pancreas:

1. I Cells -> cholecystokinin (CCK) -> increase pancreatic secretions
2. S cells -> secretin -> increase pancreatic HCO3- secretion
3. K cells -> gastric inhibitory peptide (GIP) -> increase insulin release

In addition to its action on the pancreas, secretin also decreases gastric acid secretion and increases bile secretion.  The release of gastric HCl into the duodenum is the most potent stimulator for secretin release. Increased levels of HCO3- act to neutralize gastric acid in the duodenum thereby allowing proper functioning of pancreatic enzymes.

Question: A 7-year-old male is admitted to the hospital with his fourth episode of wheezing and dyspnoea. His symptoms are exacerbated by mold and pollen. Which of the following is most likely to be observed in this patient?
Explanation:
The patient's presentation is consistent with extrinsic/allergic asthma where, occasionally  eosinophils are observed in the sputum of patients with this condition.

Asthma can be divided into intrinsic and extrinsic types. In intrinsic asthma, infection, exertion, stress, or a drug reaction is responsible for bronchoconstriction. This type of asthma is not allergen-mediated. In extrinsic asthma, an inhaled allergen triggers a type I (IgE-mediated) hypersensitivity reaction that leads to activation of mast cells and eosinophils. The release of inflammatory substances from those cells is then responsible for the bronchoconstriction observed. Approximately 1/3 of asthma cases are allergen-triggered.

Question: You fall asleep at a lecture when suddenly the lecturer wakes you up with a long stic.  You want to know quickly what this lecture is about and the only word you see is "Langerhans cell"..you wonder what this is all about and remember about Islets of Langerhans...but are these two the same?
OptionA: The Islet of Langerhans are large Lymphoid aggregations found in the small intestinal mucosa, while Langerhans cells are cells releasing glucagon or insulin.
OptionB: The Islet of Langerhans is the endocrine tissue of the pancreas and the Langerhans cells are the cells within the islets.
OptionC: Islet of Langerhans are aggregations of Langerhans cells which are dendritic cells found in the skin.
OptionD: Langerhans cells are dendritic cells found on the skin while Islet of Langerhans are endocrine tissu found in the pancreas, which releases glucagon and insulin.
Explanation: Peyer's patches are the lymphoid aggregations found in the small intestin.

Question: Mr Potter attends A&E after vomiting blood several times throughout the day.  You carry out an endoscopy of his upper GI tract and find a small lesion in the distal portion of his oesphagus.  On closer examination you discover the culprit... a ruptured small vessel.  After cauterizing the vessel, you carry out further tests.  These show his bleeding time, prothrombin time, and his activated partial thromboplastin time are all elevated, leading you to the diagnosis of vitamin K deficiency.  Vitamin K is important in the coagulation cascade as it activates many of the factors.  What are these factors?
OptionC: Factors III, IV, VIII, IX, and X.
OptionD: Factors I, II, IV, V, and IX.
OptionE: Factors II, IV, VII, VIII, and X.
Explanation:
Vitamin K activates factors II, VII, IX, and X.

 

This is also a useful website for vitamin K deficiency.

 

http://www.patient.co.uk/doctor/vitamin-k-deficiency

Question: A 6-year-old girl presents to A&E with acute airway obstruction. Physical examination by a consultant shows cough, episodic wheezing, and excess mucus production. Increased quantities of which of the following options would predispose the child to extrinsic asthma sensitisation?
Explanation:
Extrinsic asthma is a  response to inhaled allergens initially mediated by Th2 cells.

Increased quantities of Th2 cells genetically predispose children to asthma development in the presence of certain environmental allergens, such as pollen or mould.

Early activation is through mast cells activated by cross linking of IgE.

Late activation is via eosinophils. 

Resolution in asthma occurs via macrophages.
Tags: Lung function, Respiratory physiology, Case 5, Immunology

Question: Stress has a number of different psychological theories that govern how it works. Which of these is NOT one of the prominent theories?
Explanation: The 1st answer relates to health based behaviours; the others are all major stress theories covered in Andrew Lawrence's lectures in PCS

Question: Shadowing a neurologist, you are asked questions about neurones and wiring mechanisms.  One question the doctor asks you is; the fact that each neuron contains one axon but can contain many collaterals is most important for what?
Explanation: In divergence a single neurone can influence many others, having many collaterals enables this.

Question: Give the name of the nicotinic receptor antagonist in autonomic ganglia
Luke has been diagnosed with a rare condition called Hutchinson-Gilford progeria, where he is 20 years old, however appears 160 years old. What is the genetic basis of this condition?
Explanation: Hutchinson-Gilford progeria syndrome involves mutations in the LMNA gene.The LMNA gene provides instructions for making a protein called lamin A. This protein is an essential supporting component of the nuclear envelope. Mutations that cause Hutchinson-Gilford progeria syndrome result in the production of an abnormal version of the lamin A protein. The altered protein makes the nuclear envelope unstable and progressively damages the nucleus, making cells more likely to die prematurely.

Question: Fusion of a presynaptic vesicle in neurotransmission depends on two groups of proteins, V (vesicle)  Snare and T (target) Snare. What two proteins are included in the T Snare category?
Explanation:
T snare proteins consist of Syntaxin and SNAP25. V snare proteins consist of Synaptobrevin and Synaptotagmin. 

 

Syntaxin and SNAP25 bind to Synaptobrevin to form a core complex. 

 

On arrival of an impulse Na gated ion channels open causing depolarisation, enabling Ca gated ion channels to open. Ca then binds to C2A on Synaptotagmin, which further binds to phospholipids on the presynaptic membrane, causing vesicular fusion. 

 

Toxins such as Botulinum work by cleaving SNARE proteins 

 

a good video 

 

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iNaOwRjEf1M
Tags: Microbiology, Nervous system, Neurotransmitters, cell biology, Physiology

Question: Which of the following best describes an upper motor neuron lesion?
OptionA: Increased Muscle tone (spasticity - velocity dependant), Increased deep reflexes, loss of superficial reflexes, upward plantar response (Babinksi sign) and decreased strength in the affected limb.
OptionB: Increased Muscle tone, loss of reflexes, no Babinski sign, no effect on muscle strength in affected limb.
OptionC: Decreased muscles tone (not velocity dependant) , loss of reflexes, Muscle fasciculations and atrophy in effected limb
OptionD: Spasticity, negative Babinski's sign, atrophy, fasciultation, and absent deep reflexes.
OptionE: Positive Babinski's sign, Stronger Deep reflex, loss of superficial reflex, atrophy and Fascicultations.
Explanation: A best describes an upper motor neuron lesion, whilst C best describes a lower motor neuron lesion.
Tags: Nerve innervation of upper limb, Nervous system, Peripheral nerve, Case 6, Clinical Skills

Question: A junior doctor has just finished his ward round and decides to go and buy a snack from the café across the road as he is hungry. What hormone promoted his appetite at first and where has it been released from?
Explanation:
All of the above hormones influence food intake. It is ghrelin that is secreted from gastric mucosa following lack of nutrients, ghrelin stimulates neurones in the hypothalamus, where NPY is released and this stimulates orexin release from lateral hypothalamus, which promotes appetite.

 

Ghrelin is important in short-term control of food intake. Remember that ghrelin is the 'mealtime stimulator'

 

Leptin is important in the long term regulation of food intake and energy balance.

 

CCK is an anorexogenic hormone, which, in the presence of fats and protein suppresses appetite.
Tags: Random, Digestion, Functions of different tissues, Gastrointestinal System, Case 3

Question: A 36 year old female patient walked into the GP clinic and had been diagnosed with Hepatitis C virus infected liver. Studies have shown that house keeping genes could play a role.  Which of these are an example of the class of proteins that are considered to be products of housekeeping genes?
Explanation:
Housekeeping genes are involved with the maintenance of basic cellular function, and are expressed in all cells of an organism under normal and patho-physiological conditions.

Examples of the products of housekeeping genes are: ribosomal proteins, metabolic enzymes, RNA polymerase etc.
Tags: DNA, cell biology, cell function, Cell cycle, PCS Unit2

Question: A 40-year-old man presents to a new GP. According to the patient, he has been healthy his entire life and rarely visits doctors, but his sister referred him recently. He reports no past medical or surgical history. His physical exam is notable for an elevated blood pressure (150/90), and a rather large head and jaw, which is larger than you would expect given a photograph of the patient from 10 years ago. Despite the large size of the patient at 105 kg and his height, he is quite weak. What will be the most likely cause of death for this patient?
Explanation:
This patient has likely got acromegaly, the most common cause of death from which is cardiovascular disease.

This is an excess of growth hormone and most commonly occurs in the setting of a pituitary adenoma, but may also occur due to other factors such as cancer. Excess GH in acromegaly results in significant organomegaly.

 

In the case of the cardiovascular system, patients can develop hypertension, left ventricular hypertrophy, asymmetric septal hypertrophy, diastolic heart failure, and cardiomyopathy. Though the patient has a raised risk of dying from malignancy, CV death, usually from congestive heart failure is the most common cause of death in patients with acromegaly.

 

Treatment of acromegaly involves resection of the pituitary adenoma when possible and medical management of growth hormone excess with somatostatin analogues.

Question: An 18 year old man is involved in a fight that leaves his right eye severely damaged and bruised. The examining ophthalmologist takes a biopsy of his tissue and sees that the sympathetic fibres suppling the levator palpebrae muscle have been damaged. The patient is told that this links to the main symptom he is experiencing which is likely to be....
Explanation: The levator palpebrae muscle that acts to elevate the upper eyelid has both striated muscle (supplied by the somatic nervous system) and smooth muscle (supplied by the autonomic nervous system via sympathetic branches). If the striated muscle nerve supply is damaged, B would occur and the patient would be unable to open the eyelid. If smooth muscle nerve supply is damaged, ptosis (drooping of the eyelid) would occur. This symptom may be a further sign of Horner's Syndrome, where the sympathetic trunk is damaged via usually neck disease or chest disease (such as a lung Pancoast Tumour) but can be rarely caused by trauma.

Question: You are observing the various layers of the epidermis of a skin biopsy taken from the sole of a foot of a patient. Where would you expect to find the melanocytes within the layers of the epidermis?
OptionC: found in all of the layers of the skin (stratum corneum, stratum lucidum, stratum granulosum, stratum spinosum and stratum basalestratum corneum, stratum lucidum, stratum granulosum, stratum spinosum and stratum basale)
OptionD: first two layers- the stratum corneum and stratum lucidum
OptionE: the final three layers stratum granulosum, stratum spinosum and stratum basale
Explanation:
Melanocytes are ONLY found in the stratum basale, they make up around 8% of the TOTAL number of cells in the epidermis, and 10-20% of the cells in the stratum basale (http://www.histology.leeds.ac.uk/skin/epidermis_cells.php), they are melanin producing cells and the amount of melanin produced can be increased with exposure to UV light. The amount of melanin produced is one of the key factors of skin pigmentation (along with Carotene pigments in subcutaneous fat (adipose tissue) (orange-yellow colour) and amount of blood and how much oxygen its carrying - haemoglobin (red colour)). The number of melanocytes is constant across all races however the amount of melanin produced by the cells varies. 

A useful way to remember the layers of the epidermis is Come Lets Get Sun Burnt (stratum corneum, stratum lucidum, stratum granulosum, stratum spinosum and stratum basale)

Question:
A 25 year old male enters A and E after being stabbed in the popliteal fossa. The patient is unable to invert his foot or stand on his tip toes. He has also lost sensation on the sole of his foot. 

 

Which nerve has been damaged?
Explanation: The tibial nerve originates from the sciatic nerve and descends through the popiteal fossa through the posterior compartment of the leg and divides into medial and lateral plantar nerves. It supplies the posterior leg muscles and knee.

Question: Restrictive and obstructive lung disease can cause very distinct differences in symptoms-which of the following is incorrect in regards to both sets of conditions?
OptionA: Total lung capacity increases in obstructive lung disease but decreases in restrictive lung disease.
OptionB: Your FVC decreases more significantly in restrictive lung disease.
OptionC: FEV1 only decreases in obstructive lung disease
OptionD: Residual volume decreases only in restrictive lung disease
Explanation: C is not true; FEV decreases usually in both sets of diseases but decreases more significantly in obstructive lung disease in comparison to FVC; in restrictive lung disease, your FEV1/FVC ratio remains constant as these values decrease by the same proportion

Question: Duncan is taken ill (again) with a peptic ulcer. What is the most likely cause of his ulcer?
OptionC: Taking Ibuprofen for a leg injury suffered 2 days ago.
Explanation:
H. pylori is the most common cause for peptic ulcers. 

Influenza does not commonly lead to peptic ulcers.

Short term ibuprofen is unlikely to be the cause. Longer term use will increases the chance of a peptic ulcer developing.

Hot currys contain capsaicin which will trigger C-fibres causing pain but the pain is likely to die down fairly quickly

Question: Robbie falls over whilst playing football. On X-ray he is found to have fractured his Hook of Hamate. Which nerve is most likely to have been affected?
Explanation:
Ulnar nerve turns around the hook of hamate. The hook of hamate is also the distal lateral border of the Guyon canal in which the ulnar nerve runs.

The other nerves do not run this close to the hook of hamate.

Question:
A 27 year old female presents to A and E after being in a domestic fight with her significant other. She was stabbed in the thigh with a knife. 

 

Which of the following suggests damage to the femoral nerve?
Explanation: A lesion of the femoral nerve (L234) is characterised by weakness of the quadriceps femoris muscle and hence weakness of extension of the knee, loss of sensation over the front of the thigh and loss of the knee jerk.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb

Question: What type of cell makes up the majority of cells in the anterior pituitary/adenohypophysis??
Explanation: Somatotrophs, that secrete GH from the adenohypophysis, makes up 50% of the cells. Lactotrophs make up 15 to 20%, Corticotrophs make up 15 to 20%, Gonadotrophs 10% and thyrotrophs 5%

Question: Which of the following description is true when comparing the ileum to the jejunum?
OptionB: Ileum has longer vasa recta and more prominent plicae circulares
OptionC: The Ileum has a greater diameter and is thicker
OptionD: Only the Ileum is supplied by the Superior Mesenteric artery branches
OptionE: Only the Jejunum is supplied by the Ileocolic artery of the Superior Mesenteric Artery
Explanation:
A-Only true one

B-The opposite, the ileum has shorter vasa recta and less prominent plicae circulares

C-The opposite, the jejunum has a greater diameter and is thicker but the ileum has more mesenteric fat 

D-Both the ileum and jejunum are supplied by SMA branches

E-Only the ileum is supplied by the ileocolic artery; clue in the name.

Question: A 59-year-old woman with a longstanding history of GORD presents for follow-up evaluation of endoscopically confirmed gastric and duodenal ulcers. Her symptoms have been unresponsive to proton pump inhibitors and histamine receptor antagonists in the past. Results for H. pylori infection are still expected. Which of the following changes is expected in the patient's duodenum, given her peptic ulcer disease?
OptionD: Increased glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide (GIP) release from K cells
Explanation:
Hyperplasia of duodenal bicarbonate-secreting Brunner's glands is seen in peptic ulcer disease, which are found only in the duodenal submucosa. These tubular glands secrete alkaline mucus and neutralize acidic chyme from the stomach as it moves into the small intestine. Hyperplasia of Brunner's glands is occasionally seen with peptic ulcer disease (PUD).

 

The crypts of Lieberkühn are secretory glands present throughout the mucosa of both the small and large intestines.

 

K cells are present in the duodenum and jejunum. GIP is released in response to the presence of glucose, fatty acids, or amino acids, and is not related to PUD.
 

Peyer's patches are specific to the ileum only.

 

While secretin-releasing S cells are present in the duodenum and stimulate pancreatic HCO3 secretion in response to the presence of gastric acid; proliferation of these cells is not a characteristic of PUD.
Tags: Anatomy of Abdomen, Case 3, Histology, Physiology

Question: What is the distal attachment of teres minor?
OptionA: Superior facet of greater tubercle of humerus
OptionB: inferior facet of greater tubercle on humerus
Explanation:
A- distal attachment for supraspinatous 

B- distal attachment for teres minor

C- Distal attachment for deltoid tuberosity

D- Proximal attachment for teres minor

E- lateral attachment of trapezius, and posterior attachment for deltoid and probably some other muscles

 

LoVe AnAtOmY, LoVe LiFe. Not.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb, Case 1

Question:
Diana a 31 year-old patient is admitted into hospital with symptoms of involuntary contractions of her muscles. The doctor you are shadowing takes you to examine Diana and explains that she is suffering from hypocalcemia. 

What hormone is released to cause blood calcium levels to rise during normal calcium homeostasis?
Explanation:
Low plasma levels of calcium causes the parathyroid to release parathyroid hormone.

High plasma levels of calcium cause thyroid to release calcitonin

The involuntary muscle twitching the patient experiences is due to the role of calcium in muscle contraction.

A common cause of hypocalcemia is vitamin D deficiency, because it increases absorption of calcium in the GI tract

Question: A patient is presented to you with an alterations in consciousness.  On taking her history from her partner you discover that they have recently had a new boiler fitted. This leads you to a diagnosis of carbon monoxide poisoning.  Which complex in the electron transport chain does carbon monoxide inhibit?
Explanation:
Carbon monoxide poisoning not only prevents oxygen transport but also inhibits Cytrochrome C Oxidase (i.e. Complex IV).

 

Lecture: Releasing Energy From Food Using Oxygen (DR Shore 16/10/2014)

Question: The brain is a complex organ and is heavily in motor function of the body. Which of the following parts of the brain is most responsible for motor sequence learning?
Explanation: The basal ganglia is mots responsible for motor sequence learning; an example of this is learning to walk during infancy.
Tags: Anatomy, Nervous system, Case 6, muscle contraction

Question: The brain is very detailed and complex in controlling movement; a young neurologist is testing the function of a young child's brain and finds that they struggle to initiate their movement. Which part of this child's brain is likely damaged?
Explanation: Though the premotor cortex controls movement sequence and the preparation for movement, the SMA is most responsible for initiating and planning movement.

Question: A car accident leaves a 42 year old severely hurt in A&E. He states that he struggles to point his foot down and finds it unbearable to walk. Which of the following muscles is likely not affected by this damage?
Explanation: A-D are all muscles of the posterior compartment of the leg, innervated by the tibial nerve and act to plantarflex the foot (point the foot down) among other functions (i.e. tibialis posterior also inverts the foot). The tibias anterior muscle is innervated by the deep fibular nerve and acts to dorsiflex and invert the foot.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the upper limb, Case 1

Question: A 23 year old runner is sent to her musculoskeletal clinic. She complains of paraesthesia across her right heel and the underside of her right foot, with her big toe and 2nd and 3rd digits also in discomfort. The physician diagnoses tarsal tunnel syndrome-what nerve is most likely compressed that is causing these symptoms?
Explanation: The tibial nerve innervates the posterior leg compartment (both superficial and deep aspects) and is the nerve caught in compression by the flexor retinaculum posterior to the medial malleolus. This causes paraesthesia across the heel, plantar aspect of the foot and radiates to the hallux and 2nd and 3rd  digits.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb, Case 1

Question:
The severity of Respiratory disease can be assessed via arterial blood gases. 

 

What would be the most likely arterial blood gas data for a critically ill patient with severe COPD?
Explanation:
C - the ABG data shows respiratory acidosis and is suggestive of Type II respiratory failure. pH is low, PaO2 is low, PaCo2 is high and there is a normal Aa gradient

 

B- could also be ABG for COPD as it is suggestive of compensated respiratory acidosis because HCO3- is raised but pH is normal. This is likely to be the case in mild COPD NOT severe like the question asked. 

 

A - normal ABG data

 

D - uncompensated metabolic acidosis because pH raised. PaO2 and PaCo2 normal but Hco3- is raised.

Question: You see a patient who your consultant tells you has had an occlusion in a major cerebral artery. She is cannot eat, walk or talk as well as she could previously. What is the most likely occluded artery?
Explanation: The motor cortex, which is the main areas for above activities, is mostly supplied by the middle cerebral artery. The anterior cerebral artery supplies the the medial edge, but this is only a small proportion.

Question: Which of the following best describes the action of the superior oblique muscle?
Explanation: The superior oblique muscle of the orbit is involved in depression of the pupil in the abducted position (eg gazing down a page when the gaze of both eyes is directed medially)

Question: A 79 year old woman is admitted into the emergency room after she was found unconscious in her apartment. After she regained consciousness, a neuro exam indicated that she had suffered a stroke with paralysis to the R arm and leg, as well as loss of speech. What is the most likely region affected by this stroke that accounts for the limb paralysis ?
Explanation:
The Primary cortex is located in the precentral gyrus, which is organised somatotropically. The functions or the upper and lower limbs are represented in different regions along the precentral gyrus. 

 

I remember that "postcentral" has an s in it - represents the Primary somatosensory cortex, where as "precentral" is the motor area.

Question: A friend of yours falls over and cuts her hand, after a few days its starts to heal. You know there are a number of factors that can compromise wound healing. Which from the list below is not a compromising factor?
Explanation:
Systemic factors that compromise wound healing are:

  • Bad nutrition (vitamin C is needed to make collagen)
  • Circulatory status- poor perfusion is bad
  • Metabolic status
  • Hormones (glucocorticosteroids)- diabetes compromises

Local factors:

  • Infection (delays as more inflammation increases injury)
  • Mechanical factors (movement of area)
  • Foreign Bodies
  • Size, location and type of wound

Question: The cranial nerves are involved in sensory innervation for tastes via the nucleus solitarius; which of the following cranial nerves may be defined as the most responsible for taste sensation?
Explanation: Cranial nerve VII provides innervation to the anterior 2/3 of the tongue and CN IX to the posterior 1/3. As this is an SBA, B is thus the better of the two answers and thus would be deemed the most responsible.

Question: What is the anatomical position of the kidneys?
OptionB: The right inferior pole is covered by the 12th rib
OptionE: the left hilum passes through the transpyloric plane
Explanation:
A) - The kidneys lie on the posterior abdominal wall at the level of the T12-L3 vertebrae

B) - The right kidney lies slightly lower than the left and therefore the right inferior pole would definitely not be covered by the 12th rib which would be at T12-L1

C) - Too low for the kidneys although transplanted kidneys are often placed in this area (second best answer)

D) - The kidneys are retroperitoneal organs

E) The left hilum is at the level of the transpyloric plane (L1)

Question:
A woman enters your GP surgery and tells you she is concerned about her 14 year old girl. She is constantly hungry and quite short of stature, she will fight with other children for food and she has begun hoarding food. After examining the child you suspect the child has hypogonadism. She has also not had her first period. 

 

Which genetic abnormality best fits this description?
Explanation:
Leptin is a hormone associated with reducing appetite, it is also associated with puberty. A congenital lack of Leptin is believed to result in an absence of puberty (sexual maturation) and an unsatiable appetite. The child has hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, this is charateristic of leptin deficient patients. 

 

Another genetic condition resulting in hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism is Prader-Willi Syndrome (PWS). The symptoms are very similar to congenital leptin deficiency but the cause is different; a genetic defect on chromosome number 15 results in PWS.

Question: A young woman visits her optician complaining of double vision and sight problems. She is caucasian and the optician refers her to a neurologist straight away as he see nothing wrong with her eyes. What cell type is likely causing the pathology here?
Explanation: This is classic case of Multiple sclerosis (MS) as described by Dr Santer; oligodendrocytes can lead to degeneration of myelin in pathology that can causes a wide range of symptoms including double vision and sudden outbursts of pain. MS is the most common permanently disabling disorder of the central nervous system seen in young adults; it is most common in caucasian females. Of the subtypes of MS, relapsing-remitting is the most common of which typical symptoms include sensory, motor and coordination disturbances, optic neuritis, as well as fatigue. Importantly, the course of disease is highly variable. . Diagnosis and response to therapy can be assessed with MR imaging, which is the gold standard diagnostic tool.

Question: A smoker of 12 pack years is referred to a GP by his wife after developing a serious chronic cough. The GP determines that the patient has the first signs of COPD, with chronic bronchitis present. What metaplasia is one likely to see with regards to changes in respiratory epithelium?
Explanation: Cigarette smoke can be toxic to respiratory epithelium-pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium and may cause metaplasia of this epithelium to stratified non-keratinising epithelium, similar to that found in the mouth and the oesophagus. In chronic bronchitis, the cilia may be immobilised by the smoke and thus can cause an accumulation of mucus. the metaplasia change is often a first sign of squamous cell carcinoma.

Question: Which of the following is UNTRUE about the central executive component of working memory?
OptionA: It is located in the medial temporal lobe.
OptionB: It allocates data to the phonological loop subsystem.
OptionC: It can recall information from long term memory stores.
OptionD: It allocates data to the visuo-spatial sketchpad subsystem
OptionE: It can send information to long-term memory stores.
Explanation: The diagram below shows the functions of the central executive. A is wrong as it has no location, but is rather a collection of pathways.

Question: A man walks into clinic showing signs of foot drop; this means that he is unable to dorsiflex his foot-which nerve is most responsible for innervating the muscles that cause dorsiflexion of the foot?
Explanation: The deep fibular nerve innervates the anterior leg compartment; its four muscles can all act to dorsiflex the foot; to point your toes up. The tibial nerve is the nerve most responsible for plantarflexing-pointing toes down-the foot.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb, Nervous system, Case 1

Question:
You want to assess the catalytic efficiency of the Pepsin enzyme using the Michaelis Menton equation. 

 

What is the equation for the rate of catalysis of an enzyme?
Explanation:
V0 is the rate of reaction

 Kcat is the catalytic efficiency. Higher Kcat means more efficient enzyme and reflects max number of enzymalitical reactions per second.

Km is the [s] that is needed to achieve 1/2 Vmax

 

A is correct for this question

B is the correct equation for Kcat

C and D are made up ( I think) 

 

Any questions check out good old KhanAcademy  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7u2MkbsE_dw

Question:
To prevent muscle damage from over stretching and sense the positioning of the body your muscles you have receptors in your muscles and tendons which sent impulses back to the spinal cord. 

 

What structure detects changes in muscle tension?
Explanation:
Golgi tendon is structure in the tendons where dendrites from ib afferent sensory neurons wrap round collagen fibres and detect changes in muscle tension. They synapse with inhibitory interneurons to prevent over stretch. 

 

Muscle Spindles detect changes in muscle length with afferent fibres and dentrites within the muscle tissue. 

Ruffini's corpsule is a exteroreceptor in the dermis of the skin that responds to heat and sustained pressure

Merkels disk is another exteroreceptor in the epdermis of the skin which detects light touch.

Meisseners corpsule is in the dermis is very sensitive to brief touch. it can distinguish two different pin points.

Question: What causes the power stroke during muscle contraction?
OptionB: Hydrolysis of ATP to ADP and Pi
Explanation:
The hydrolysis of ATP form ADP + Pi, which pulls the myosin head back like a spring. Once the Pi is released from the myosin, this imitates releasing the spring which is essentially the power stroke.

 

ATP does not bind to the actin. The myosin head binds to the actin.
Tags: cell biology, cell function, Physiology, muscle contraction

Question: A young woman is having a cranial nerve examination when the neurologist tells her that one of the nerves emerging from the internal acoustic meatus has been damaged. Which of the following nerves is he most likely talking about?
Explanation:
The facial and vestibulocochlear cranial nerves emerge from the internal acoustic meatus (VII and VIII).

Vagus-jugular foramen

Glossopharyngeal-jugular foramen 

Abducens-Superior Orbital Fissure

Optic-Optic Canal

Question: A man has contracted severe sarcoidosis and is told that the condition has spread into his conductive airways. Where in the respiratory structure does the conducting zone end?
Explanation: The conducting zone of airways, generations 1-16 end at the terminal bronchioles; the transitional/respiratory bronchioles begin at the respiratory bronchioles-generations 17 to 23.
Tags: Anatomy, Lung function, Respiratory physiology, Case 5, Physiology

Question:
Prazosin is a alpha 1 adrenorecepter antagonist.

 

What is the likely  mechanism of action for this drug?

(also consider it's possible uses for a bonus point)
OptionA: Blocks Gs receptors leading to a fall in cAMP and a fall in heart rate and cardiac muscle contractility
OptionB: Aids activation of the Gs receptor leading to a rise in cAMP which inhibits myosin light chain kinase in smooth muscle in the lungs leading to bronchodilation.
OptionC: Blocks Gi receptors and leading to a rise in cAMP which inhibits myosin light chain kinase in smooth muscle in blood vessels leading the vasoconstriction and bronchoconstriction
OptionD: Blocks Gq receptor so reduces the IP3 production. This prevents smooth muscle contraction and leads to dilation of blood vessels
Explanation:
D is correct. Alpha 1 adrenoreceptors are in blood vessels and activation by noradrenaline causes a rise in IP3 which leads to a rise Ca+ which causes smooth muscle and bronchoconstriction. Hence Prazosin is an antagonist so blocks this pathway. Hence it is used to treat hypertension by lowing vascular resistance. 

 

A is a B1 antagonist such as Atenolol

B is a B2 agonist such as salbutamol

C is a B2 antagonist ( may be included in a non selective Beta blocker such as propanolol)
Tags: Nervous system, Case 6, Autonomic Nervous System

Question: In patients with diabetes endothelial dysfunction is common. What areas of blood vessels have decreased endothelial repairing abilities?
Explanation:
A is incorrect as there's decreased endothelial repair downstream of bifurcations.

D is correct as endothelial are exposed to disturbed shear stress.

E is incorrect as more so in hypertension.

B and C are irrelevant. 

Endothelial dysfunction likely to lead to atherosclerosis.
Tags: Blood Circulation, Functions of different tissues, Cardiology, case 4

Question: Whilst listening to a lecture you start to wonder how you are able to differentiate between the high and low pitched voices. You remember that is has something to do with how far pressure waves travel across the basilar membrane, and thus the hair cells stimulared. How would a low frequency sound be interpreted?
OptionA: Because the basilar membrane is taut at the end nearest to the oval membrane (base) and slack towards the terminal end (apex)the low frequency cannot travel very far.
OptionB: Because the basilar membrane is slack at the end nearest to the oval membrane (base) and taut towards the terminal end (apex) the low frequency cannot travel very far.
OptionC: Because the basilar membrane is taut at the end nearest to the oval membrane (base) and slack towards the terminal end (apex) the low frequency sounds travel the furthest.
OptionD: The structure of the basilar membrane is the same stiffness from the apex to the base, however low frequency sounds have more energy so travel further towards the terminal end.
Explanation:
As you can see in the diagram, the base of the basilar membrane is taut and thin, whilst the apex is more slack and wide. High frequency sounds cannot travel as far, whilst low frequency sounds travel further along the basilar membrane. As they travel the basilar membrane moves and causes the stereocilia of the hair cells to touch the tectorial membrane, this causes the opening of channels, and thus information to be sent along nearby afferent nerves. The area of the basilar membrane is therefore determined by the pressure waves, and the basilar membrane contains hair cells that detect different frequencies, allowing the sound to be interpreted by the brain differently.

As a side note the INTENSITY of the sound (or volume) is determined by the NUMBER of hair cells stimulated
Tags: Random, Brain, Case 6, anatomy of the ear

Question: The tympanic membrane has limited ability to hear frequencies of all sound waves. What unit of measurement is sound measured in and what is the range humans can hear?
Explanation:
This was detailed in Prof. Watsons lectures on the ear 

Sound is compromised of pressure changes in air particles, and is thought of as 'cyles of pressure' this is also known as frequency and is measured in Hetz (Hz). At birth the tympanic membrane has the ability to detect frequencies of 20-20,000Hz, however with environmental factors this diminishes with age.

Question: An athlete is involved in a half-marathon competition that results in her tearing her semitendinosus muscle in severe extension of her leg at the knee in eccentric contraction of the hamstrings muscles. She is informed that the tear is towards the origin of this muscle. Which of these is the correct origin of the semitendinosus muscle?
Explanation: The semitendinous and semimembranous muscle both originate from the ischial tuberosity, part of the hip. The biceps femoris long head originates from the ischial tuberosity and the short head originates from the linea aspera of femur.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of pelvis and perineum, Anatomy of the lower limb, Case 1

Question: Cholinesterase inhibitors are a class of drug that can be effective in reducing symptoms of certain types of dementia. Which type of dementia below is NOT IMPROVED by this class of drug?
Explanation:
Cholinesterase inhibitors increase neural levels of CNS ACh, which increases the activity of cholinergic brain networks, to temporarily improve or stabilize memory or thinking skills.

They are effective in Alzheimer's, Lewy body dementia and Parkinson's disease dementia but not Vacular dementia or fronto-temporal dementia.
Tags: Nervous system, Neurotransmitters, Brain, Pharmacology, Case 6

Question: Mrs. Jones is an 86 year old women, she lives independently in her community and comes to see you with symptoms of memory loss, hallucinations, muscle spasms and numbness/ tingling in her hands and feet. She admits that recently she has had trouble going shopping regularly and cooking at home and so has been increasingly been relying on processed foods. Which of the following mineral deficiencies would explain her symptoms?
Explanation:
Hypocalcemia symptoms include: (see Andrew Shore's lecture; essential mineral and vitamins from PCS)

Osteoporosis
Memory loss
Muscle spasms
Numbness and tingling in hands and feet and face
Depression
Hallucinations

Question: There are many forms of vitamin D, involving a series of conversions which result in the regulation of calcium. Of the following forms which is responsible for the release of calcium and phosphorus from reserves such as bone through the action of osteoclasts?
OptionC: 25-hydroxyvitamin D (25 (OH) D) this is also known as Calcifediol
OptionD: 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin d (1,25 (OH) D) this is also known as calcitrol
Explanation:
D is the correct answer, this website gives an excellent explanation about the synthesis of 1,25 (OH)2 from its precursor
ANSWER A- this is formed from the precursor of vitamin D (7-dehydrocholesterol) through the action of sunlight

ANSWER B- This is the form of vitamin D we can obtain from plant resources, however provided you have adequate exposure to sunlight, dietary supplements of vitamin D are not needed

ANSWER C- 25(OH)D is formed from 7-dehydrocholesterol in the liver

ANSWER D- this is through further modification of 25(OH)D in the kidney, this is the activated form of vitamin D

ANSWER E- this is the precursor of vitamin D found in the skin, which is activated by sunlight.
Tags: Nutrition, Lectures, Vitamins and Minerals, PCS

Question: Which of the flowing structures passes through the lesser sciatic foramen?
Explanation: The obturator interns muscle tendon is the best answer, as although the pudendal nerve also passes through the lesser sciatic foramen, it also passes through the greater sciatic foramen below the piriformus.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb, Case 1, Random

Question: A 62-year-old man sustains an intracranial injury to a nerve that also passes through the parotid gland. Which of the following is a possible consequence of this injury?
OptionA: Loss of sensation from anterior 2/3 of the tongue
OptionB: Loss of taste from posterior 1/3 of the tongue
OptionD: Inability to abduct eye from the midline of the eye
Explanation:
Cranial nerve (CN) VII passes through the parotid gland (BUT DOES NOT INNERVATE) and also innervates the stapedius muscle in the ear. 

The facial nerve (CN VII) exits the skull via the internal acoustic meatus and provides the following innervations/functions: muscles of facial expression, stapedius, stylohyoid, posterior belly of digastric, TASTE (but not sensation) from anterior 2/3 of tongue, salivation (submandibular and sublingual glands), and lacrimation.

The stapedius muscle dampens the stapes, one of the 3 bones of the inner ear and the smallest bone in the human body. By dampening the stapes, the stapedius muscle protects the inner ear from loud sounds. Loss of function of the stapes results in increased sensitivity to sound, known as hyperacusis.

A-CN V3, the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve, transmits sensation, BUT NOT TASTE, from anterior 2/3 of tongue. The chorda tympani branch of the Facial Nerve (CN VII) provides taste sensation to the anterior 2/3 of the tongue.

B-CN IX, the glossopharyngeal nerve, transmits taste from the posterior 1/3 of tongue

D-CN VI, the abducens nerve, innervates the lateral rectus muscle.

E-Horner's syndrome is ptosis, miosis, a sunken eye  and anhydrosis resulting from loss of sympathetic innervation to the face, which may occur due to lesions of the superior cervical ganglion, compression by a mediastinal mass, or damage to the nerve in the posterior retroparotid space as by a parotid tumor
Tags: Cranial Nerves, Nervous system, Neuroanatomy, Functions of different tissues, Case 6

Question: A 45-year-old man is brought to A&E after being found down in the middle of the street. Witnesses reported to the police that they had seen the man as he exited a local bar, where he was subsequently assaulted. He sustained severe facial trauma, including multiple lacerations and facial bone fractures.  Several days later, he complains of the inability to open his mouth wide or to completely chew his food, both of which he seemed able to do prior to surgery he had on the night of the attack. Where does the affected nerve exit the skull?
Explanation:
Thee man  likely suffered an iatrogenic injury to the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve. CNV3 exits the skull via the foramen ovale.

The divisions of the trigeminal nerve exit the skull via the superior orbital fissue (CNV1), the foramen rotundum (CNV2), and the foramen ovale (CNV3). CNV3 is composed of both motor and sensory components, the motor of which are responsible for the muscles of mastication. Injury to CNV3 would produce symptoms as presented in the question stem.
Tags: Cranial Nerves, Nervous system, Neuroanatomy, Case 6

Question: You and your friend are running late to lectures one day. Just outside of the lecture theater, your friend is hit in the back by a fast-moving bicycle. A few days later, you notice that she has hip drop on walking, and also she cannot stabilize her left knee properly when standing up. You suspect damage to which nerve?
Explanation: The superior gluteal nerve supplies the gluteus medius and minimus, which prevent hip drop when walking, and it also supplies the tensor fascia latae, which stabalizes the knee in extension. The roots of this nerve are L4 and L5.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb, Nervous system, Case 1, muscle contraction

Question:
A consultant asks you to perform an eye examination on one of his patients.  On carrying out the examination, you ask the patient to look to their right... this is what you see.

 

 

Which nerve is mostly like to be affected?
Explanation: This particular picture shows abducens nerve palsy (or sixth cranial nerve palsy).  It is caused by a lesion of the abducens nucleus in the pons or by compression of the peripheral course of the nerve by an aneurysm or spacing occupying tumour.  It leads to an inability to move the eye outwards... i.e. abduct the eye.

Question: A 55 year old man comes into hospital with a suspected myocardical infarction. An ECG is performed which indicates an ST elevation. This elevation is in leads V1 to V4. Which artery is involved?
Explanation: If V1-V4 have ST elevation the MI has occurred in the anterior or anteroseptal area of the heart. The LAD supplies this region of the heart.

Question: Which cranial nerve supplies taste to the anterior two thirds of the tongue?
Explanation: The vagus nerve supplies taste from the epiglottis whereas the glossopharyngeal nerve supplies the posterior third of the tongue. The hypoglossal nerve supplies the intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue

Question: Which cranial nerve leaves the skull via the cribiform plate?
Explanation: Hypoglossal exits the skull from the hypoglossal canal, the optic via the optic canal, the oculomotor and trochlear via the superior orbital fissure

Question: What does the inferior, superior, medial rectus as well as the inferior oblique do to the eyeball?
Explanation: This action is supplied by the oculomotor cranial nerve. The superior oblique muscle rotates the eyeball downwards and medially and the lateral rectus muscle abducts the eye

Question: A woman comes in with a bilateral loss of the temporal visual field. What could be causing her this visual deficit?
OptionA: Lesion of the retina or optic nerve before the chiasm
OptionC: A lesion in the lateral geniculate nucleus
Explanation: The chiasm sits over the pituitary and so tumours in this structures can compress the chiasm which would prevent transmission in the crossing fibres.

Question: Most of the tongue extrinsic and intrinsic muscles are innervated by CN XII; which of the following muscles is not?
Explanation: The hypoglossal nerve, which emerges from the hypoglossal canal, innervates all the extrinsic and intrinsic tongue muscles bar the palatoglossus muscle, innervated by the vagus nerve. The extrinsic muscles are the genioglossus, hypoglossus, styloglossus and the palatoglossus muscles. The intrinsic muscles include the superior and inferior longitudinal muscles, and the transverse and vertical muscles.

Question: The facial nerve has five terminal branches that emerge from the parotid gland. Which of these is not one of the terminal branches of the Facial nerve?
Explanation: The cervical branch is the terminal branch missing; the chorda tympani is a branch that comes off earlier and provides taste sensation to the anterior 2/3 of the tongue.

Question: A young man reacts with fear upon seeing a snake; which part of the brain is most responsible for coordinating the emotion of the man into his response of being frightened?
Explanation:
The amygdala of the brain is most responsible for the emotional response, via implicit/non-declarative memory. This is a type of associative learning; the skeletal musculature response (e.g. running away from the snake) would be from the cerebellum.

Hippocampus-Mainly responsible for storage of explicit/declarative memory-particularly episodic.

Neocortex-responsible for priming (type of implicit/non-declarative memory) and stable Long term memory-remote memory.

Striatum-storage of procedural habits (brushing teeth etc)-type of implicit/ non-declarative memory

Question: The toxic product of the anaerobic bacterium Clostridium botulinum, botulinum toxin, is associated with food poisoning and a resulting flaccid paralysis. What is the mechanism underlying botulinum toxin action?
OptionA: Blocks adrenergic synaptic transmission, leading to reduced noradrenaline release into the synapse.
OptionB: The heavy chain of the toxin cleaves V and T SNARES, leading to impaired fusion of cholinergic ACh vesicles to the presynaptic membrane.
OptionC: Blocks cholinergic synaptic transmission via its light chain which cleaves V and T snares, preventing ACh from being released into the synapse.
OptionD: Toxin binds to post synaptic ACh receptor sites, reducing transmission of ACh.
OptionE: Toxin binds to inhibitory interneurones of the spinal cord, and blocks their release of inhibitory neurotransmitters.
Explanation:
- Botulinum toxin blocks cholinergic synaptic transmission at the central and peripheral nervous systems.

- Botulinum toxin binds to a receptor on the pre-synaptic membrane.

- It is internalised in a vesicle

- The light chain of the toxin is released into the cytoplasm which cleaves the V and T SNAREs

- Fusion of these vesicles containing ACh is impaired

- No ACh is released into the synapse ---> flaccid paralysis 

 

E is the mechanism of Tetanus. The others are made up.
Tags: Nervous system, Neurotransmitters, Pharmacology, muscle contraction

Question: How does Noradrenaline cause smooth muscle relaxation?
OptionA: Via Beta-2 receptors: activates Gs which leads to Protein Kinase A inactivating Myosin Light Chain Kinase
OptionB: Via Alpha-1 receptors: activates Gs which leads to Protein Kinase A inactivating Myosin Light Chain Kinase
OptionC: Via Alpha-1 receptors: activate Gq leading to an increase in IP3, increasing Calcium levels in the cell
OptionD: Via M3 Muscarinic Receptor: Activates Gq leading to an increase in IP3, increasing Calcium levels in the cell
OptionE: Via beta-2 receptors: Activates Gi leading to depleted levels of Protein kinase A, which increases activation of myosin phosphatase
Explanation:
NA binds to the beta-2 receptor. A conformational change causes the Gs-alpha subunit to cleave and bind to adenyl cyclase, activating it. ATP is converted to cAMP which activates protein kinase A. Protein kinase A causes inactivation of myosin light chain kinase, and activation of myosin light chain phosphatase. This results in relaxation of the cell. 

 

Alpha-1 receptors bind NA to cause smooth muscle contraction. NA binds to Gq, this activates Phospholipase C which leaves PIP2 in to IP3 and DAG. IP3 interact with calcium channels of the endoplasmic reticulum, causing a release of calcium into the cell; and therefore the cell contracts.
Tags: Nervous system, Neurotransmitters, Pharmacology, muscle contraction

Question: Many drugs such as Statins, as well as Carbon Monoxide act as competitive enzyme inhibitors. What is the effect of competitive inhibitors on the values of Km and Vmax?
Explanation:
- Competitive inhibitors bind directly to the active site of the enzyme

- The substrate is therefore blocked from binding

- This reduces the enzyme's affinity for the substrate. Km is therefore increased. 

- Vmax does not change because you can add more substrate to overcome the effect of the competitive inhibitor. 

- On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, the X-intercept would therefore change, but the Y-intercept will stay the same.

Question: Non-competetive enzyme inhibitors bind at a site other than the active site. What happens to the values of Km and Vmax in the enzyme kinetics in this situation?
Explanation:
- As non-competitive inhibitors bind to a site other than the active site, the enzymes conformation is changed. 

- The enzyme can have both the substrate and inhibitor bound at the same time. Therefore the enzyme-substrate complex is able to form and there is no reduced affinity for the substrate-  Km stays the same. 

- The enzyme-substrate complex cannot make any product, so the Vmax is lowered. 

- On a lineweaver-burk plot the observed changes would be a change in the Y-intercept and no change in the X-intercept. 

- Cannot overcome the effect by adding more substrate because the enzyme-substrate complex can still form.

Question: An woman with frequent gastrointestinal complaints undergoes a bowel biopsy.  The pathologist observes that submucosal glands of Brunner are present in the specimen used for the biopsy? Which portion of the GI tract was most likely biopsied?
Explanation:
The duodenum is part of the small intestine contains the submucosal glands of Brunner, which secrete alkaline mucous.

 

It is worth knowing that only the duodenum and esophagus contain glands in the submucosal layer of the GI tract.

 

Secretions from Brunner's glands pass into the crypts of Lieberkuhn and are released into the lumen. Brunner's glands secrete neutral and alkaline glycoproteins and bicarbonate ions, a mixture that neutralizes the acidic chyme arriving in the duodenum from the stomach; in a way this supplements that bicarbonate secretions from the ducts cells, stimulated by secretin released by S cells in the duodenum. The increase in the pH protects the duodenum and brings the pH closer to the range needed for proper functioning of the pancreatic enzymes of digestion.
Tags: Anatomy, Functions of different tissues, Gastrointestinal System, Histology, Case 3

Question: A young man curious about hearing asks a GP to explain how hearing works; he is curious to know how man layers of outer hair cells and inner cells there are-which is the correct reply?

OptionB: 2 inner cell rows, 2 outer cell rows
OptionC: 1 inner cell row, 3 outer cell rows
OptionD: 2 inner cell rows, 3 outer cell rows

Question:
Mr Grange, a 40 year old man presents to your GP surgery with balding, reduced muscle mass and strength, and decreased energy. You struggle after rigorous history taking to come up with a plausible explanation for this. You have a look back over his notes and discover that in childhood, Mr Grange suffered with growth hormone (GH) insufficiency in childhood as a result of a pituitary tumour which was later removed. You are concerned that this tumour may have come back. 

 

GH insufficiency in adults is rare, but may lead to which condition?

Which hormone has a stimulatory effect on GH in the pituitary?
OptionC: Addison's disease. Gonadotrophin releasing hormone increases GH production.
OptionD: Acromegaly. Gonadotrophin releasing hormone increases GH production.
Explanation:
GH insufficiency has no major symptoms in adults but may lead to hypoglycemia. This is because GH usually causes a release of glucose from tissues, and production of new glucose in the liver by gluconeogenesis. 

 

GH insufficiency in children leads to pituitary dwarfism. These children have normal body proportions, but poor muscle development and excess subcutaneous fat. 

 

Ghrelin (produced by the stomach) and GnRH have a stimulatory effect on GH in the anterior pituitary. Somatostatin inhibits release of GH and is used in treatment of GH excess.

Question: The organ of corti is vitally important in control and coordination of hearing in the body; which of the following parts of the organ is best described as the container of endolymph?

Question: Whilst in histology class you observe the myocardium layer of a section of cardiac tissue, which is made up of cardiac muscle cells.You are informed that cardiac muscle cells have several properties such as being smaller than skeletal muscle cells, having one centrally located nucleus and being joined via intercalated discs. Adherins: these attach the thin filaments of the sacromere to the cell membrane 

 

Hemidesmasomes: not present in cardiac muscle ,hemidesmosomes are asymmetrical and are found in epithelial cells connecting the basal face of the cell to basal lamina. They are found in keratanocytes

Question: The principle organs involved in Ca2+ metabolism are the gut, kidney and bone. The hormone PTH (Parathyroid hormone) is released to increase serum calcium levels. What are the direct effects of PTH on the 3 organs mentioned
OptionA: Stimulate absorption of Ca from the gut, Stimulate the excretion of Ca from the kidneys, Stimulate osteoclast activity
OptionB: No direct effect on the gut, Stimulate the excretion of calcium from the kidneys, stimulate osteoblast activity
OptionC: No direct effect on the gut, Stimulate the reabsorption of calcium by the kidneys, stimulate osteoclast activity
OptionD: Stimulate calcium absorption from the gut, stimulate the reasborption of calcium by the kidneys, stimulate osteoclast activity
Explanation:
PTH works to increase Ca serum levels by

- Promoting the reabsorption of it in the distal tubules 

- Stimulating the work of the bone- breakers (osteoclasts) 

 

It has no direct effect on absorption from the gut!!

It has an indirect effect by stimulating the renal hormone that activates calcitriol 1,25(OH)2D which is the active protein in the Vitamin D pathway. It is the calcitriol that stimulates gut absorption of calcium.

Question: One litre of Dextrose 5% in water is charted over 8 hours. The drop factor is 10. Calculate the number of drops per minute.
Explanation:
Rate of IV infusion: 

 

(total volume (ml))/total time (hours) x drip factor of set/60

 

total volume = 1000ml

total time = 8 hours

drip factor = 10

 

Or logically: 

- We want the hours in minutes so need to convert 8 hours to minutes: 8x60 = 480 minutes. 

- Next, we know our set gives 10 drips per ml so we can work out how many drips it will take to deliver 1000ml: 10x1000 = 10000 drips. 

- Now we have drops and minutes so drops per minute = 10000/480 = 20.83

Question:
When you fall and bang your knee there are various pain modulation mechanisms to control the pain. The periaqueductal Grey is thought to be activated when you have positive expectations about the effects of a particular treatments. Hence pain is reduces.

Question: Which of the following statements is FALSE about DNA replication?
OptionA: Okazaki fragments are formed from small RNA primers on the lagging strand
OptionB: DNA ligase seals the final knicks in-between the fragments of DNA on the lagging strand
OptionC: DNA is always replicated in a 5' to 3' direction
OptionD: Single stranded binding protein prevents hairpins forming once Helicase has unwound the strands
OptionE: DNA polymerase III is used on both the leading and lagging strand to build DNA
Explanation:
DNA replication: 

 

1. Helicase unwinds DNA, breaking the H-bonds. It begins in the origin of replication

2. Single-stranded binding protein (SSBP) prevents hairpins from forming

3. DNA primase is needed at the site of replication, so polymerase can begin replication 

4. DNA polymerase III follows helicase and builds DNA from a 5' to 3' direction 

5. On the lagging strand, DNA primes attaches near to the helicase, and follows Helicase backwards as it unwinds DNA

6. DNA primase makes RNA primers

7. DNA polymerase III fills in the gaps in between the RNA primers. These small DNA fragments which DNA polymerase builds are called okazaki fragments. --> Okazaki fragments are NOT formed from RNA primers as stated by answer A. 

8. DNA polymerase I converts the RNA primers into DNA

9. DNA ligase seals the knicks, making a stable DNA strand.

Question: A young Mixed Martial Artist see his GP the day after a 3 round fight. He reports severe numbness in his left leg and examination of his leg suggest a foot drop. The fighter says that he took a lot of hits to his knee throughout all 3 rounds. Which nerve has most likely been damaged in this person?
Explanation:
The brief history is typical of peroneal nerve damage, meaning the common fibular nerve is most likely the one damaged. though damage to the deep fibular nerve is also a possibility.

This type of injury typically involves a strong force to the knee or just below, chronic compression at the fibula head or peripheral neuropathy can cause damage to the common/deep fibular nerve. This causes foot drop, meaning that the muscle of the anterior leg compartment cannot dorsiflex (point toes up) the foot. Sensory loss of the dorsal foot surface and lateral distal leg is also common. 

Since this is an SBA, B and D are the most likely answers; what gives B the edge is the mechanism of injury. The knee is clearly the area hit, which is where the common fibular (more lateral) and tibial nerves comes off the sciatic nerve.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb, Nervous system, Case 1

Question: Anna presents to her GP with complaints of a tight chest pain upon exertion which eases with rest. She says she is asthmatic, so the doctor gives her Ivabradine as an alternative to a Beta-Blocker. What is the mechanism of action of the drug?
OptionA: Liberates NO in the body which activates guanylyl cyclase to convert GTP to cGMP activating PKG which lowers intracellular calcium and phosphorylates and inactivates MLCK for smooth muscle relaxation and vasodilation.
OptionB: Diffuses through the membrane and binds to the intracellular part of calcium channels causing a conformational change to inactivate the channels thus cause a negative inotropic and negative chronotropic effects on the heart and cause vasodilation.
OptionC: Binds to B1-adrenoceptors in the heart to competitively inhibit the bidning of adrenaline or NA which prevents activation of adenylyl cyclase thus cAMP production would activate PKA to phosphorylate and open L-type calcium channels - it therefore has negative inotropic and chronotropic effects.
OptionD: Activates guanylyl cyclase to liberate cGMP thus PKG causing smooth muscle relaxation and vasodilation as in A.
OptionE: Inhibits the mixed Na-K inward current which generates the 'funny current' in SA nodes to begin depolarisation - it therefore reduces the rate of depolarisation thus having a negative chronotropic effect on the heart.
Explanation:
A is the action of organic nitrates such as glyceryl trinitrate (GTN) or isosorbide mononitrate

B is a calcium channel block such as verapamil

C is a beta-blocker such as propranolol

D is the action of nicorandil

E is the action of ivabradine

Question: A young man reports to the GP with severe depression, saying that it is because of his recent weight gain. You measure his height at 167cm, and mass at 89kg-what is his BMI, to 1 decimal place?
Explanation: BMI is calculated by mass in kg divided by height in metres squared. D is thus equal to 89/1.672 =31.9 kg/m2 to 1 dp. Underweight is under 18.5, normal is 18.5 to under 25, overweight is 25 to 30, obese is over 30 and morbid obesity is over 40.
Tags: Gastrointestinal System, Health Psychology, Health Sociology, Case 3

Explanation:
UGT1A1 deletion or mutation, therefore bilirubin cannot be conjugated hence build up of unconjugated bilirubin, resulting in jaundice in the patient (Coffey, 2015)

Question: Which of the pairs of CYP450 enzymes take part in the CYP pathway of paracetamol metabolism, and what is the name of the toxic species produced, and how does the body get rid of it (the toxic substance)
Explanation: None of the above. CYP2E1 and CYP1A2 are responsible for the CYP pathway of paracetamol metabolism. N-acetyl-p-benzoquinone imine (NAPBQI) is the toxic species produced. its gotten rid off by conjugation with glutathione. okaybye.

Question: It has been found that, at its peak, Ndaba's voice can reach a sound intensity of 120 dB. For how long is it safe to be exposed to this intensity of sound in one day?
OptionE: It is not safe to be exposed to this much sound at all...Ndaba should keep his mouth shut
Explanation: At 85 dB (considered to be the start of the 'danger zone') safe exposure time is 8 hours. For every 3 dB increase in sound intensity the safe exposure time halves (or decreases by a factor of 10 for every 10 dB increase). Following this method, safe exposure time for 120 dB is roughly 7 seconds. This is not to be confused with dB measurements for sound pressure level (dB SPL) for which a 6 dB increase represents a doubling in pressure and a 20 dB increase represents a tenfold increase in pressure.

Question:
As a young F1 doctor you are told by your consultant to review a patient who has Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome (ZES). Luckily you had just read up on this condition the night before and are able to recall that it is caused by a gastrinoma and patients present with various symptoms including diarrhoea and vomiting blood.

Unfortunately for you the consultant is not interested in the symptoms you memorised in the Oxford Clinical Handbook and instead wants to know how gastrin indirectly causes HCl release.

What is your reply?
OptionA: acts on P cells to stimulate release of histamine which induces H+ secretion in parietal cells
OptionB: acts on ECL cells to stimulate release of histamine which induces H+ secretion in chief cells
OptionC: acts on ECL cells to stimulate release of somatostatin which induces H+ secretion in chief cells
OptionD: acts on D cells to stimulate release of histamine which induces H+ secretion in parietal cells
OptionE: acts on ECL cells to stimulate release of histamine which induces H+ secretion in parietal cells
Explanation:
Gastrin indirectly causes H+ release by binding to CCK2 receptors on ECL (enterochromaffin like) cells which stimulates the release of histamine. Histamine acts on parietal cells to cause release of H+ into the lumen of the stomach

Gastrin also has a direct effect by inducing insertion of K+/H+ ATPase pumps onto apical membrane of parietal cells

Jo presents to her GP concerned that she is at risk of a heart attack after her mother recently suffered an MI. The GP explains to her that a high risk factor of atherosclerosis is high blood pressure. With high risk being around 130/80.  You are a medical student and the GP asks you to calculate the pulse pressure from this and then the mean arterial pressure. What are the correct values for these.
Explanation:
PULSE PRESSURE: this is calculated by (systolic)- (diastolic), in this case this is (130)- (80)= 50

MEAN PRESSURE: this is 1/3 of the pulse pressure (calculated above as 50) + the diastolic pressure, in this case (1/3(50)) + (80)= 97

What muscle within the fascial coverings of the spermatic cord contracts reflexively in the cold to draw up the testes?

The cremastor muscle forms loops within the cremestaric fascia it is forned from the internal oblique. 

 

Dartos muscle will assist with in the movement however it is a smooth muscle which forms part of the scrotum not a fascial covering.

 

The external oblique forms the external spermatic fascia from its aponeurosis

Question:
Hernias can be acquired or congenital. This shows a congenital hernia. 

 

What is another name for it?
Explanation:
The two types of inguinal Hernias are Direct and Indirect. 

 

Indirect is congenital due to an internal opening of the inguinal canal after birth. This allows the herniating bowel to pass through the deep inguinal ring  (lateral to the epigastric vessels) with the spermatic cord through the canal and into the scrotum. 

 

Direct Inguinal hernias are acquired during adulthood due to a weakness in the anterior abdominal wall. The herniating bowel passes medial to the epigastric vessels through the peritoneum in the inguinal triangle but usually doesnt descend into the scrotum. This is less common, 1/3 of inguinal hernias.
Tags: Sexual Health, Anatomy of pelvis and perineum, Case 2, Puberty

Question: Which of the following drugs acts to inhibit the P2Y12 ADP receptor on platelets to prevent platelets aggregation, which may be given in the case of a STEMI?
Explanation:
Fondaparinux is a synthetic pentasaccharide which is an indirect thrombin inhibitor which acts like heparin to bind to antithrombin causing a conformational change to expose the active site to allowing it to inhibit thrombin IXa and Xa

Bivalirudin is a direct thrombin inhibitor which binds to thrombin and inhibits its active site and substrate recognition site to prevent activation of fibrinogen to fibrin

Clopidogrel and Ticagrelor are thienopyridines which both inhibit P2Y12 ADP receptors on platelets but Clopidogrel must be activated by CYP 450 enzymes in the liver so is not used in the case of STEMI as it may have poor metabolism if single nucleotide polymorphisms are present

Abciximab is a glycoprotein IIb/IIIa inhibitor which prevents binding of platelets to vWF, fibronectin and fibrinogen which allows platelet adhesion and aggregation

Question: Which of the following nerves does NOT exit the skull via the superior orbital fissure?
Explanation: The maxillary nerve CN V2 exits the nerve via the foramen rotundum

Question: Which of the following strains of the Hepatitis virus is NOT an RNA virus?
Explanation: Hep B is the only virus that is a DNA virus. It is blood bourne virus and can be sexually transmitted.

Question: A patient presents to you a with a right eye that has a downward and outward gaze, a drooping superior eyelid and a dilated pupil which does not constrict when you shine a light at it. The left eye appears normal on examination. This is likely to be a complete lesion of which nerve?
Explanation:
A complete lesion of CN III causes a 'down and out' appearance in one eye, because of the unopposed action of the lateral rectus and superior oblique muscles, with signs of ptosis (a drooping eyelid) and no pupillary reflex (no constriction when a light is shone at it). The patient has dilation of the pupil because there is interruption of parasympathetic fibres to the sphincter pupillae, leaving the dilator pupillae unopposed. There is also no accommodation of the lens as the ciliary muscle is paralysed.

a lesion in CN IV would cause double vision (diplopia)

a lesion of CN VI would causes medial deviation of the affected eye
Tags: Eye, Case 6, Clinical Skills, Cranial Nerves

Question: Your encounter a patient who has suffered from an MI and take a look at his ECG. He has deviating waves in leads II, III,  avF and V2. Which of the following places in the heart is the area where there is most likely an occlusion?
Explanation: II, III and aVF are leads that correspond to the inferior part of the heart, while V2 corresponds to the septal part of the heart; as there is not option for inferior septal area, then inferior seems like the best answer given that there are more leads corresponding to the inferior part of the heart.

Elevated FSH and LH in response to the LHRH stimulation test.

Question: Which of the following is an exopeptidase (can break terminal peptide bonds)?
Explanation:
The correct answer is Carboxypeptidase (D). This is an exopeptidase meaning it can cleave terminal peptide bonds. All the other options are endopeptidases and so can only cleave internal peptide bonds.

All the enzymes mentioned are enzymes that break down protein. Pepsin is the only enzyme that breaks down protein during gastric phase. The rest work during Pancreatic phase.

 

List of Zymogen --> enzyme

Pepsinogen --> Pepsin

Trypsinogen --> Trypsin (activated by enteropepsidase)

Chymotrypsinogen --> Trypsin (activated by trypsin)
