This was mentioned in Jeff's lecture about digestion and absorption in PCS 2 Week 7.

Question: You are studying bone cells when an inquiring professor asks what cells are osteocytes directly formed from-what is the best answer to this question?
Explanation: Osteoblast, which secrete the organic bone matrix of bone (osteoid) and collagen of bone, are termed osteocytes when they become trapped within the bone matrix. Osteoblasts are differentiated from osteoprogenitor cells (bone stem cells) and the role of osteocytes is to maintain bone tissue and form gap junctions with other osteocytes. Osteoclasts reabsorb bone, while chondroblasts and chrondrocytes are involved in cartilage production and maintenance.

Question: A 26 years old lady came into the GP clinic having amenorrhea, abdominal pain and intermittent bleeding. the GP diagnosed that she is likely to have ectopic pregnancy. Which of the following sites is the usual site of fertilisation?
Explanation: The upper third of the oviduct (ampulla) is the most common site where fertilisation occurs within the 24 hours of ovulation. It has a wide, convoluted thin wall with large surface area and can control the movement of the zygote. Endometrium and Myometrium is not the site where fertilisation occurs/ not part of the fallopian tube. Whereas the other two answers is not a common site for fertilisation. Most of the ectopic pregnancy occurs in the isthmus and ampulla.

Question: A 28-year-old male visits his GP because of fertility issues with his wife. Physical exam reveals bilateral gynaecomastia, elongated limbs, and shrunken testicles. Levels of plasma gonadotropins-FSH and LH- are elevated. Which of the following is also likely to be increased in this patient?
Explanation:
The clinical presentation is consistent with Klinefelter syndrome (of 47, XXY), which is characterized by elevated aromatase and is caused by a karyotype of two or more X chromosomes due to nondisjunction or translocation during meiosis.

Patients with Klinefelter syndrome have decreased testosterone levels due to Leydig cell dysfunction. Loss of Sertoli cells also occurs, and leads to decreased levels of inhibin. Thus plasma gonadotropin levels increase due to a lack of negative feedback. The increase in serum FSH up-regulates aromatase, which leads to increased conversion of testosterone to oestrogen. The estrogen:testosterone ratio is highly correlated to the degree of feminization in patients with Klinefelter syndrome, that is displayed in what the GP saw in the PE.
Tags: Anatomy, Sexual Health, Genetics, Case 2, Puberty

Question: A teenage mum just gave birth to a baby boy and you are a year1 medical student standing in the room. She turned towards you with curiosity and asked what caused her to produce and secrete milk when her baby started suckling on her nipples. With your knowledge from PCS Unit3, you answered...
Explanation: Suckling activates the mechanoreceptors in the nipples. This sends a signal to the hypothalamus, then to the posterior pituitary gland which secretes the hormone oxytocin involved in milk ejection. Progesterone and Oestrogen prevents lactation until after birth.
Tags: PCS, Hormones, hormonal control, Pregnancy, reproductive system

Question:
What does the following karyotype represent? 

47,XX,+21
Explanation: A karyotype is recorder as: number of chromosomes, identity of sex chromosomes, anomalies. Down's syndrome is a trisomy mutation with an extra copy of chromosome 21.

Question: Energy in metabolism is a complex topic and can involve a wide variety of molecules. Which of these is most true about energy metabolism in the given situations?
OptionA: During a 100m sprint, oxidative phosphorylation is the primary energy resource used to provide energy to the skeletal muscles of the athlete
OptionB: Running 800m flat uses glycogen as the main energy store for the body's skeletal muscles
OptionC: A half-marathon uses oxidative phosphorylation as the prime energy resource throughout
OptionD: The brain in metabolism is considered an insulin sensitive organ
OptionE: Red blood cells can only ever use glucose for ATP generation
Explanation:
A-A 100m sprint is a short burst of energy that is usually over before oxidative phosphorylation can take part to provide the body with ATP. In most cases, pre-synthesised ATP, creatine phosphate and anaerobic glycolysis are the main processes that provide ATP to make you sprint as fast as you can for 15 seconds or less.

B-Oxidative Phosphorylation is usually sufficient enough to provide energy to one going from over 100m to 1km; glycogen may begin to be used towards the end of this time but it would not be the 'main' energy resource.

C-The opposite of B; oxidative phosphorylation is used for the first part of the half-marathon and may be used throughout the race but after about 1km, your body will begin to use glycogen reserves and Beta-oxidation of fatty acids to primarily provide your ATP needs over a long period of time.

D-The opposite; the brain is considered an insulin resistant organ; the main places where insulin acts is  hepatocytes, adipocytes and myocytes.

E-Erhthrocytes have no nucleus or mitochondria; oxidative phosphorylation and beta oxidation cannot take place so glucose can be the only molecule used by the cell to generate ATP.
Tags: Biochemistry, Nutrition, Blood Cells, Blood Circulation

Question: The human body's nervous system has many support cells. Which of the these support cells is only found in the peripheral nervous system?
Explanation: A schwann cell is only found in the PNS and is reasonable for myelin formation and the formation of the nodes of ranvier. All the others are found in the CNS.

Question: Which of the following best describes a Robertsonian translocation?
OptionA: Fusion of between long arms of sub-metacentric chromosomes with loss of short arms
OptionB: Fusion of between long arms of metacentric chromosomes with loss of short arms
OptionC: Fusion of between short arms of sub-metacentric chromosomes with loss of long arms
OptionD: Fusion of between long arms of acrocentric chromosomes with loss of short arms
OptionE: Fusion of between short arms of sub-metacentric chromosomes with loss of long arms
Explanation:
A robertsonian translocation is the fusion of long arms of acrocentric chromosomes (the ones with a very short p arm). This means that the short arms are lost. A person with this mutation is unaffected because there is no significant net loss/gain of genetic material. However their offspring will be at risk of net loss/gain.

See Dr Sweeney's lecture on chromosomal abnormalities, PCS 3!

Question: What is the correct sequence of events for wound healing and repair?

- Remodelling is the stage where collagen becomes reorganised, myofibroblasts contract wound and reepithelialization occurs by keratinocytes

Question: What is the function of steroid-receptor complexes in cells.
OptionE: Binds to the tRNA to help with protein translation process.
Explanation:
Chaperones assist the covalent folding or unfolding and the assembly or disassembly of other macromolecular structures.

Steroid-receptor complexes act as a transcriptional regulator of nuclear DNA when formed in cells. However, this does not produce such rapid effects.

Question: Tissue repair involves the proliferation of various cells such as the remnants of injured tissue, vascular endothelial cells and fibroblasts. The proliferation of any of these cells is driven by growth factors. What is a major action of growth factors with regards to the cell cycle?
OptionA: Promote movement of cells into the Go phase
OptionC: Trigger phosphorylation of centrosomes and microfilaments in the cytosol as part of prophase
OptionD: Overcome the checkpoint controls by liberating suppression of CDK activity
OptionE: Inhibits the G0 to G1 transition, and the entry of cells into G1.
Explanation: Any stimulus that initiates cell proliferation, such as exposure to growth factors, needs to promote G0/G1 transition, and entry of cells into the G1 phase. Progression through the cell cycle from G1 is regulated by proteins called cyclins, which form complexes with enzymes called cyclin-dependent kinases. These complexes regulate the phosphorylation of proteins involved in the cell cycle progression leading to DNA replication and mitosis, and this are required for cell cycle progression. A major action of growth factors is to overcome the checkpoint controls by liberating the suppression of CDK activity.

Question: Which cells form and maintain the extracellular matrix?
Explanation: Fibroblasts in the connective tissue form and maintain the ECM.

How many ml of the solution will you give to Mrs. Harris?
Explanation: If there are 500mg in 2ml, there is 1g in 4ml. Therefore for 65g, you will need 65x4ml = 260ml

Question: A 30 years old patient arrives to A and E with Haematemesis. He is pale and has sharp abdominal pain. When you take his history, he tells you that he was a "junky" when he was in his 20s but has stopped drinking alcohol and any other addictive substances since. He says he never had this sort of pain before. He has a big, balloon-like belly. What is the most likely diagnosis...
Explanation:
A. and C. would not provoque aneamia, such a sharp pain and haematemesis (vomiting blood)

D. A duodenal ulcer caused by H. Pylori, which has provoked a posterior perforation near the gastroduodenal artery, and therefore, bleeding and anemia; could be the cause of aneamia, sharp pain however, it would not explain his physical appearance. 

E. Pulmonary fibrosis could provoque ascites (accumulation of fluid in the abdominal cavity), but it would not provoque anemia or sharp pain. 

B. He could have developed hepatitis B or C during his 20s if he practiced some syringe-sharing. These two types of hepatitis can take years to provoke symptoms. Because it provokes a chronic inflamation of the liver, often fibrosis of the liver develops, which puts a lot of pressure in the portal system. Therefore, varices (which are points where the portal system and the systemic system meet without passing through the liver), get overloaded with blood and are prone to perforate. Important varices are located in the oesophagus, others in the stomach. They can explode and cause the symptoms described above.

Question: In which of the following conditions/diseases are anticardiolipin antibodies most highly detected in
Explanation:
The test for anticardiolipin antibodies are used as a diagnosis for Syphilis.

Anticardiolipin antibodies act against cardiolipin. cardiolipin is a phospholipid in the blood and is found in the membranes of most bacteria. Examples of anticardiolipin include IgA, IgG, IgM.
Tags: Microbiology, Sexual Health, Case 2, Immunology, STI

Question:
Mesengial cells help to autoregulate the glomerular filtration rate in the kidneys when mean arterial blood pressure changes. 

 

How do Mesengial cells react to rise in blood pressure?
Explanation:
Mesengial cells like the blood vessels in the kidney. They are smooth muscle cells which contract in response to high blood pressure. This prevents the high pressure being passed on the glomerular capillaries and maintains GFR around 80-160 mmHg

 

ANP is released by cardiomyocytes when blood pressure is too high. This causes reduced Na+ reabsorbtion

Renin is released by juxtoglomerular cells when blood pressure is too low. This activates the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system which ultimately causes increases reabsorbtion of NA+

Question: Where is the nitric oxide oxide stored in the body?

Question: Which one of the conditions below is an autosomal recessive sex limited condition?

Question: You are measuring the effect of the COX enzyme in PGHS-2 in an experiment. You add aspirin; what would you most likely expect the graph of 1/v against 1/[s] to look like compared to the control experiment with no aspirin?
Explanation: Aspirin, a non-competitive inhibitor of COX domain by acetylation of a specific residue, will show a graph showing no change in Km and a decrease in Vmax. A competitive inhibitor, such as a statin with HMG-CoA reductase, would show an increase in Km and unchanged Vmax.

Question: A patient you see in clinic has problems digesting protein and you believe this problem arises from her pancreas. Which nerve(s) is responsible for secretomotor functions of the exocrine pancreas?

The vagus nerve is the right answer as is parasymathetically controls secretomotor functions. E is correct but C is more correct.

most active after the consumption of a carbohydrate rich meal

Question: How does DNA damage arrest the cell cycle in G1?
OptionA: The p53 protein is activated and stimulates transcription of the p21 gene. p21 is a protein which inhibits Cdk, so the cell cycle arrests.
OptionB: The p21 protein is activated and stimulates transcription of the p53 gene. p53 is a protein which inhibits Cdk, so the cell cycle arrests.
OptionC: The p53 protein is activated and directly inhibits Cdk, arresting the cell cycle.
OptionD: Cyclin inhibits Cdk, arresting the cell cycle.
OptionE: p21 is inactivated, which causes Cdk to become inactivated and arrest the cell cycle.
Explanation: When DNA is damaged, specific protein kinases activate p53, and also halt it's natural degradation. Activated p53 stimulates transcription of the gene that encodes for p21, which is a Cdk inhibitor. p21 is encoded and binds to S-Cdk and G1/Cdk and inactivates them, so stops the cell moving from G1 phase to S-phase. So the cell cycle arrests.

Question: At what level does the common carotid artery bifurcate on each side?
Explanation: The common carotid artery emerges either directly from the arch of the aorta on the left side or from the brachiocephalic trunk as on the right side. It divides at C3/C4 to form the external and internal carotid arteries.
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of Thorax, Blood Circulation

Question: Which of the following types of nerve fibres has the slowest conduction speed?
Explanation: C fibres are unmyelinated and thus travel at the slow sped of 0.5 to 2m/s. These fibres transmit colicky pain and are often slow so that one can adequately respond to the stimulus. A-alpha are proprioceptive fibres and are fastest, A-beta are tactile fibres that become pain sensitised in allodynia and are slightly slower than A-alpha while A-delta are the pain fibres that transmit the sharp pain sensation.
Tags: Anatomy, Nervous system, Autonomic Nervous System, Neuroanatomy, Case 1

Question: What condition below could be described as a 'non-nociceptive' pain?
Explanation:
A - correct answer, because non-nociceptive pain can be classed as neuropathic or sympathetic. Neuropathic pain can be described as a lesion or disease of the somatosensory nervous system

B - bee sting would be a nociceptive pain carried by A-delta fibres to the CNS. A-delta fibres are myelinated and produce the initial sharp pain

C - colic is a bout of severe pain that is caused by activation of nociceptive afferents in the viscera, a gallstone passing along the bile duct could cause this type of pain (visceral pain)

D - primary hyperalgesia occurs when an injured area is more sensitive to pain than before, the nociceptors in the area of tissue damage are sensitised and have a lower depolarisation threshold than before

E - pruritis is another name for itch and is thought to occur because of an increased density of bare nerve endings in that area of skin

Question: What is allodynia?
OptionA: localised inflammation leading to hyper excitability of peripheral nociceptors
OptionB: sensitisation of A-beta fibres in the dorsal horn allowing them to evoke pain sensations
OptionC: stimulation of a nerve trunk somewhere along its length rather than at its termination giving rise to an unpleasant, confused sensation
OptionD: degenerative lesions of the posterior thalamic nuclei give rise to this type of pain
OptionE: severe and unremitting pain that is resistant to treatment
Explanation:
A - hyperalgesia

B - correct answer

C - paraesthesia

D - thalamic pain

E - neuralgia

Allodynia is the triggering of a pain response from A-beta fibres which usually only detect light touch and vibrations. Occurs following painful repetitive stimulation.

MUST BE distinguished from HYPERALGESIA which is an exaggerated reaction to a stimulus that is ALREADY painful

Question:
A 60-year-old male ex-smoker has trouble breathing. He is sent for spirometry and his FEV1/FVC ratio is found to be 90% - a restrictive pattern.
Which of the following disorders typically presents with a restrictive pattern on spirometry?
Explanation:
Obstructive disorders (forced expiratory volume in one second [FEV1]/forced vital capacity [FVC] less than 70%) include those which cause airway narrowing, for example,

Asthma
Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)
Cystic fibrosis
Bronchiectasis
Airway-compressing tumours.
Restrictive disorders (FEV1/FVC greater than 70%) are those which limit lung expansion and include pulmonary fibrosis and sarcoidosis.

Question:
Mirena IUD (intrauterine device) was approved in 2000. It is a small, T-shaped container of flexible plastic that releases continuous doses of levonorgesterel. It thickens the cervical mucus and decreases the sperm motility. In 2013, dozens of lawsuits were filed against "Bayer" ( the pharmaceutical company). There were nearly 500 cases with extreme side effects.

 

One of these cases was Nicole Lee Johnson. She presented with heavy bleeding and requested that the device be removed. An abdominal radiography revealed that the IUD was located in the right lateral pelvis. She was declared infertile after the surgery.  What happened to the IUD ?
OptionB: The device penetrated the Fallopian tubes to become entangled in the fimbrae.
OptionC: The device perforated into the bladder and ascended the ureter to the kidney.
OptionD: The device perforated the vaginal wall, through to the rectum and ascended via the colon.
Explanation:
In this particular case, it was answer B. However there are major health risks associated with IUD use and these are perforation of the uterus, pregnancy (both intrauterine and ectopic), and pelvic inflammatory disease. Perforation of the uterus by an IUD is a serious complication and this is possible both during the insertion and later. Perforation of the uterus is rare, but potentially fatal. The incidence is estimated at 0 to 2.6 per 1,000 insertions Although some patients have signs and symptoms suggestive of perforation (pain or bleeding), many are apparently asymptomatic at the time the diagnosis of perforation is made. Perforation is often suspected or diagnosed when the IUD string is no longer visible at the external os. A patient who has sustained a perforation is not protected against pregnancy.

 

See these articles for more information

 

http://www.aafp.org/afp/2013/1115/p634.html

 

http://www.drugwatch.com/mirena/lawsuit/

 

http://www.drugdangers.com/mirena/organ-perforation.htm

Question: What is the primary control centre for descending pain modulation?
Explanation:
Periaqueductal gray (PAG) forms a key part of the pain-inhibition system. Ascending pain and temperature fibres send information to the PAG. Stimulation of the PAG matter activates enkephalin-releasing neurons that project to the raphe nuclei in the brainstem. These release serotonin which activates inhibitory interneurons in the dorsal horn. The interneurons can inhibit the release of substance P from A-delta and C fibres, which inhibits activation of the second order neurone responsible for carrying the pain signal up to the thalamus.

Information taken form Dr Watson's PCS 3 lecture on pain and nociception and a lecture given by Andrew Lawrence on psychology of pain in Case 1

Question: A woman has brown hair, blue eyes and is of an adequate height for peering over her neighbours hedge. anyway a different woman presents to a doctor with enlarged axillary lymph nodes in all 5 different axillary lymph types. aw oh looks like cancer eh? well it is cancer and that's not good at all but also the different woman can no longer medially rotate and adduct her shoulder, and she has a winged scapula. what 2 nerves have been compressed by the cancerous lymph nodes?
Explanation:
The 5 types of lymph nodes are apical,pectoral,humeral, central and subscapular btw.

 

the answer is long thoracic and thoracodorsal. these are 2 most vulnerable to enlarged lymph nodes and innervate serratus anterior and laetissimus dorsi respectively. the actions are supporting scapula hence winged scapula and medial rotation, adductor of shoulder respectively. amen

Question: Which cells are primarily responsible for wound contraction and minimising the extent of scarring?
Explanation: Wound contraction is facilitated by myofibroblasts in granulation tissue which attach to one another and contract to pull together surrounding tissues

Question: Which of the following adrenoreceptors is a Gq coupled protein receptor?

alpha-2 is Gi

beta -1,2 and 3 are Gs

Question: Which of the following is true about sertoli and leydig cells in the testis?
OptionA: LH stimulate testes make testosterone in sertoli cells.
OptionB: FSH stimulates sertoli cells to release Sex Hormone Binding Globulin to bind testosterone for spermatogenesis
OptionC: Leydig cells are in connective tissue between tubules
OptionD: Sertoli cells nourish sperm and convert testosterone to DHT via aromatase
OptionE: Oestrogen stimulates contraction of the seminiferous tubules
Explanation:

B: FSH stimulates sertoli cells to release Androgen Binding Protein to bind testosterone for spermatogenesis- Sex Hormone Binding Globulin is produced in the liver and binds testosterone in the blood

D: Sertoli cells nourish sperm and convert testosterone to DHT via 5-alpha reductase -aromatase converts testosterone to estrogen

Question: Which of the following is involved in both the clotting system and inflammation?
Explanation: Thrombin both converts fibrinogen into fibrin to form a stable mesh, as well as mobilising P selectins, chemokine production, CAM expression and COX-2 induction.

Question: Which of the following functions is not carried out by the Trigeminal nerve?

Question: In which of the following places would you find Hyaline Cartilage?

Myotendinous junction- fibrocartilage

Question: Which of the following is NOT a function carried out by Adenosine in the vasodilation of coronary vessels?
OptionE: Activating PIP2 to form IP3 and DAG
Explanation:
Adenosine binds to A2 receptors coupled to Gs receptors, which activate adenyl cyclase to increase intracellular cAMP and cause protein kinase activation. This stimulates K+ATP channels that hyperpolarise smooth muscle causing relaxation.

 

Increased cAMP also causes smooth muscle relaxation by inhibiting myosin light chain kinase, which leads to decreased myosin phosphorylation and a decrease in contractile force.

 

There is also evidence that adenosine inhibits calcium entry into the cell through L-type calcium channels. Since calcium regulates smooth muscle contraction, reduced intracellular calcium causes relaxation.

Question: H.Pylori is a common infection that causes Peptic ulcers and dyspepsia. But what test is most commonly used by doctors because it is the most sensitive and specific but least invasive test for H.Pylori?
Explanation:
Urea Breath test is 95 % accurate and uses a carbon isotope to measure the amount of CO2 produced from the break down of urea by urease enzyme produced by the bacterium. 

 

Stool Antigen test is 92% accurate

Serology is 80%

Endoscopy is accurate but invasive. It may be used when doctors are concerned about complication such as cancers.

Question: The pancreas stores proteolytic enzymes as zymogens. One of these is trypsin. What enzyme activates trypsin?
OptionE: None of the above, trypsin does not need to be activated.
Explanation:
Enteropeptidase is the correct answer, in it a brush-border enzyme in the duodenum.

 

Trypsin will activate chymotrypsin (another proteolytic enzyme) and colipase ( a pancreatic lipolytic enzyme) as well as cholesterol esterase and phosphlipase A, which are other pancreatic lipolytic enzymes.

 

The alkaline environment of the duodenum is due to bicarbonate secretions by the pancreas and the duodenum itself, and activates other proteolytic enzymes- carboxypeptidases, elastases and aminopeptidases.
Tags: Digestion, Gastrointestinal System, Case 3, Physiology, Random

Question: Which of the following physiological changes in the body decreases pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR)
OptionA: Breath holding maneuver at functional residual capacity (FRC)
Explanation:
Pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) is a function of intrathoracic pressure and alveolar expansion, and is lowest at FRC.

PVR is increased by inhalation (increased pressure on lung vessels by expanding alveoli) and forced exhalation (increased intrathoracic pressure compresses lung vessels). At FRC, the balance of alveolar expansion and intrathoracic pressure results in the lower PVR. Note that FRC is the lung capacity at which pulmonary resistance is lowest.
Tags: Respiratory physiology, Anatomy of Thorax, Case 5, Lung function

Question: What is the function of rectus femoris?
OptionB: Flexes thigh at hip joint and medially rotates at hip joint
OptionC: Extends leg at knee joint and laterally rotates at hip joint
OptionD: Flexes thigh at hip joint and extends leg at knee joint

Question: You are on placement in A&E and a 42 year old man comes in who has been in a car accident. On examination he shows loss of sensation on the medial part of his thigh and he struggles to adduct his leg at the hip. Which nerve is most likely affected?
Explanation:
The Obturator nerve is the correct answer. It supplies the muscles in the medial compartment of the thigh (with the exception of the hamstring portion of Adductor Magnus which is supplied by the Tibial part of the Sciatic nerve)

 

The Femoral nerve supplies most of the muscles of the anterior compartment of the thigh

The Nerve to Obturator Internus supplies Obturator Internus (duh!) and Superior Gemelli

The Sciatic nerve supplies all the muscles in the posterior compartment of the thigh

The Pudendal nerve innervates the perineum
Tags: Anatomy, Anatomy of the lower limb, Nervous system, Case 1, Lower Limb

Question: What is the general function of the muscles of the anterior compartment of the thigh?
OptionC: Flexes leg and laterally rotates thigh at hip joint
OptionD: Extends leg and medially rotate thigh at hip joint

Question: What is the the key way of detecting post-hepatic conjugated Hyperbilirubinaemia from the other types?
Explanation:
ALP is Alkaline Phosphatase is especially high in the cells lining the bile ducts hence obstructions of the biliary tree and bile ducts cause a rise in ALP. 

 

ALP is not siginificantly high in liver disease hence it is used for cholestatic blockages. 

 

All the other options are true for post hepatic conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia however they may also be present in other types of hyperbilirubinaemia.

Question: A 27-year-old male is brought to the emergency room following a violent assault in which he was stabbed in the chest. The knife penetrated both the left lung and the left ventricle. Where did the knife most likely enter his chest?
OptionA: Left seventh intercostal space in the midclavicular line
OptionB: Left fifth intercostal space just lateral to the sternum
OptionC: Left fifth intercostal space in the midclavicular line
OptionD: Left fifth intercostal space in the midaxillary line
OptionE: Left seventh intercostal space in the midaxillary line
Explanation:
The only possible knife path to pass though the left lung and left ventricle would be in the left fifth intercostal space in the midclavicular line.

The apex of the heart is covered anteriorly by the left lung. The cardiac notch is an indentation in the left lung due to the deviation of the apex of the heart to the left side. The lingula, a homolog of the right middle lobe, is a flap of lung tissue of the superior lobe that lies below the cardiac notch. Several life-threatening conditions can result this attack: open or closed pneumothorax; hemothorax; flail chest; pericardial tamponade; injury the esophagus, trachea or great vessels
Tags: Anatomy, Respiratory physiology, Anatomy of Thorax, Case 5, Lung function

Question: How does DNP (2,4-dintirophenol) disrupt ATP synthesis?
OptionA: It stops oxygen from entering the mitochondrial matrix
OptionB: It inhibits glycolysis, so pyruvate cannot be formed
OptionC: It disrupts the proton gradient in the electron transport chain
OptionD: It prevents the influx of protons through ATP synthase
OptionE: It stops electron flow down the electron transport chain
Explanation: DNP is a hydrophobic molecule, so can freely diffuse across the inner mitochondrial membrane. It can carry protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane, which is normally impermeable to them. This means that they don't go down the usual route, through ATP synthase. This means that normal ATP synthesis stops. It is said to be an 'uncoupler' of oxidative phosphorylation. The body tries to compensate by oxidizing more fuel and pumping more protons out of the mitochondria. In this way, large amounts of energy is lost as heat, but not captured as ATP.

Question: Which of the following would be expected to cause renal inulin (or creatinine) clearance to increase?
Explanation: E - Both dilation of the afferent arteriole and constriction of the efferent arteriole would increase glomerular capillary hydrostatic pressure and thus increase GFR. (Note that inulin (or creatinine) clearance is a measure of GFR).

Question: The rate of water reabsorption from the proximal tubule is determined primarily by the....
OptionA: rate of dissolved particle (solute) reabsorption from the proximal tubule
OptionB: concentration of ADH (antidiuretic hormone) in the blood
OptionC: osmotic pressure developed by plasma proteins in the proximal tubule
OptionD: active transport of water molecules by the proximal tubule cells
OptionE: passive filtration due to the high hydrostatic pressure in the proximal tubule
Explanation:
A. The proximal tubule is very permeable to water, so water reabsorption follows solute (dissolved particle) reabsorption. 

 

(B) Increase in ADH within the blood will stimulate the translocation of aquaporins (AQP2) to the membrane of the collecting duct (the collecting duct is the only place along the nephron where water reabsorption is regulated) allowing water to be reabsorbed, thus concentrating the urine.

(C) Plasma proteins are too big to filtrate through the glomeruli into the nephron, therefore should not be present in the proximal tubule.

(D) Movement of water is passive, (through aquaporins) therefore does NOT require energy

What are these ions?

A 35-year-old man presents with paraesthesia in the central area of the dorsum of his foot and proximal toes except the fifth. He is also found to have some weakness of eversion of the foot.
Which of the following nerves is most likely to be involved?
Explanation:
The superficial peroneal nerve also supplies peroneus longus and brevis, tested by everting the foot against resistance.

The only sensory loss from damage to the deep peroneal nerve is in the first interdigital cleft.

The sural nerve supplies the dorsum of the lateral one and a half toes.

Question: You are listening to a woman's chest and you hear a murmur during mid-diastole, at the sound of the 1st heard sound - S1 the 'lub'. what are you hearing?
Explanation:
Systolic murmurs are either aortic or pulmonary stenosis (narrowing) or tricuspid/ mitral regurgitation (leaky valves).

Diastolic murmurs are either aortic or pulmonary regurgitation or mitral/ tricuspid stenosis. 

Therefore as the murmur is heard at the sound of the tricuspid/ mitral valve closing it must be MITRAL STENOSIS. (as tricuspid stenosis is not in the above options) rather than pulmonary regurgitation or aortic regurgitation as you would hear this at S2.

Question: What is the role of CCK (cholecystokinin)?
Explanation:
Cholecystokinin neutralises the acidic partially digested food by inducing the gallbladder to contract and the pancreas to release alkaline pancreatic fluid.

Gastrin increases stomach acid and increases the rate of gastric emptying.

Secretin reduces stomach acid production.

Leptin acts to suppress appetite.

Question: During glycolysis, which enzyme is responsible for the conversion of pyruvate to acetyl CoA?
Explanation: Pyruvate dehydrogenase converts pyruvate to acetyl CoA. This reaction allows the coupling of glycolysis to the Kreb cycle and on to the electron transfer chain allowing efficient energy production per molecule of glucose. The reaction takes place in the mitochondrion and generates one molecule of NADH for each molecule of pyruvate converted into acetyl CoA.

Question: Which of the following is not a function of the liver?
OptionB: Production of bilirubin from haem in senescent red blood cells
Explanation:
The overall function of the liver is in the regulation of blood composition to maintain physiologically acceptable concentrations of solutes, toxins and drugs. This occurs through countless metabolic reactions: removing excess solutes, synthesising deficient solutes and storing solutes for later use. For example, the liver is involved in maintaining blood glucose levels. After a meal, excess glucose is taken up from the liver, and stored as glycogen. In the fasting state, when blood sugars are lower, glycogen is released as glucose back into the blood stream. Additionally, the liver uses other substances such as fat, protein or other sugars to produce more glucose in gluconeogenesis.

Nitrogenous waste from protein catabolism is processed in the liver, with the conversion of ammonium from amino acids to urea. Urea is a less toxic solute than ammonium and can be renally excreted allowing for rapid clearance from the blood stream in healthy individuals.

A further function of the liver is in producing bilirubin from haem in red blood cells. This reaction occurs in the reticuloendothelial macrophages in the liver, spleen and bone marrow. The processing of bilirubin to make bile occurs exclusively in the liver.

The liver is involved in the production of plasma proteins such as albumin, many hormones, cytokines and C-reactive protein. Immunoglobulins however are made by plasma cells (B-lymphocytes) and are not produced in the liver as such.

Question: Activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system causes a significant physiological effect on renal blood flow and filtration. Which of the following is most likely to occur in the hormonal response to combat decreased renal perfusion?
OptionA: Increased renal plasma flow, decreased filtration fraction
OptionB: Increased renal plasma flow, increased filtration fraction
OptionC: Decreased renal plasma flow, decreased filtration fraction
OptionD: Decreased renal plasma flow, increased filtration fraction
OptionE: Decreased renal plasma flow, increased glomerular capillary oncotic pressure
Explanation:
Angiotensin-II  usually constricts renal efferent arterioles, resulting in increased GFR and decreased renal plasma flow (RPF). Thus producing a net increase in filtration fraction (Filtration Fraction = GFR/RPF).

The renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system helps regulate blood pressure and total body sodium. Renin is released in response to decreased renal perfusion and converts angiotensinogen to angiotensin-I, which is converted to angiotensin-II by ACE in the lung. Angiotensin-II is a potent vasoconstrictor and also assists in increasing total body volume by stimulating aldosterone secretion. Preferential efferent constriction by Angiotensin-II increases hydrostatic pressure in the glomerulus, increasing GFR, and filtration fraction because total RPF is decreased by the efferent arteriolar constriction.

Question: A healthy 36-year-old Caucasian man takes part in an experimental drug trial. The drug is designed to lower glomerular filtration rate (GFR) while simultaneously raising the filtration fraction. Which of the following effects on the glomerulus would you expect the drug to have?
OptionA: Afferent arteriole constriction and efferent arteriole constriction
OptionB: Afferent arteriole constriction and efferent arteriole vasodilation
OptionC: Afferent arteriole dilation and efferent arteriole vasodilation
OptionD: Afferent arteriole dilation and efferent arteriole constriction
Explanation:
Afferent and efferent arteriole constriction would both decrease GFR and raise the filtered fraction.

 

The afferent arteriole provides blood to the glomerular capillaries. Constriction of the afferent arteriole therefore lowers the GFR, while dilation of this arteriole raises the GFR.

 

The efferent arteriole takes blood out of the glomerular capillaries. Constriction of the efferent arteriole raises GFR and selective dilation lowers GFR.

 

The filtration fraction represents the proportion of the fluid reaching the kidneys that passes into the renal tubules (usually around 20%). It is described by the following equation: FF = GFR / RPF (RPF =renal plasma flow). Constriction of either arteriole decreases RPF while dilation increases it. To lower GFR the efferent arteriole must dilate and/or the afferent arteriole must constrict. The only way to raise the filtered fraction while simultaneously lowering GFR is to decrease the RPF m ore than the GFR. Constricting both efferent and afferent arterioles would have this effect.

Question: Which organ secretes the hormones cortisol, aldosterone and the adrenal androgens?
Explanation:
The pituitary gland - growth hormone, prolactin, ACTH, MSH, TSH, FSH, LH, oxytocin and vasopressin.

The thyroid gland - thyroid hormones and calcitonin

The adrenal medulla - adrenaline and noradrenaline

The pancreas - insulin and glucagon

Question: Growth hormone and FSH have similar chemical properties in that they ...
OptionE: Both need to be bound to proteins in the plasma to be transported in the circulation
Explanation:
FSH and growth hormone are peptide hormones, so are hydrophilic and can travel freely in the plasma.

 

Catecholamines include adrenaline and noradrenaline. They have similar properties to peptides in that they are hydrophilic, but have a different structure.

 

Steroid hormones such as testosterone are hydrophobic and must be bound to proteins in the plasma to be transported in the circulation.

Question:
N- acetyl cysteine is given intravenously after a paracetamol overdose.

 

How does it reduce to the toxicity of Paracetamol?
OptionA: It catalyses the conjugation with glucuronic acid

Question: Which of the following is NOT true of the Krebs cycle?
OptionA: GTP is produced and converted to ATP

Question: You are on placement in A&E when a 23 year old man comes in saying that he has fallen of his bike. You notice swelling around the lateral aspect of his right knee joint and also that as he walks, the toes of his right foot struggle to clear the ground. What is this alteration in his gait referred to as, and what nerve is likely to be affected to cause it?
Explanation:
Because of its position (winding superficially around the fibular head) the common fibular nerve is the nerve which is most frequently injured in the lower limb. Since this nerve supplies the anterior and lateral compartments of the lower leg (the dorsiflexors) it results in a loss of dorsiflexion which is what results in footdrop.

 

Steppage gait and Swing-out gaits are ways in which patients may compensate for footdrop

Question: What is an orchidometer used to measure?

The modern diet contains a 15:1 ratio of omega 6:omega 3, but it is recommended that the ratio should be 4:1 or even 2:1. Question: Which of the following is NOT an action of angiotensin-II?
Explanation:
Angiotensin is a peptide hormone which is derived from the precursor molecule angiotensionogen (serum globulin released in the liver.

 

Overall the action is to increase blood pressure by various ways:

Reabsorption of Na+, H2O follows

Potent direct vasoconstrictors, constriction arteries and veins - increase the blood pressure

increases secretion of ADH in the posterior pituitary to increase water reabsorption

Angiotensin II has a direct effect on the proximal tubules to increase Na+ reabsorption

Angiotensin II acts on the adrenal cortex, causing it to release aldosterone, a hormone that causes the kidneys to retain sodium and lose potassium.

Question: B vitamins are an essential part of our diet. One of these is found in virtually all foods and is used to form CoA (coenzyme A). Which of the following is it?

Question: A peripheral artery is found to have 50% stenosis.  Compared to a normal artery with no stenosis, by what factor has the flow of blood been decreased?
Explanation:
Flow through a vessel is inversely proportional to the radius of that vessel to the 4th power. Therefore, flow in this artery would be decreased by a factor of 16.

 

Flow of blood in an artery is given by Q = P/R, (where Q = flow, P is pressure difference, and R is resistance to flow). Resistance is given by Poiseuille's equation: R = (viscosity of blood) X (length of vessel)/r^4. Therefore, if the radius decreases by a factor of 2, resistance increases by a factor of 16, and flow decreases by a factor of 16.
Tags: Blood Cells, Blood Circulation, Cardiology, Cardiovascular System, cardiac cycle

Question: Which of the following compounds is most responsible for the maintenance of appropriate coronary blood flow via autoregulation?
Explanation:
Nitric oxide (NO) is the most important factor influencing coronary blood flow autoregulation.

NO is synthesized by the endothelium from arginine and oxygen. It causes vascular smooth muscle relaxation mediated via an increase in cGMP.

Question: Which molecule activates Pyruvate Dehydrogenase?

Side effects of aspirin

Question: In which of the following pathological states would the oxygen content of the trachea resemble the oxygen content in the affected alveoli?
OptionE: Foreign body obstruction distal to the trachea
Explanation:
Pulmonary embolism (PE) effectively results in a blockage of flow in a vessel to its corresponding alveoli. As a result, there is no extraction of oxygen or ventilation in this region (i.e. dead space physiology) and the alveoli have a gas composition similar to the trachea (O2=150, CO2=0).

 

A. Emphysema is a diffuse process and does not change the oxygen content of an affected alveoli, but instead reduces the number of functioning alveoli.

C. Pulmonary fibrosis is a diffuse process that does not change the oxygen content of an affected alveoli, but instead reduces the number of functioning alveoli.

D. Exercise does not significantly change the oxygen content of the alveoli; PAO2 may increase slightly with exercise in normal subjects, as PaCO2 decreases with increased ventilation: PAO2 = PiO2 - PaCO2 x [FiO2 + (1 - FiO2)/R]

E. An airway foreign body would reduce the oxygen content of the affected alveoli (not increase as in PE), and would result in shunt physiology of the alveoli distal to the obstruction.

Question: A 28-year-old woman presents to a GP with decreased appetite, malaise, and fever. Serologic tests reveal positive Anti-HBsAg and Anti-HAV IgM antibodies. Which of the following is most likely responsible for this patient's presentation?

Question: What is the end result of a rapid burst of excitatory post synaptic potentials from one pre-synaptic neuron on the membrane of the post-synaptic cell .
Explanation:
- Temporal summation occurs when a single neuron fires many excitatory post synaptic potentials (EPSPs). If the summation crosses the threshold potential, then the post-synaptic cell will depolarise and generate and action potential.

- Spatial summation occurs when different neurons synapse with the cell body of a neuron and they each fire EPSPs.

- Frequency potentiation occurs is a phenomena that is specific to the presynaptic membrane and not the post synaptic membrane (temporal and spatial summation are phenomena in the post synaptic membrane). It occurs when many action potentials arrive at the presynaptic membrane, leading to a larger release of neurotransmitter from the presynaptic cell. The postsynaptic membrane is therefore more likely to depolarise.

- Inhibitory postynpatic potentials occur when a presynaptic membrane release a neurotransmitter that causes the opening of Cl- channels in the postsynaptic membrane and hyperpolarisation. This briefly (dies away after 5 ms) makes it harder for the membrane to depolarise.

Question: A woman with coronary artery disease goes for a walk. As she begins, her heart rate accelerates from a resting pulse of 60 bpm until it reaches a rate of 120 bpm, at which point she begins to feel a tightening in her chest. She stops walking to rest and the tightening resolves. This has been happening to her consistently for the last 6 months. Which of the following is a true statement?
OptionA: Increasing the heart rate decreases the relative amount of time spent during diastole
OptionB: Increasing the heart rate increases the amount of time spent for each cardiac cycle
OptionC: Perfusion of the myocardium takes place equally throughout the cardiac cycle
OptionD: Perfusion of the myocardium takes place entirely during diastole
OptionE: This patient's chest pain is indicative of transmural ischemia
Explanation:
Increasing the heart rate decreases the relative amount of time spent during diastole, and thus this there is less time for the majority of coronary blood flow to occur.

Perfusion of the myocardium via the coronary arteries and myocardial capillaries occurs during mainly diastole (90% of blood flow during diastole, 10% during systole). At higher heart rates the relative amount of time spent during diastole is decreased, likely contributing to angina, as this patient has here.

 

Increasing the heart rate decreases the amount of time spent during each cardiac cycle, as the effect of right sympathetic branches on the SAN and suppression of the right vagus nerve stimulates a faster beat.
This patient's chest pain is so far consistent with stable angina; transmural ischemia would be a concern in myocardial infarction and the fact that this has happened multiple times and has consequently recovered from the woman stopping her activity demonstrates this to be likely stable angina.
Tags: Cardiology, Cardiovascular System, cardiac cycle, case 4

Question: When looking at a pressure volume loop the end systolic pressure volume relationship (ESPVR) shows the maximum pressure that can develop at a given left ventricular volume. At this point what is the relationship between the intra cardiac pressure and the peripheral pressure and what does the ESPVR represent?
OptionA: Peripheral pressure exceeds intra cardiac pressure.ESPVR represents inotropy.
OptionB: Intra cardiac pressure exceeds peripheral pressure. ESPVR represents chronotropy.
OptionC: Peripheral pressure exceeds intra cardiac pressure. ESPVR represents chronotropy.
OptionD: Intra cardiac pressure exceeds peripheral pressure. ESPVR represents inotropy.
OptionE: Intra cardiac pressure and peripheral pressure are the same. ESPVR represents both chronotropy and inotropy.
Explanation:
All statements are false except D. 

Intra cardiac pressure exceeds peripheral pressure causing aortic valve to open so blood can be pumped around the body from a high to low pressure. Otherwise blood would not leave the ventricle. 

ESPVR represents inotropy (contractility) of the ventricle as at this point semilunar valves open due to ventricular systole causing pressure in ventricle to exceed aortic pressure. So higher ESPVR means higher left ventricular pressure so stronger contraction. Chronotropy represents heart rate. 

 

https://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=i&rct=j&q=pressure+volume+loop&source=images&cd=&ved=0CAcQjRw&url=http%3A%2F%2Fjeb.biologists.org%2Fcontent%2F210%2F12%2F2192%2FF2.expansion.html&ei=6-5aVZm4LcaC7gbWyIH4DA&bvm=bv.93564037,d.ZGU&psig=AFQjCNGA9uiHMVx14mIhgBiQDWaYIGjbTQ&ust=1432109159174394

Question:
Calcium Channel Blockers can be used to treat Angina Pectoris.

 

What is the mechanism for their negative chronotrophic effect?
OptionA: Blocks L type calcium channels in pacemaker cells hence reducing depolarization and reducing firing rate of the SAN node.
OptionB: Blocks L type calcium channels in cardiac myocytees so less calcium calmodulin complexes formed which are needed to activate myosin light chain kinase
OptionC: Blocks L type calcium channels in smooth muscle of blood vessels so less calcium calmodulin complexes formed which are needed to activate myosin light chain kinase
Explanation:
All are correct mechanisms of actions of calcium channel blockers.

 

However negative chronophic effect is a slower heart rate. 

B would have a negative inotrophic effect by lower myocyte contractilit, hence lower force of contraction. 

C would lower vascular resistance by causing vasodilation. 

 

Verampril is the calcium channel blocker most specific to the heart.

Question: A 19-year-old male is found to have Neisseria gonorrhoeae bacteremia. This bacterium produces an IgA protease capable of cleaving the hinge region of IgA antibodies. What is the most likely physiological consequence of such a protease?
OptionB: Opsonization and phagocytosis of pathogen cannot occur
Explanation:
Neisseria gonorrhoeae and Neisseria meningitidis both produce a protease capable of cleaving IgA molecules. This results in impaired mucosal immune protection.

Dimeric IgA molecules present on the basolateral side of epithelial cells are able to bind to basolateral receptors (poly-Ig receptors) on the epithelial cell and, via transcytosis, are presented on the apical side of the mucosal cell. On the mucosal surface, dimeric IgA is able to bind microorganisms and prevent them from entering the epithelial cells. Cleavage of IgA hinge regions impairs the antibody from performing this function.

 

A: S. pyogenes M protein impairs membrane attack complex formation which has no relationship to IgA protease.
B: Opsonization and phagocytosis inhibition is an example of many different bacterial virulence factors but not those seen in Neisseria species.
C: Impaired adaptive immune system memory is not a result of Neisseria species virulence factors.
D: Neisseria species virulence factors do not Impair antibody binding to mast cells.

Question: The Modification of Diet in Renal Disease (MDRD) Study equation is the most widely used equation for estimating GFR in patients age 18 and over in Wales. Which one of the following variables is not taken in to account when using the MDRD equation?
Explanation:
These differences account for differences in muscle mass. 

- Less creatinine in the elderly and females

- More creatinine in afro-caribbean individuals

 

The equation does not require weight or height variables because the results are reported normalized to 1.73 m2 body surface area, which is an accepted average adult surface area.

 

It is important to remember that the derivation of the MDRD formula comes from a population of patients in the USA with renal impairment, and as such the formula performs very well in the mid-range of GFR but less well at higher GFR levels.

Question: Mr Griffiths has a lower motor neurone lesion and has come to visit his neurologist for a review of his symptoms. The consultant neurologist says you (a medical student) can sit in on the consultation, at the start of the consultation he asks you to name the main signs associated with lower motor neurone lesions.
OptionA: Spasticity, focal weakness, fascilculations, muscle wasting, exaggerated reflexes, absent plantar reflex
OptionB: Flaccid focal weakness, fasciculations, muscle wasting, weak or absent reflexes, absent or normal plantar reflex.
OptionC: Spastic pyramidal weakness, absence of fasciculations, no muscle wasting, exaggerated reflexes, toes point up in plantar reflex
OptionD: Flaccid pyramidal weakness, fasciculations, muscle wasting, absence of reflexes, toes go up in plantar reflex
OptionE: Spastic focal weakness, absence of fasciculations, no muscle wasting, absence of reflexes, absence of plantar reflex
Explanation:
Lesions in upper motor neurone symptoms:

- high muscle tone (spasticity)

- pyramidal pattern of weakness

- lack of fasciculations

- no muscle wasting

- exaggerated reflexes

- abnormal plantar reflex (toes point up instead of down)

 

Lower motor neurone lesion symptoms:

- loss of muscle tone (flaccidity)

- focal pattern of weakness (often starting at the peripharies)

- fasciculations

- muscle wasting

 - weak or absent reflexes

- absent or normal plantar reflex

Question: Which of the following is the most appropriate Cardiac biomarker to ascertain whether a patient has had MI, and why?
OptionA: Creatinine Kinase - MB. It persists for over a week and is uniquely released post-MI
OptionB: Troponin type-E. Type E is unique to cardiac myocytes and therefore is indicative of MI
OptionC: Tropnin types-I & T. These isoforms are unique to cardiac myocytes and are not present in health.
Explanation:
A. CK-MB is a biomarker, but if there is skeletal muscle damage then it is difficult to differentiate between the differing types of Creatinine Kinase. CK-MB levels peak at around 10 hours but levels return to normal after 3 days.

 

B. This is a made up isoform of troponin.

 

C. Correct answer! These isoforms of troponin are unique to cardiac myocytes and remain in the body's system for up to 7 days after a Myocardial Infarction. They are the most sensitive (a good rates of detecting MI) and specific (gives few false positives) biomarkers for MI.

 

Biomarkers are used in to assess the level of damage done to the heart, and the time-scale of the MI. By taking chronological measurements of a marker, we can work out whether it is reaching its peak concentration or if the levels are dropping again.

Question: A 68-year-old male painter with severe chest pain is found to have atherosclerosis of his coronary arteries. What type of cells were most likely injured in the initial stage of his disease?
Explanation:
Atherosclerosis begins with repetitive endothelial cell injury.

Endothelial cell injury (e.g. from hypertension, diabetes, smoking, etc.) results in increased permeability of the endothelium and exposure of subendothelial collagen. Monocytes, lymphocytes, and LDL cholesterol migrate into the intima, and exposure of subendothelial collagen promotes platelet aggregation. A chronic inflammatory state in the intima perpetuates the formation of an atheroma.

Question: A 56-year-old Caucasian male notices substernal chest pain while walking his dog in Bute park on a sunny Saturday morning. The pain disappears after 5 minutes of rest, and he continues to enjoy his weekend. As he smokes a cigarette later in the day, he wonders: which of the following pathologies were most likely responsible for his chest pain that morning?

OptionC: A fixed atherosclerotic plaque obstructing 50% of one of his coronary arteries

OptionE: An ulcerated fibrous plaque in one of his coronary arteries
Explanation:
The patient displays stable angina pectoris with an underlying risk factor for atherosclerosis (smoking). Fixed atherosclerotic plaques obstructing >75% of the coronary artery are associated with stable angina.

Chronic (stable) angina pectoris is characterized by 3 distinct features:

1.Deep, poorly localized chest or arm pain

2.Reproducible with physical exertion

3.Relieved with 5 minutes of rest or use of sub-lingual nitroglycerin.

Hypertension, cigarette smoking, and hyperlipidemia are major risk factors for atherosclerosis.

Question: You are examining a patient who has been involved in a vehicle dashboard accident. The patient presents with a shortened lower limb held in position of hip flexion, adduction and internal rotation. From looking at their X-ray you make the following diagnosis.
Explanation:
Hip dislocations are either anterior or posterior.

Posterior dislocations are more common than anterior and are usually caused by motor vehicle accidents where the hip is flexed and the knee is pushed backwards by impact on the dashboard. In a posterior dislocation the femur will be pushed out of the socket in a backwards direction, which is seen in the X-ray above.

 

In anterior dislocations the femur slips out of the socket in a forward direction and the patient presents with lower limb extension, abduction and external rotation.

Question: A paracetamol overdose of >12g results in significant hepatocyte damage and is potentially lethal. This is because of the accumulation of what toxic substance?
Explanation:
Normal paracetamol metabolism

  • majority of the paracetamol is directed down the glucuronidation pathway
  • inactivating the drug and making it water soluble by sulphination.
  • this means it can be easily excreted
  • only very small amounts of paracetamol are involved with the cytochrome pathway,
  • with CYP1A2 and CYP2E1 generating the toxic NAPBQI.
  • this is very rapidly deactivated by conjugation to glutathione, an anti oxidant, so no net damage is done to hepatocytes. 

Overdose of paracetamol

  • the high concentration of paracetamol overwhelms the UGT enzyme in the glucuronidation pathway
  • so excess paracetamol is forced down the cytochrome pathway instead.
  • a much larger quantity of NAPBQI is generated
  • glutathione reserves rapidly depleted by liver
  • build up of NAPBQI in hepatocytes leading to necrosis

Depending on the concentration of paracetamol in blood and the time since consumption, NAC can be given by IV to replenish glutathione levels.

>15hrs --> irreversible damage to the liver --> internal bleeding as clotting factors aren't produced --> death

Question: A 70 year old man fell down his stairs and deeply cut open his leg. Not wanting to go to the hospital, he leaves it for a few days. He lives alone with no close family so, eventually, his neighbour calls an ambulance as he is in severe pain and delirious from the infection. You are the junior doctor who sees him and it is clear that the infection is spreading rapidly. Your assessment is that the leg must be amputated immediately or the man will die but he is screaming and won't allow it. What would be your next course of action?
OptionA: He is delirious and unable to understand, retain and  weigh up the information you are giving him so he doesn't have the capacity to make the decision. You think he will die if he doesn't have the surgery so, with no other close family or friends to speak with, you decide to go ahead with the surgery.
OptionB: Time is running out for the man but you decide you speak with your superior and get a second opinion.
OptionC: While delirious, he can still communicate that he doesn't want the surgery and could sue if he has the amputation and survives. You decide to leave it and wait for the next 24 hrs, monitoring him.
OptionD: He is 70 years old so has a reduced chance of surviving the surgery anyway. Give him medication to reduce the pain and monitor him over the next 24 hrs.
Explanation:
This was difficult to write and would be interested to know any other perspectives on the answer but I feel that in most situations like this you always need a second opinion. You could be wrong in your diagnosis and with such a life changing surgery you don't want to make a mistake. Obviously, it always depends on the scenario so you'd probably need more information about the man such as medical history, smoking, drinking etc... 

Also, I may have missed something obvious so please comment if you notice any other factors.

Question: A 38-year-old builder who is male who takes NSAIDs routinely for his chronic back pain begins to get severe abdominal pain aggravated with eating. Upper endoscopy is performed and you asks the supervising gastroenterologist how a differentiation between a gastric ulcer and erosion is made. Up to which set of the following layers of the gastric lumen is a lesion breach to be considered an ulcer at the minimum?
OptionD: Epithelium, lamina propria, muscularis mucosa, and submucosa
OptionE: Epithelium, lamina propria, muscularis mucosa, submucosa, and muscularis externa
Explanation:
Gastric ulcers are a breach in the mucosa with extension into the submucosa or even deeper; the submucosa must be penetrated if a lesion is an ulcer.

Erosions are mucosal defects that do not reach  the submucosa.

Layer order in the stomach is Mucosa, submucosa, muscularis externa, adventitia/serosa
Tags: Functions of different tissues, Gastrointestinal System, Histology, Case 3

Question: Marnie is an alcoholic, who in a drunken state falls over on the pavement. She has a deep wound on her knee, yet doesn't stop bleeding, so admits herself to the hospital. At the hospital they find she has a Cirrhosis of the liver and decreased levels of a protein associated with her profuse bleeding. What is this protein?
Explanation:
Prothrombin is a plasma protein, that is unstable and formed by the liver. Vitamin K is required for the synthesis of this protein also. A vitamin K deficiency or liver damage - e.g. damage to the hepatocytes - Cirrhosis, can cause decreased or inefficient production of Prothrombin and so severe alcoholics (people with liver damage) often have a tendency to bleed. Unstable prothrombin plays an important role in the Coagulation cascade as factor Xa activates prothrombin to form Thrombin, which in turn activates Fibrinogen to form Fibrin monomers and subsequently cross-linked fibrin polymers, to form the fibrin clot.

 

Heparin co factor II inhibits Thrombin in the presence of Heparin.

 

Von Willebrand factor is needed in platelet adhesion in the initial stages of Haemostasis and produced in connective tissue.

 

Albumin is the main protein of the blood with its main function to regulate Colloid osmotic properties of the blood plasma. Albumin is produced in the liver however it is not involved in Haemostasis.

Explanation: In Pemphigus the immune systems attacks desmosomes leading to the formation of painful blisters all over the skin.

The coagulation cascade comprises the extrinsic and intrinsic pathway before combining to form a final common path

V + II + ??? --> IIa

Question:
The Duke and Duchess of Cambridge are visiting their GP surgery to have Princess Charlotte vaccinated against Men C. Whilst at the surgery the GP explains to Kate and Will that a vaccination is a form of acquired immunity. Having studied Geography, Will looks perplexed and asks 'What is an acquired immune response?'

 

Which of the following characteristics best defines an acquired immune response?
OptionE: it involves CD4+ T cells that induce the death of cells infected with viruses
Explanation:
A - innate responses also involve leukocytes

B - proliferation does occur in order to generate sufficient numbers of cells but it's not the best defining characteristic 

C - cells of the innate response do this too when the express pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) to recognise pathogen associated molecular patterns (PAMPs)

D - correct because immunological memory is a defining feature of the adaptive response. Memory B and T cells can become activated if a previously encountered antigen is recognised. There is a stronger and faster immune response

E - this last statement is incorrect because CD4+ cells have no cytotoxic ability, they are T helper cells. CD8+ are cytotoxic T cells

Question: A 45-year-old  male presents to a gastroenterologist complaining of heartburn and difficulty swallowing. He recalls that he has been told by his GP that he has gastroesophageal reflux disease (GORD). The gastroenterologist decides to perform an upper endoscopy with biopsy. Which of the following findings would be consistent with Barrett's esophagus?
OptionA: A  region of red, velvet-like mucosa in the lower oesophagus
OptionC: Presence of Paneth cells in the lower oesophagus
Explanation:
Barrett's oesophagus is a condition impacting the lower esophagus and is defined by intestinal metaplasia of esophageal tissue. Endoscopic findings of a region of patchy redness near the gastroesophageal junction is common .

Barrett's oesophagus is believed to be mediated by chronic GORD. It is important to perform endoscopic procedures on patients with GORD because it is believed that the metaplasia seen in Barrett Oesophagus is correlated with future adenocarcinoma of the oesophagus. Treatment includes anti-reflux medications, dietary modifications, and lifestyle changes such as weight loss and head of bed elevation. Patients must be continually monitored and ultimately may undergo surgery to remove the abnormal region or surveillance biopsies to assess for malignant transformation.

Answer B: The metaplasia that occurs in Barrett's oesophagus is mainly located in the lower esophagus.

Answer C: Paneth cell metaplasia is more consistent with Crohn's disease.
Answer D: Neutrophilic infiltration would be more consistent with infectious oesophagitis.

Answer E: Oesophageal varices are more consistent with portal hypertension.

Question: ................. binds to the CCK receptor on the pancreatic Acinar cell which stimulates the ............... pathway
Explanation: Gastrin binds to CCK receptor - activates Gq - Increases PKC - Increases Calcium ions

Question: Reduced blood flow through which arteries can lead to erectile dysfunction?
Explanation: Erectile tissues in the perineum receive their blood supply through the internal pudendal artery. Reduced blood flow through the internal pudendal artery, often a result of vascular disease of aorta or internal ileac artery, can lead to erectile dysfunction.

Question: Which part of the nephron reabsorbs only water?
Explanation: The descending limb absorbs only water because it is impermeable to ions.

Question: Which is the antibiotic most commonly given synergistically with fluoroquinolones (another type of antibiotic)?
Explanation:
Fluoroquinolones are a type of antibiotic which interferes with DNA and RNA synthesis in the cell. 

They are most commonly given with penicillin as penicillin is a type of Beta-lactam ring antibiotic which inhibits the cell wall synthesis of bacteria.

Therefore, using these two together has a greater effect because the penicillin would break down the cell wall allowing entry for the fluoroquinolones which can then inhibit DNA/ RNA synthesis.

 

A, B, D and E are all antibiotics which interfere with protein synthesis so it is less likely that these will be given with fluoroquinolones.
Tags: Sexual Health, Case 2, Lectures, Clinical Skills, Drugs

Tay- Sachs disease is a build up of myelin in the body.

MS is a lack of myelin in the body.

Question: Which part of the nephron in the kidney releases the enzyme renin in response to low blood pressure?

Question: Which part of the nephron is impermeable to water but actively transports ions such as Na+, Cl- and K+ into the medullary interstitium?
OptionB: the descending limb of the loop of Henle
OptionC: the ascending limb of the loop of Henle
Explanation:
The ascending limb is impermeable to water (allows no water out), but actively transports ions in to the interstitium, which makes it very concentrated. This causes water to move by osmosis out of the descending limb. This system is called countercurrent multiplication.

Question: When the myocardium becomes hypoxic, which process brings about local vasodilation in the coronary arteries?
OptionA: Adenosine binds to type A2 receptors in vascular smooth muscle to increase cAMP and cause vascular smooth muscle relaxation
OptionB: Nitric Oxide is released. Which causes increased cGMP which causes increased activation of a cGMP dependent kinase to bring about smooth muscle relaxation.
OptionC: Sympathetic innervation causes smooth muscle relaxation via a Gi protein coupled receptor.
Explanation:
Adenosine is produced in hypoxia as there is an accumulation of AMP due to less ATP production in aerobic respiration. The enzyme 5'nucleotidase is responsible for converting AMP-->Adenosine. Adenosine then binds to type 2A receptors in VSM couple to a Gs protein. This activates adenyl cyclase, PKA activated. Katp channels open, so hyperpolarisation occurs. The increased cAMP also inhibits myosin light chain klinase so a lower contractile force. Adenosine also binds to type A1 receptors in SAN and AVN coupled to a Gi protein. So Adenyl cyclase is inhibited. This causes K+ channels o open, hyperpolarised so less frequent action potentials. Also thought to inhibit the funny current (HCN4 channel) so a longer phase 4 of pacemaker potential.

Nitric oxide is released from endothelial cells when stimulated by sheer stress, histamine, bradykinin and Ach. These messangers activate a Gs, Adenyl cyclase activated, increased PKA. Increased Ca2+-Calomdulin dependent kinases so Nitric oxide synthase activation. L-arginine converted to L-citruline releases NO which diffuses into smooth muscle. Here, it activates guanyl cyclase so increased cGMP. Causes a lower Ca2+ conc. Also myosin light chain phosphatase activated and K+ channels open so hyperpolarisation.

Question: Mr Man comes in to your surgery for a follow up appointment after his recent prescription for acid-reflux treatment. He says everything is going well, and he has had no more symptoms of indigestion. However, you notice that he has quite a few suspicious bruises on his arms. You ask about them, and he appears not to have noticed. You double check the other medications he is on, and see that he is on an anti-coagulant. Why do you think these bruises have appeared?
OptionA: He is on Cimetidine which interferes with VWF and VIII synthesis
OptionB: He is on Omeprazole which inhibits the enzyme that breaks down Heparin, leading to increased inhibition of Xa
OptionC: He is on Cimetidine which is a CYP450 inhibitor, and impairs Warfarin metabolism
OptionD: The Omeprazole he is on is a CYP450 inhibitor which impairs Heparin metabolism
Explanation:
H2 receptor antagonists such as Cimetidine inhibit CYP450, which impairs Warfarin metabolism. Other side effects of H2 receptor antagonists are gynaecomastia and impotence in men.

 

Omeprazole is a PP. Side effects include diarrhoea, nausea, dizziness and headaches. 

 

All apart from C I made up

differentiation- changes in cell structure and function occur

calor - heat.

Question: Which of the following is responsible for the absolute refractory period during repolarisation?
OptionA: Activation gate of voltage gated sodium channel
OptionB: Inactivation gate of voltage gated sodium channel
OptionC: Activation gate of voltage gated potassium channel
OptionD: Deactivation gate of voltage gated potassium channel
Explanation:
The absolute refractory period refers to a point during an action potential when another action potential cannot be generated. During depolarisation, this is obvious as the neurone is already in the depolarisation phase. During repolarisation, the inactivation gate of voltage gated Na channels results in a closed channel which cannot be opened. Therefore another action potential cannot be initiated.

A is responsible for a Na influx

C is responsible for K efflux

D doesn't exist

 

In Dr Vazquez lecture on Action potentials

OptionB: Loss of innervation from the occulomotor nerve (III) to superior rectus muscle

Question: What type of cartilage is found in the outer ears?
Explanation: elastic cartilage has lots of elastic fibres, it provides strength elasticity and shape, perfect for ears.

Question: What hormone do somatotropes produce?
Explanation:
The somatotropes are cells in the anterior pituitary gland that produce growth hormone.

 

Secretin is produced by the S cells of the duodenum.

 

Somatostatin is produced by the D cells of the duodenum and the D cells of the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. Also in the brain, somatostatin is produced by neuroendocrine neurons of the ventromedial nucleus of the hypothalamus. Note that Somatostatin can actually inhibit growth hormone releasing hormone in the hypothalamus hence inhibit growth hormone release from the anterior pituitary gland. 

 

Dopamine is produced in several areas of the brain, including the substantia nigra and the ventral tegmental area.

 

Adrenocorticotropic hormone is made in the corticotroph cells of the anterior pituitary gland.

Question: What is the rate limiting enzyme for noradrenaline synthesis?
Explanation: Tyrosine hydroxylase is the rate limiting enzyme in noradrenaline production.

Question: Which of the roatator cuff muscles attaches to the middle facet of the greater tubercle of humerus?

Supraspinatus- Originates from supraspinous fossa and inserts to the superior factet of GT. Abducts 1st 15

Subscapulris- originates from subscapular fossa inserts to lesser tubercle of humerus

Teres Major is not a muscle of the rotator cuff

Question: In emphysema the compliance of the lung is:
What is the Dentate Line?
OptionC: Bifurcation of common iliac from Abdominal aorta
Explanation:
The Dentate line marks the transition of endoderm to ectoderm separating the superior 2/3 of rectum (endoderm) from the lower 1/3 (ectoderm). Here the epithelium changes from columnar to stratified sqamous. Above the dentate line the rectum is supplied by the superior rectal artery from the IMA and below the dentate line by the Inferior rectal from the internal pudenal.

McBurneys point marks the location of the appendix and is 1/3 from ASIS to the Umbilicus

The Common iliac arrises at L4 vert. from the abdominal aorta and runs to the sacroiliac join where it bifurcates to the internal and external iliac arteries.

Question: Which artery supplies the lower 1/3 of the rectum?
Explanation:
Below the Dentate line (transition of endoderm to ectoderm) separating upper 2/3 of rectum from lower 2/3 recieves blood from the inferior rectal artery, a branch of the pudenal.

Above the dentate line the supply is from the superior rectal which is a branch of the IMA.

Question: Which artery is NOT a branch of the SMA?
Explanation:
The SMA gives rise to the right and middle colic arteries as well as the ileocecal.

The IMA gives rise to the left colic and sigmoid arteries.

They communicate via a marginal artery which runs parralel to length of colon and gives rise to vasa recta.

Question: Which of the following best describes the process of defecation?
OptionA: Mass peristalsis causes distension of the rectum. This causes a sympathetic reflex via S2,3,4 roots. Causes involuntary opening of internal sphincter and external.
OptionB: Mass peristalsis causes distension of the rectum. Causes a local parasympathetic response via nerve roots S2,3,4. This causes relaxation of internal spincter and contraction of the rectum. There is a parasympathetic urge to relax the external sphincter but voluntary contol.
OptionC: Mass peristalsis causes distension. Stimulates puborectalis to contract which overcomes the action of both sphincters so you can squeeze one out.
OptionD: You go for a hot curry. You wake up the morning after, knowing its bad news. The capsacian in the chilli has activated your TRPV1 receptor, so the rectum contracts to overcome action of sphincter, thus, leaving your toliet in a bad state.
Explanation:
The internal sphincter is under involuntary control via nerve roots S2,3 and 4. A useful mneumonic is "S2,3,4 Keeps the Sh!t off the floor"

Puborectalis loops around the rectum and forms a "kink" which can obstruct stool passage.

Question: When a baby is born it already has a small amount of passive immunity. This is because some immunoglobulins can pass across the placenta from mother to baby. Which immunoglobulins can do this?

Question: Which enzyme is required to convert Glucose-6-Phosphate to free glucose?
OptionC: When it comes to biochemistry, I haven't got a clue-cose
Explanation:
In glycogenolysis, stimulated by glucagon and adrenaline, glycogen phosphorylase glycogen by phosphorylating 1-4 Glycosidic bonds. This cleaves Glucose-1-Phosphate.

Only works if the chain is at least 4 glucose residues long.

Phosphoglucomutase converts G-1-P to G-6-P which can entetr glycolyis.

In the LIVER G-6-P to glucose by Glucose-6-Phosphatase. Muscles lack this enzyme and G6P cannot diffuse across membrane, so any glycogen brakdown in muscle can only provide energy for that muscle, whereas liver can provide glucose for other tissues.

Debranching enzyme=hydrolyses 1-4glycosidic bonds in 4 glucose residue length chains. 3 of them attach elsewhere on the glycogen polymer.

Amylo-alpha-1,6-glucosidase hydrolyses 1-6 glycosidic bonds to release free glucose.

Question: A patient presents with jaundice. Upon testing, they have an increased clotting time and increased AST and ALT. Is this pre, post or hepatic jaundice?
Explanation:
Pre hepatic: Due to haemolysis or unneffective erythroposisis. Signs are increased concentration of unconjugated bilirubin (there is no bili in the urine as it is insolube)

Hepatic: Cause could be Gilbert's syndrome (mutation in UDP-gluconury transferase), Viral infection, Cirrhosis, Autoimmune disease to name a few. Signs are increased clotting time and raised AST+ALT

Post hepatic: Causes are pancreatitis, gall stones, drugs, carcinoma (of head of panc on bile duct), biliary stricture. Signs are dark urine (with biirubin), Pale stools as less stercobillocgen as less stercobillogen. pruitus (itching) due to bile salts leaking into circulation.

Question: Which process stimulates the classical pathway of complement?

Question: You see a patient who has recently suffered a head injury, during examination you ask them to describe a picture of a park, they reply "picnic..flying kite.. house… tree.. pouring water.. boat.. trees.. okay… car".  What is wrong with the patient?
Explanation:
• Both Wernicke’s and Broca’s area are involved in language processing and are present only on the left (dominant) hemisphere
  • Broca’s aphasia - language is halting and non-grammatical (lack of pronouns, articles and conjunctions)
  • Wernicke’s aphasia - language fluent and grammatical but often meaningless, including nonsense words that sound similar to real ones (e.g. ‘You know that smoulder tinkered and that want to get him round and take care of him like you want before’)
  • Aphasia may occur as a result of stroke, severe brain injury or brain tumour  

 

From case 6 auditory pathways lecture
