Question:
Duncan is a 56 year old man who was recently featured in a channel 4 series "Secret Eaters". It was revealed on the show that his BMI of 34 was down to his longstanding lifestyle choices; which included a calorific intake of 3600 calories a day and meals high in saturated fat. In his post- show medical checkup the doctor found that Duncan's serum cholesterol was high enough for him to be prescribed a drug to lower his cholesterol. 

 

 

The doctor considers several drugs. 

 

Which drug is matched to its correct mode of action?
OptionA: Fibrates: Competitive inhibitor of intracellular cholesterol pathway- leading to greater uptake of LDLs from plasma and therefore a decrease in serum cholesterol
OptionB: Bile Acid Sequestrants: Stimulate LPL and HDL activity
OptionC: Statins: Competitive inhibitor of intracellular cholesterol pathway- leading to greater uptake of LDLs from plasma and therefore a decrease in serum cholesterol
OptionD: Fibrates: Inhibit intestinal absorption of cholesterol by binding to components of bile
Explanation:
Statins: Competitive inhibitor of the rate limiting enzyme in the cholesterol biosynthesis pathway. By reducing the synthesis of cholesterol inside the cell it must get its cholesterol from the plasma. The cell removes cholesterol from the plasma and therefore reduces serum cholesterol levels 

 

Fibrates: Stimulate the activity of LPL so cells take up more triglycerides; by increasing HDL levels they promote the reverse cholesterol pathway which leads to more cholesterol being taken back to the liver for excretion in bile salts 

 

Bile Acid Sequestrants: Rarely used anymore but they work by binding to components of bile to prevent it from being reabsorbed from the gut. Less bile reabsorbed means less cholesterol reabsorbed

Question: A woman is about to undergo minor surgery of the vagina. A local anaesthetic is prepared to be injected into a nerve, which nerve would be the most appropriate??

The sensory and motor innervation of the perineum is derived from the pudendal nerve, which is composed of the anterior primary divisions of the second, third, and fourth sacral nerves. The pudendal nerve’s 3 branches include the following:

  1. Dorsal nerve of clitoris, which innervates the clitoris
  2. Perineal branch, which innervates the muscles of the perineum, the skin of the labia majora and labia minora, and the vestibule

1) Monocytes migrate into the intima and differentiate into macrophages

Considering these 5 steps.Place them in chronological order concerning the development of an atherosclerotic plaque that could lead to a MI.

The heart has myogenic actvity which means that  it has an intrinsic ability to beat without an external nervous stimuli. 

 

The SAN is the pacemaker of the cell located in the right atrium 

 

Which statement is incorrect about the SAN ?
OptionA: Depolarization occurs via an influx of Ca2+
OptionB: The "funny current" is activated upon hyperpolarisation and leads to an influx of Na+
OptionD: There are 3 phases for a SAN action potential
OptionE: The pacemaker potential occurs between 2 action potentials
Explanation:
The three phases of an SAN action potential are 4,0 and 3

 

The "funny current" is responsible for the spontaneous depolarization stage (end of Phase 4) . After the end of an AP the membrane is hyperpolarised, this opens Na+ channels which leads to an influx of Na+ into the cell.

 

NOTE!: The Na+ influx causes the membrane to reach the threshold potential. Once the threshold potential has been met Ca+ open 

  • It is the influx of Ca+ in Phase 0 which causes depolarization of the membrane and the firing of an AP 

Phase 3 is repolarisation, it is caused by the closing of Ca+ channels and opening of K+ channels 

 

The cells of the SAN have no resting potential 

  • The resisting potential is the voltage difference across a membrane when the cell is unstimulated 

The SAN is never "unstimulated"; it generates spontaneous action potentials which means it is never at rest

Question: A 2 year old child presents with a fever, irritability, lack of response to quiet sounds and is continuously tugging and rubbing their ear. You inspect the patient's ears using an otoscope (see image below). How would you treat the patient?

The patient's symptoms suggest that they may have otitis media (an infection of the inner ear) - a common condition in young children as the eustachian tube is not fully developed and is easily blocked - leading to infection. In serous otitis media, fluid may build up in the middle ear which can be seen behind the tympanic membrane using an otoscope (usually bubbles). 

  • Antibiotics would be used to clear infection, grommets can be used in serous otitis media to drain fluid from middle ear 
  • Cochlear implants are inserted in patients who have lost hair cell function but still have functioning sensory neurones
  • Please don't remove a patient's pinna!
  • A Stapedectomy is used to treat otosclerosis - insertion of prosthetic stapes to replace calcified stapes causing conductive hearing loss
  • Earwax may be safely removed if it builds up and blocks the ear canal

Brian just passed his test, for the first time. As a 17 year old, he wanted to taste this 'freedom' that all his cool, driving test passing friends are chatting about. So, he ventured out alone in his turbo-engined, tinted windowed Renault Clio (in metallic blue) for the first time on the big old dangerous roads. Brian's bad-ass and he didn't want to use the green p plates (who wants to declare to the world that they've just passed their test?- lame).  Brian thought he'd better stick to the national speed limit of 60mph to gain the respect of others on the road. He took a scenic route where the roads were narrow and windy. He underestimated the bend ahead- silly Brian- so, he crashed. Yet another Renault Clio gone to waste (RIP). He was crying due to the shock of losing his Clio. He was also crying because he was in a lot of pain. It was determined that he had sustained a left brachial plexus injury. After initial recovery it was observed that  his diaphragm functions normally, there was no winging of the scapula but abduction cannot be initiated. However, if the arm is helped through the first 45 degrees of abduction, Brian can fully abduct the arm. So where on earth has Brian injured his brachial plexus?
Explanation:
Let's take the observations one by one to break down this question.

  • If the diaphragm is functioning normally, you know that the phrenic nerve is probably uninjured, which means that the C5 root has not been damaged.
  • Since the scapula is not winged, there was no damage to the long thoracic nerve or the C5-7 nerve roots.
  • Since the patient cannot initiate abduction of the arm, you know that the suprascapular nerve is injured and supraspinatus has been denervated. But, the patient can abduct the arm once it is lifted to 45 degrees, so the deltoid muscle and the axillary nerve must be intact.

Taking the answer choices one by one: The axillary nerve is ok, because deltoid is functioning. The posterior cord of the brachial plexus must also be intact, since this cord gives off the axillary nerve. The roots of the brachial plexus are ok, since the phrenic nerve and long thoracic nerve (which are derived from the roots) are still functioning. The superior trunk of the brachial plexus must also be undamaged, since this trunk contributes to the posterior cord which is intact. So, this means that the injury must be to the suprascapular nerve.

You encounter a patient in A&E who reports that they have have taken 10g or so of paracetamol in a suicide attempt but she has changed her mind after having an epiphany about her life. She arrived an hour after tang the dose. What is the next best management option to  deal with the overdose?
OptionA: Give the patient activated charcoal to absorb the paracetamol and check serum paracetamol 3 hours later  since they have referred within 4 hours of overdosing but don't give the patient NAC until until after the full 4 hours from overdose have occurred
OptionB: Give the patient n-acetylcysteine immediately to combat the paracetamol overdose and give the patient activated charcoal to absorb the paracetamol and check serum paracetamol 3 hours later since they have referred within 4 hours of overdosing
OptionC: Do nothing; the patient has not gone over the lethal limit of 12g and can only be given palliative care to ease her pain
OptionD: Wait until measuring the patient's serum paracetamol levels 3 hours later and then begin adding n-acetyl cysteine accordingly to the paracetamol levels
OptionE: Give the patient activated charcoal to absorb the paracetamol after serum paracetamol levels are recorded 3 hours later
Explanation:
Patients presenting less than four hours after ingestion of a large quantity of paracetamol should receive activated charcoal. The first paracetamol level should be drawn four hours after ingestion. Treatment with N-acetylcysteine within 8 hours guarantees survival in any case and should also be started as soon as impossible according to british research by the BMJ.

Metabolism of paracetamol depletes glutathione and forms toxic metabolites that accumulate in the liver and cause necrosis. This effect is exacerbated by chronic alcohol, which induces formation of cytochrome P450 enzymes and accelerates the production of harmful metabolites. If acetaminophen ingestion occurred less than 4 hours ago, activated charcoal should be given to reduce absorption. Serum paracetamol levels should be drawn four hours after ingestion and the result should be applied to the Rumack-Matthew nomogram, which predicts the risk of hepatotoxic effects and guide therapy. N-acetylcysteine works as an antidote by regenerating glutathione and may be given at any time within the first 8 hours after ingestion without sacrificing efficacy.

Question: With a patient undergoing difficulty in inducing labour over a week past the due by date, you decide to use a PGE analogue of dinoprost to try to induce labour via uterine contractions. How will this be given to the patient?

Uterine muscle contractility sensitivity to Prostaglandins increases in pregnancy, hence PGE analogues  such as dinoprost and misoprostol can be provided intravaginally to induce labour via coordinated uterine contractions.

Oxytocin, a posterior pituitary hormone, can also be provided by slow IV infusions to induce waves of uterine contractions.

Question: A patient who requires an abortifacient is given a high dose of mifepristone along with a second drug, that is there to prevent obstetric bleeding via vasoconstriction? What drug is this most likely to be?
Explanation:
Gemeprost, Dinoprost and misoprostol are all PGE analogues. However, only gemeprost, PGE1 analogue is used with mifepristone to help address the obstetric bleeding that can occur thanks to the large progesterone dose as the drug.

Dinoprost and misoprostol are PGE analogues given intravaginally as gels to induce labour as they produce waves of coordinated contractions. In pregnancy, the uterus becomes sensitive to PGEs, hence these drugs can induce uterine contractions.

Question: Simon is on his Bronze D of E expedition and finds himself getting tired and running out breath.  For a second, he wonders what actually controls his breathing. Help Simon determine where the "respiratory centre" is located.
OptionD: Medulla Oblongata and parts of the Pons
OptionE: Medulla Oblongata and parts of the Midbrain
Explanation:
The "respiratory centre" is located in the Medulla Oblongata and the parts of the Pons.  This centre receives neuronal, chemical and hormonal signals and controls the rate and depth of respiratory movements of the diaphragm and other respiratory muscles.  

 

Initially, I thought it was just located in the Medulla, however, after research I found that it was in both the Medulla and Pons.  Don't worry we don't need to know this for the exam - but for those who are interested:

 

- Inspiratory Centre Location = Dorsal portion of Medulla

 

- Expiratory Centre Location = Antero-lateral part of the Medulla

 

- Pneumotaxic Centre (Controls rate and pattern of breathing) = Upper part of Pons

 

- Apneustic Centre (discharges stimulatory impulse to inspiratory centre causing inspiration) = Lower part of Pons
Tags: Respiratory physiology, Case 5, Pulmonary, Lung function

BMI between 18.5-24.9: this is a healthy range. It shows that you're a healthy weight for your height. 
BMI score of 25 or more: your BMI is above the ideal range and this score means you may be overweight.

Question: Which cells produce inhibin?
Chylomicrons transport fat and cholesterol from the gut to the Liver and adipose tissue. What happens when the triglyceride content of these chylomicrons decreases to around 20%?
OptionC: ApoC is lost, Chylomicron becomes Chylomicron remnant
OptionD: ApoE is lost, Chylomicron becomes Chylomicron remnant
Explanation:
In adipose: ApoC binds to Lipoprotein Lipase on endothelial cells - triglycerides are cleaved into fatty acids and glycerol. These products are absorbed into the adipocyte. As chylomicron's triglyceride content reduces to around 20%, they lose apoC and become Chylomicron Remnants. Chylomicron remnants then travel to the liver where they bind their apoE with the Chylomicron remnant receptor. The Liver then takes up this Chylomicron remnant. 

 

In the Liver the Chylomicron can bind straight with the LDL receptor using its apoE protein, to then be taken up and used by the liver.

Question: As a GP, you are reviewing one of your patients, Mrs Jones. She is 55 years old, overweight and smokes, and has been complaining of breathlessness and chest pain when she is walking to the shops. You decide that given her high risk of a cardiovascular event, she should begin aspirin. When you prescribe it, she is confused and says she thought aspirin was for stopping swelling. Explanation:

C- the COX domain of PGGS- this isn't a real enzyme as far as I'm aware

D- phospholipase A2 is involved in the synthesis of prostaglandin H2 but is responsible for cleaving membrane phospholipids to produce arachidonic acid- an earlier step.

E- CORRECT- NSAIDs and aspirin both inhibit this, preventing the first step of PGHS in which arachidonic acid is converted to prostaglandin G. The production of prostaglandin H2 is involved both in platelet aggregation and inflammation.

Question: You are at home over the summer holidays and start talking to your 60 year old neighbour. She starts telling you about her problems at home following the death of her husband. During the conversation, a car drives by and your neighbour says "How peculiar, that car has no wheels", even though the car does in fact have wheels. What is the correct terminology for her symptom?
Explanation:
A) Compulsions are repetitive and behaviours with a degree of apparent purpose, and are therefore associated with obsessional behaviour which comprises of thoughts that enter the mind. People often try to (unsuccessfully) resist obsessions.

 

B) Delusions: A belief firmly held despite evidence to the contrary. Must be inappropriate in terms of cultural beliefs. For example if believing in reincarnation is culturally appropriate, it is not a delusion. Example: "I can fly"

 

C) Hallucinations are sensory perceptions (e.g. visual auditory) occurring in the absence of an external stimulus: in contrast to illusions which are misperceptions of external stimuli

 

D) Illusion: misperception of a “real” external stimulus e.g. seeing the a car travelling with no wheels (although the car is there). Differentiated from a hallucination by the fact it is a "misperception" of a real physical stimulus.

 

E) Overvalued ideas are thoughts which can then lead to changes in behaviour or actions which are neither obsessional nor delusional. Praying an unusually large amount of time is an example: the praying may be consistent with the religious belief but not the extent which its being taken.

Question: What are the consequences of the pathology shown in this image?

OptionC: Less compliant lung due to an inability to produce pulmonary surfactant
OptionD: More compliant lung due to an inability to produce pulmonary surfactant

Explanation:
Image shows Hyaline membrane Disease, characterized by thick membranes lining the alveolar sacs. This disease presents within the first few hours of the life of a premature baby.

 

Pathophysio:  type 2 alveolar cells do not produce pulmonary surfactant which as we all know, decreases surface tension by preventing hydrogen bonding of water molecules. So a lack of it means more surface tension and thus, a less compliant lung. You get damaged and necrotic cells.

Question: A man comes into your neurology clinic who you suspect has a lesion to his upper facial nerve on the right side of his brain (in the corticobulbar tract). What would you expect to see?
OptionA: Total paralysis of the left side of his face
OptionB: Total paralysis of the right side of his face
OptionC: Paralysis of the lower part of the left side of his face, with forehead sparing
OptionD: Paralysis of the lower part of the right side of his face, with forehead sparing
Explanation:
-The lesion would affect the contralateral side of his face, ie the left side, because the facial nerves cross over to synapse on contralateral lower motor neurones in the pons

-The lesion would cause paralysis of the facial muscles

-The lesion would only affect the lower part of the face, with forehead sparing, because not all of the upper motor neurones cross over. Some synapse onto the ipsilateral lower motor neurones supplying the forehead, meaning that the facial nerve in the left side of the patient's brain can still supply his forehead with innervation. However the ipsilateral facial nerve does not supply facial expression muscles below the eyes so the lower part of the face would be paralysed. Hope this picture helps-

Question: Which phases are involved in the action potentials generated in the sinoatrial node?
Explanation:
Sinoatrial node action potentials have:

Phase 4 - resting membrane potential (sodium ions leak into the cell via funny/pacemaker channels)

Phase 0 - depolarisation (influx of calcium ions via voltage gated calcium channels - T-type first followed by L-type)

Phase 3 - repolarisation (potassium ions leave the cell [counteracting sodium influx] and calcium channels close)

 

Most cardiac cell action potentials have:

Phase 4 - resting membrane potential (potassium ions leak out; when nearby cell depolarises sodium and calcium ions enter the cell via gap junctions)

Phase 0 - depolarisation (threshold is reached and voltage gated sodium channels open)

Phase 1 - slight repolarisation (sodium channels close and voltage gated potassium channels open)

Phase 2 - plateau (voltage gated calcium channels open and membrane potential levels as calcium enters the cell and potassium leaves it)

Phase 3 - repolarisation (voltage gated calcium channels close and the efflux of potassium continues)

Question:
Leptin is a hormone secreted from adipose tissue that helps to regulate energy balance by inhibiting hunger. An obese person has a decreased sensitivity to leptin meaning they can always be felling hungry.

 

Leptin has also been linked to the onset of puberty. Having enough body fat seems to be a crucial indicator that the body is ready to become sexually mature.

 

Considering the infromation above, identify the correct statement(s) below
OptionA: Leptin and Ghrelin work on the same receptors in the hypothalamus to inhibit hunger
OptionB: Obese girls may have an earlier onset of puberty
OptionC: Those who produce no leptin will never enter puberty
OptionD: Obese girls may end up with a tall stature
Explanation:
A: incorrect - Although the two hormones work on the same receptors in the hypothalamus to regulate appetite, they have opposing actions. Ghrelin is the hunger hormone (makes you fell hungry)... It is mentioned in Case 3

 

B: correct- Obese girls will have more adipose tissue meaning they produce more leptin. Once a certain level of leptin is being produced the body will start to enter puberty

 

C: correct - Those who produce no leptin will ever enter puberty, this is how the link between leptin and puberty was established 

 

D: Incorrect: If you consider the fact that B is correct. If the girl enters puberty early (before she has finished growing) she will start to produce high levels of oestrogen. Oestrogen in females is responsible for the closure of the epiphyses. The early closure of the growth plates will mean the girl will have short stature 

 

E: CORRECT! B & C are correct statements

Question:
Tim is having a wild Friday night in the disco room in Pryzm, when suddenly "Reach for the stars" by S Club 7 starts playing. As the chorus begins, his friend Alex knocks him out as he was attempting to reach for the stars, and Tim hits his head badly on the disco room floor. Tim wakes up, realising a drooping of his left eye, he holds his eyelid open, looks in the mirror and is greeted by this: 

Which cranial nerve has Tim damaged? (P.S. don't judge Tim by his age, the disco room is welcome to anyone and everyone.)
Explanation:
Tim has damaged his oculomotor nerve. This causes ptosis, drooping of the upper eyelid; strabismus, a deviation of the eye in which both eyes do not fix on the same object; dilation of the pupil; movement of the eyeball downward and outward on the damaged side; loss of accommodation for near vision; and diplopia, double vision.

 

A) Abducens (VI) Nerve damage would result in: affected eyeball unable to move laterally beyond the midpoint, eye is usually directed medially.

B) Facial (VII) Nerve damage due to viral infection (shingles) or a bacterial infection (Lyme disease) produces Bell's Palsy (paralysis of the facial muscles), loss of taste, decreased salivation, and loss of ability to close the eyes, even during sleep.

C) Optic (II) Nerve damage can cause visual field defects and loss of visual acuity. Blindness due to a defect in or loss of one or both eyes is called anopia. 

E) Glossopharyngeal (IX) Nerve results in difficulty swallowing; reduced secretion of saliva; loss of sensation in the throat, and a loss of taste sensation.

Question: A woman comes into your GP surgery and tells you that she obtained a dodgy pill from one of her Cardiff Met pals. She took the pill and headed off to Metro's, but didn't have a great night and is now complaining of a strange problem with her eyesight. You examine the surprisingly informative leaflet that has come with her dodgy pill and find that it is a drug known to kill the cones of the eye. Therefore, what's this girl likely to be complaining of?
OptionD: Ability to see colours but only very blurry
Explanation:
The cones in the eye are responsible for seeing colours, whilst the rods are responsible for seeing light (black and white). Therefore loss of the patient's cones in her eyes will cause her to only see in black and white.

 

She won't be buying drugs from a Met student again.

Question: Mr Khan comes into A&E, on the insistence of his wife, with a problem with his left eye. The eye is deviated outwards and downwards and on examination, the eye does not have a light reflex for the light being shone into either eye. The pupil is dilated; why is this feature a worrying sign?
OptionC: May have a posterior communicating artery aneurysm
Explanation: The parasympathetic fibres of the occulomotor nerve, which innervate sphincter pupillae, have been damaged causing the absent light reflex and pupil dilation. Because these fibres travel superficially in CNIII, damage suggests physical compression rather than intrinsic nerve damage, as might occur with diabetes. Posterior communicating artery aneurysm is a typical source of compression of CNIII.

Question: What would the response of the body be, in order to buffer the urine in a respiratory acidosis.
OptionA: Excreting H+ from the proximal convoluted tubule.
OptionB: Secreting cacitriol to increase calcium and phosphate reabsorption
OptionC: Secreting parathyroid hormone to increase calcium reuptake and reduce phosphate reabsorption
OptionD: Secrete less H+ into tubular fluid in the loop of Henle
Explanation:
After a few hours, the renal system would attempt to compensate the respiratory acidosis by increase plasma pH. To do this it would need to excrete H+ (this H+ will need to be buffered in the urine).

A- H+ secretion into the tubule only takes place in the distal convoluted tubule. In the proximal convoluted tubule it is used to attract HCO3- ions which will then be converted to H2CO3. H2CO3 then dissociates into H20 and CO2 and CO2 is absorbed into the tubular cells.

B- An increase in phosphate reabsorption would mean that there is less phosphate in the urine to buffer H+. The kidney cannot excrete free H+. Less H+ would be secreted into the tubule.

C- is correct because an increase in tubular phosphate would allow more H+ to be secreted out of the cell.

D- H+ secretion does not take place in the loop of Henle.

The little finger is normally shortened due to posterior displacement of the distal part of the fracture. Fracture of the scaphoid and lunate is caused by falling on an outstreched hand (FOOSH) and fracture of the 1st metacarpal is known as Bennett's fracture- the base is fractured due to hyper abduction of the thumb.

Question: The posterior pituitary gland does not synthesise any hormones. However, it does store and release 2 hormones upon stimulation from the hypothalamus. What are these two hormones?
Explanation:
Oxytocin and ADH (vasopressin) are hormones which are synthesised within cell bodies of large neurones in the hypothalamus. They are secreted from the posterior pituitary gland in response to nerve impulses.

 

The other hormones are all derived from the anterior pituitary gland. There are 5 different cell types within the anterior pituitary, which altogether produce 7 hormones: 

FSH and LH = Gonadotrophs

TSH = Thyrotrophs

GH = Somatotrophs

ACTH = Corticotrophs

Prolactin = Lactotrophs

Question:
Steve went out on the lash last night and had one too many drinks. On returning home, he started to feel sweaty, dizzy and tachycardic. His mate Sam told him he looked very pale and urged him to sit down. Steve made it to the bathroom just in time to vomit.

 

The symptoms Steve experienced just before vomiting (sweating, tachycardia, peripheral vasoconstriction and dizziness) are all common autonomic responses that preceed vomiting (emesis). He may have also experienced a sudden increase in salivation known as waterbrash.

 

What part of the brain coordinates the vomiting reflex?
OptionA: Vomiting nucleus in the pons (comprising of the ventral part of the reticular formation and the nucleus solitarius)
OptionC: Vomiting centre in medulla oblongata (comprising of the dorsal part of the reticular formation and the nucleus solitarius)
OptionD: Dorsal respiratory group and nucleus of tractus solitarius
Explanation:
The vomiting centre is located in the medulla oblongata and comprises of the dorsal part of the reticular formation and the nucleus of the tractus solitarius.

The autonomic responses this evokes are carried in:

- Cranial nerves V, VII, XII, X and XII to the upper GI tract.

- In vagal and sympathetic nerves to the lower GI tract.

- In spinal nerves to the diaphragm and abdominal muscles.

 


A - incorrect (see above)

B - Incorrect (made up)

C - Correct (see above)

D - Incorrect - although the nucleus of tractus solitarius is involved

E - Incorrect - this is a group of nuclei involved in serotonin release among many other things (thought to be important in mood and sleep)

Question:
A 45 y/o man complains of shortness of breath and a cough that has been bothering him a lot.
Reading his spirometry, it show a reduced FEV1 and FVC, with a normal PEFR and FEV1/FVC ratio of >75%.


Which one of these is NOT linked with his abnormal spirometry results?
Explanation:
Sorry for making it a "NOT" question, I know they annoy people and we won't get a question like it in an exam as it can confuse some. Don't hate.
But for the sake of thinking the process...

 

Answer is C: Bronchiectasis.

↓ FEV1 and FVC shows a restrictive abnormality.

RESTRICTIVE LUNG DISORDERS

  • PEFR can be normal as airway patency is not affected.
  • ↓ FEV1 and ↓ FVC → the restrictive condition means a decrease in lung volume, an increased work of breathing, and inadequate ventilation and/or oxygenation.
  • Conditions include: neuromuscular diseases (e.g. MND), connective tissue diseases, late-stage sarcoidosis, pleural effusion, fibrosing alveolitis and pleural thickening.

OBSTRUCTIVE LUNG DISORDERS

  • FEV1/FVC ratios is ↓ - HOWEVER FVC can be normal/reduced, but a thing to note is that FEV1 ↓ more than FVC does.
  • Patients take longer to fully exhale.
  • As the name implies, it is due to an 'obstruction' which narrows the smaller and larger bronchioles.
  • Conditions include: COPD, asthma and bronchiectasis.
  • It can also be due to: foreign bodies and tumours.


I may have written this question, but I still get confused. 


GoodLuck to everyone for the exams!
Tags: Respiratory physiology, PCS, PCS Unit2, Case 5

Question: An 85 year old woman, Betty, was recently discharged from hospital following a complicated UTI caused by E. coli infection. She now presents to your GP surgery with bruises all along her arms, and shows you a small cut on her finger which has been taking a long time to heal. You suspect she might have a vitamin K deficiency causing reduced clotting, which would explain why she is bruising so easily and healing slowly. Why do you suspect this?
OptionA: Elderly patients tend to eat less fresh food and less balanced diet- might be a dietary vitamin K deficiency
OptionB: She may have developed septicaemia from her UTI
OptionC: Disruption of intestinal microflora caused by the antibiotics used to treat her UTI
Explanation:
The best answer here is disruption of her intestinal microflora. Dietary vitamin K deficiencies are very rare as it is found in a lot of vegetables, meat, dairy and fruit. Deficiency is more commonly caused by problems with the intestinal microflora, which actually produce vitamin K themselves.

 

The fact that Betty had an E. coli infection suggests she would be treated with antibiotics targetting gram-negative bacteria, which also tend to disrupt bowel microflora as many enteric bacteria are gram-negative (the go-to treatment would be an aminoglycoside, eg gentamicin).

Question: Which of these is not a feature of the pericardium?
OptionD: Enables the heart to beat in a frictionless environment
OptionE: Consists of a fibrous outer layer and an inner visceral layer only
Explanation:
The walls of the pericardium from outside to in are: 

 

Fibrous Pericardium: Tough external layer which binds with the central tendon of the diaphragm; protecting against infection from other organs (e.g. lungs) and sudden overfilling 

 

Parietal Layer: Option E missed this layer; lines the outside inside of the fibrous pericardium and is separated from the visceral layer by a potential space (pericardial cavity) which is filled with a small amount of fluid and allows the heart to beat in a frictionless environment.

 

  • If fluid builds up in the percardial cavity it is called a pericardial effusion; if there is so much fluid that the heart is being compressed and filling is being compromised, it is called a cardiac tamponade


Visceral Layer: Together with the parietal layer they form the serous serous membrane. The visceral layer cannot be dissected from the surface of the heart and is also synonymous with the epicardium

Question:
Rob, a 14 year old boy is brought into your clinic. You immediately notice that he is short for his age and his skin is covered in lesions, which he tells you take a long time to heal. On further examination you establish that he is showing no signs of normal sexual development. He also tells you that he cannot smell or taste very well. You notice a couple of bald patches on his head (alopecia).

 

What's causing his symptoms?
Explanation:
These are all symptoms of zinc deficiency. Deficiency can be caused by severe burns and renal damage, or can be genetic (this is what Rob has). The genetic condition is called acrodermatitis enteropathica. Renal damage can cause zinc deficiency due to the albumin that is allowed to leak into the urine, lowering serum albumin and preventing zinc circulation around the body. Burns and trauma cause increased metallothionine synthesis, depleting zinc supplies.

 

Metallothionine is also needed to bind to zinc, copper, iron and other metal ions in the intestines to facilitate their absorption.

Question:
You're on your first week working on A&E and you see a 65 y/o male, who is short of breath and evidently appears to have a dry cough. He is a smoker and you find that he has been unintentionally losing weight for the past 7 months. On examination, he has a reduced chest expansion on his right side, with dull percussion and absent breath sounds at the right base.

Considering the history noted for this man, what is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
His history:

- SOB and dry cough.

- ↓ chest expansion on the right side.

- dull percussion and absent breath sounds at right base.

- smoker.

- unintentional weight loss.

 

So let's think about it:

 

ATELECTASIS - defence expansion and collapse of lung.

 

 

- Then you ask, isn't pneumothorax also lung collapse? Yes, pneumothorax can also be called a collapse lung, HOWEVER, the difference between the two is that in pneumothorax, it involves puncture of the pleural lining of the lung, releasing air into the chest cavity (like an injury during sports or being stabbed). Atelectasis is a collapsed lung → unable to expand → shrink/cave in. The other lung will compensate for the time being whilst the other has collapsed.

 

May occur as result of:

  • Obstruction.
  • Compression.
  • Scarring.
  • Surfactant loss.

On inspection:

  • Cough.
  • Delayed chest expansion on the affected side.
  • ↑ pulse.
  • ↑ respiratory rate.

 Smokers and elderly are at increased risk of Atelectasis.


Hope the question got you guys thinking about the patterns in the finding upon examination. 

PeaceOut.

A 34-year-old woman visits her GP with the complaint that over the past 6 months she has “felt out of breath and dizzy while walking, even after short distances.” She reports no other medical problems and denies taking any medications, recreational drugs, alcohol or tobacco. Her BMI is 24kg/m2. On physical examination, the patient has a loud second heart sound over the left upper sternal border, increased jugular venous pressure, and a palpable right ventricular impulse. Which of the following is the patient most at risk of developing if her condition is allowed to persist for a prolonged period
Explanation:
The patient’s presentation is consistent with pulmonary hypertension. If allowed to progress, pulmonary hypertension can eventually lead to right heart failure.

Pulmonary hypertension is defined as an increase in pressures in the pulmonary vasculature. In this 34-year-old woman with no significant lung or cardiac history, her pulmonary hypertension is most likely a result of primary pulmonary hypertension. Right ventricular hypertrophy and subsequently right ventricular failure (cor pulmonale) can occur as the right ventricle tries to pump against the increased pressures of the pulmonary vasculature.

The 3C end product is Propinyl CoA and this is converted into Succinyl CoA.

D this is false

Question:
Beta Oxidation involves the activation of Fatty Acids. This process is achieved by adenylation of the fatty acid and combination of the fatty acid with CoA-SH. 

 

The Adenylation process is reversible but made irreversible how?
OptionA: The enzyme involved in adenylation, acyl CoA synthetase is phosphorylated by Sauron to activate its super powers. Therfore delta G is negative.
OptionB: The pyrophase produced in the hydrolysis of ATP to AMP is broken down into an inorganic phosphate. Therefore the equivalent of two ATP molecules are hydrolysed and the delta G is positive.
OptionC: The pyrophosphate produced in the hydrolysis of ATP to AMP is broken down into an inorganic phosphate. Therefore the equivalent of two ATP molecues are hydrolysed and the delta G is negative.
OptionD: The reaction relies on a large number of substrate and a small number of product, therefore by Chateiler's principle the reaction will move in the direction of the forward reaction (the production of acyl-CoA).
Explanation:
The PPi produced undergoes a hydroysis to produce inorganic phosphate releasing more energy, i.e. making the reaction more exothermic.

 

Delta G = Delta H - T Delta S 

 

H = enthalpy

T= temperature in Kelvin 

S = entropy

 

Since the reaction is made more exothermic, Delta H is more negative and Delta G then becomes more negative and so the reaction becomes irreversible.

 

 

D is incorrect since the reaction will still be reversible even if the reaction is shifted in the forward direction.

Question: Jason Bourne has just sustained severe trauma to the brain following a mission. The resulting stroke and operation leads to damage to his right S1 and S2 cortices. As he attempts to escape from the hospital, he engages in combat again. Due to the damage received to his brain, how will Bourne interpret the painful stimuli in his left hand?
OptionA: He will be able to sense where the "pain" is, but will not be able to feel an unpleasant sensation as a result of it
OptionB: Bourne cannot sense where the pain is (e.g when his hand is taken impact) but is aware of the unpleasant sensation of pain in his brain.
OptionC: Bourne should be able to both sense where he is receiving pain in his hand and feel the unpleasantness of the pain in his brain.
OptionD: He may receive a slight delay in receiving the unpleasantness of pain due to the brain damage, but can still sense where the pain is.
OptionE: Bourne should not be able to sense any pain in his hand, as his brain damage renders him identical to a patient with congenital analgesia.
Explanation:
This situation mirrors a patient described Andrew Lawrence who described an individual with post stroke lesion of right S1 & S2 cortices, who  reported normal pain sensations to laser stimulation applied outside affected area but with application of noxious heat to affected hand was “clearly unpleasant,” such that the patient wanted to avoid the stimulus, but he would not describe it as “pain,” even when given choices from menus of words describing pain. Thus, whereas the somatosensory discrimination of pain was absent due to the stroke, unpleasantness associated with noxious stimuli remained.

In Bourne's case, the loss of sensory recognition would be presented in the left affected hand, but not the feeling of unpleasantness. As the nerve supply for the somatosensory cortices cross over, his left hand will be the one affected.

Question:
The pH of the blood must be maintained between certain values to ensure that essential life processes are not affected. Both significant increases and decreases in pH can have serious consequences. 

 

Which of the following states of acidosis/alkalosis is not correctly matched with a potential cause?
Explanation:
Respiratory Acidosis: Neuromusclar disease can cause respiratory muscle weakness which can lead to hypoventilation. The build up of CO2 causes acidosis 

 

Respiratory Alkalosis: (not acidosis) is a result of high altitude. The low O2 levels at high altitude stimulate peripheral chemoreceptors to increase the rate of ventilation (hyperventilation). However hyperventilation means that you are getting rid of CO2 faster than you are producing it. This leads to an increase in pH as more CO2 is lost. 

 

Metabolic Acidosis: Renal failure may cause an increase excretion of the buffering HCO3. This means that CO2 in the blood is less buffered and causes an decrease in pH 

 

Metabolic Acidosis: Any acids added to the blood such as ketoacids in diabetes will reduce the pH of the blood 

 

Metabolic Alkalosis: Loss of acid will cause alkalosis. For example via the chronic use of antacids or pyloric stenosis  in babies (where there is a blockage of food at the pylorus causing the newborn to vomit a lot)

Question:
Down at a BioSci lab session you perform an experiement to determine the Vmax and Km for a particular substrate with a particular enzyme. Using your results you plot a double reciprocal graph of your results. As you get ready to pack up, one of the helpers approaches you and asks how the experiment and graph  would be affected if a competitive inhibitor was added. 

 

Which one of these statements is correct about the addition of a competitive inhibitor?
OptionA: The affinity of the enzyme for the original substrate will decrease
OptionB: Slope of the reciprocal graph would increase
OptionD: The y- intercept of the graph would remain the same
Explanation:
A competitive inhibitor binds to the active site of an enzyme preventing the binding of the original substrate. 

 

This means that the enzymes affinity for the original substrate will decrease

  • it is less likely the original substrate will bind to the enzyme to form a complex when a competeive inhibitor is present 

 

Km is a reflection of how well the enzyme binds to a substrate (affinity)

  • Km and affinity are inversley proportional 
  • A low Km reflects a high affinity 
  • A high Km reflects a low affinity 

 

Vmax is the maximum possible reaction velocity and is not affected by the addition of a competitive inhibitor.

  • The y- intercept on a double recirpocal graph is 1/Vmax 
  • If Vmax does not change neither will 1/Vmax and therefore neither will the y- intercept of the graph

Question:
A 40 y/o male comes into your clinic complaining that he finds it difficult to do activities that seem simple to his friends. Observing him, you see that he is uneasy and keeps on coughing, but otherwise he is generally still/normal (i.e. not supporting himself on a table). Appearance-wise, he is overweight and has pursed lips. You also notice that he does not open his mouth properly when speaking.

 

His Xray:

 

What would be the most likely diagnosis based on your gatherings of this man's case?
Explanation:
The male patient is likely to have Chronic Bronchitis.

 

Things to note:

- ↓ Exercise tolerance.
- Uneasy.

- Overweight.

- Pursed lips.

- Does not open mouth properly.

- Chronic cough.

 

The CXR shows:

- Hyperinflated lungs - you can see past the 7th anterior rib (although the CXR does not show the intervertebral spaces very well).

- Flattened hemidiaphragms on both sides.

- Small areas of ↑ opacities on the hilar region.

The CXR show hyperinflation and flattened hemi-diaphragms, so straight away you think COPD. Notes from his consultation also point towards COPD.
COPD is an umbrella term that includes: emphysema and chronic bronchitis.
His CXR does show opacities in the hilar region and this is a finding you would also find in TB, however, TB would have fibrosis which this clearly does not show. TB patient would also present with weight loss, which is the opposite for this guy.


Question is simple, as you all probably would guess COPD. I know emphysema and chronic bronchitis are similar and they do often overlap, but the differential diagnosis would probably be due to a few factors.The opacities would be calcification due to heavy smoking and the staining, pursed lips, and the mouth (not opening may indicate teeth staining he would not want to show) which all point to heavy smoking as well. Heavy smoking is mainly linked with chronic bronchitis.

 

 

They both present with kind of the same signs and symptoms. 

Generally, the main point with chronic bronchitis is mucus hyper secretion thus you would expect a whole lot more productive coughing. Also, chronic bronchitis patients are generally overweight and cyanosed: Blue Boaters, and the patient is not huffing and puffing (as you would find with 'Pink puffers' of emphysema).

 

Other findings for general COPD include:

- CO2 retention flap.

- Raised JVP.

- FEV1/FVC ↓.

- May find staining on his hands due to smoking (95% of COPD linked with smoking).

Question:
A 15 year old boy falls off his skate board after attempting to pull a 'sweet trick' off a park bench.

 

Upon falling through the bench he sustains multiple abrasions across the anterior compartment of the knee and deep puncture wounds to the posterior compartment of the right calf. 

 

On examination he is unable to invert or plantar flex is right foot, and describes a lack of sensation across the sole of his foot.

 

What nerve has he most likely damaged?
Explanation:
The tibial nerve controls foot inversion and plantar flexion

 

 

Hip flexion ---- Iliopsoas ---- Femoral nerve, and L1-L3 nerve roots

 

Knee extension ----  Quadriceps -------- Femoral nerve L2, L3, L4

 

Knee flexion------- Hamstrings (semitendinosus, semimembranosus, biceps femoris) ------- Sciatic nerve L5, S1, S2

 

Leg abduction -------- Gluteus medius Gluteus minimus, Tensor fasciae latae ------- Superior gluteal nerve L4, L5, S1

 

Leg adduction--------  Obturator externus, Adductor longus, magnus, and brevis, Gracilis ------- Obturator nerve L2, L3, L4

 

Toe dorsiflexion -------- Extensor hallucis longus, Extensor digitorum longus------- Deep peroneal nerve L5, S1

 

Foot dorsiflexion -------- Tibialis anterior--------- Deep peroneal nerve L4, L5

 

Foot plantar flexion -------- Triceps surae (gastrocnemius, soleus) ----------Tibial nerve S1, S2

 

Foot eversion --------- Peroneus longus Peroneus brevis -------- Superficial peroneal nerve L5, S1

 

Foot inversion -------- Tibialis posterior ---------- Tibial nerve

 

source - http://www.neuroexam.com/neuroexam/content.php?p=29

Question:
7 year old Jack has been diagnosed with extrinsic asthma triggered by exposure to pollen. Although advised to reduce contact with the stimuli this can be difficult during summer months. The doctor prescribes him with a bronchodilator. 

 

Bronchodilators may be endogenous (naturally occurring in the body) or administered medicines and help to dilate the airways. 

 

The doctor decides to give Jack a beta 2 - agonist. Identify its mode of action.
OptionA: A steroid hormone that initiates a negative feedback mechanism on the immune system
OptionC: Reduce the effects of the vagus nerve
OptionD: Stimulate Gs to increase cAMP and PKA levels to increase heart rate
OptionE: Stimulate the adenylyl cylase pathway to increase cAMP and promote smooth muscle relaxation
Explanation:
A: Glucocoticoids increases the expression of anti- inflammatory proteins while down- regulating the expression of pro-inflammatory cells. They are used to treat disease caused by an overactive immune system (asthma allergies) but is not recommended for mild asthma. 

 

B: Methylxanthines inhibit phosphdiesterase which would normally break down cAMP. The drug therefore increases intracellular levels of cAMP. cAMP decreases the [Ca2+] in the cells and promotes myosin light chain phosphatase activity to cause smooth muscle relaxation 

 

C: Muscarinic Antagonists are derived from atropine (deadly night shade) and are competitive inhibitors of ACh. ACh is released from parasympathetic nerve fibers in the vagus nerve to cause bronchconstriction. By inhibiting this process; antagonsist cause dilation 

 

D: This would be a beta 1- agonist 

 

E: Beta-2 Agonist stimulate beta 2 adrenergic receptors on bronchial smooth muscle to cause relaxation. It activates the adenyly cyclase pathway to increase cAMP levels. cAMP decrease Ca2+ concentrations in the cell and activates myosin light chain phosphatase
Tags: Respiratory, Respiratory physiology, Case 5, Pharmacology, Pulmonary

Question: Your friend has just had treatment for his hyperhidrosis (excessive sweating). He tells you that the treatment involved an injection of botulinum toxin, also known as botox. What is the mechanism of action of botox?
OptionA: It blocks the release of acetylcholine into the synaptic cleft
OptionB: It blocks the release of noradrenaline into the synaptic cleft
OptionC: It increases the release of acetylcholine into the synaptic cleft
OptionD: It increases the release of noradrenaline into the synaptic cleft
OptionE: It blocks acetylcholine receptors on the post-synaptic membrane
Explanation:
Botulinium toxin prevents the fusion of acetylcholine vesicles with the pre-synaptic membrane. This prevents acetylcholine being released into the synaptic cleft binding to receptors on the post synaptic membrane. This means that nervous transmission is prevented.

 

Sweat glands are innervated by cholinergic fibres. Therefore their activation requires acetylcholine release. Hyperhidrosis cant be treated therefore by an injection of botox.

Question: Whilst on your paediatric rotation, you see a young girl with webbed fingers, and realise this is because apoptosis of the webbed skin has failed. When cells apoptose, what happens?
OptionA: Increased membrane permeability, chromatin condensation, cell 'blebs' into small fragments
OptionB: Increased membrane permeability, chromatin dissipation, cell blebs
OptionC: Decreased membrane permeability, chromatin condensation, cell blebs
OptionD: Decreased membrane permeability, chromatin dissipation, cell blebs
OptionE: Peroxisomes release toxic chemicals into cytoplasm and cell dies
Explanation:
Apoptosis of the cell, ie programmed cell death, involves:

  • Decreased membrane permeability to prevent water entering the cell; therefore the cell shrinks
  • Chromatin condenses to make it easier to digest
  • Nuclear fragmentation
  • Cell 'blebs' into small fragments or vesicles, ready for phagocytosis

Necrosis of the cell, ie unprogrammed cell death, involves:

  • Increased membrane permeability allowing water inflow to the high osmolarity cytoplasm- cell swells and eventually bursts (lysis)
  • Intracellular contents including ROS released to extracellular environment- may damage other cells

Question: On which strand(s) of DNA does the end replication problem occur during DNA replication?
Explanation:
The end replication problem is the shortening of the leading strand of DNA. It is due to the RNA primer, which is deposited at the beginning of DNA replication onto the start of the 3' end of each DNA strand, which is at the start of the leading strand. DNA ligase is then responsible for degradation of the RNA primer and, on lagging strands, replacing it with DNA (and therefore joining up the Okazaki fragments). However because the RNA primer is right at the end of the leading strand, DNA ligase cannot replace it with any DNA, so the strand becomes slightly shorter each time.

Telomeres on the end of chromosomes help to protect actual coding DNA from shortening; cancerous and germ-line cells have a telomerase enzyme that extends telomeres and therefore extends the cell's life and replicating ability.
Tags: Biochemistry, PCS, Cell cycle, Chromosomes, DNA

Question: Name the lateral wall of Hesselbach's Triangle
Explanation: Hesselbach's Triangle has the lateral wall of the inferior epigastric artery, the medial wall of the rectus abdominis muscle and a floor of the inguinal canal. It is where the peritoneal bulge of a direct inguinal hernia tends to occur. This hernia develops with weakness of the abdominis wall. An indirect hernia is the result of incomplete obliteration of the processus vaginalis. This allows the abdominal organs to penetrate through the internal inguinal ring, external inguinal ring, and into the scrotum. Of note, an indirect hernia enters the internal inguinal ring LATERAL to the inferior epigastric artery (as opposed to a direct hernia, which is MEDIAL).

Question: Any change in the sequence of DNA bases can be potentially detrimental to the resulting protein. Which one of the mutations below cannot result in a frameshift mutation.
Explanation:
DNA and mRNA are read in groups of 3 bases. Every 3 bases codes for an amino acid and is called a "frame".

 

The addition or removal of bases in a sequence can shift the frame and alter the amino acid sequence that follows

 

Insertion: This is when a section of DNA is added to the original sequence

  • Consider the sequence ...CATCATCAT....
  • If by mutation an A was added to the beginning of the sequence it would now be  ...ACATCATCAT...
  • The frame has shifted and instead of producing a His amino acid you would get a Thr

Deletion: This is when a section of DNA is removed from the sequence

  • Again consider ..CATCATCAT...
  • If by mutation the first A was removed the sequence would now be CTCATCAT...
  • The original CAT frame has been altered which affects the rest of the frames in the sequence  
  • Instead of  His amino acid Leu would be produced

A nonsense mutation however is when there is a premature stop codon. This type of mutation does not change the frame

  • The three stop codons on mRNA are UGA, UAA,UAG
  • These stop codons can be accidentally produced by an accidental base change
  • For example consider the mRNA sequence ...CAUCAUUGUCAU
  • If by mutation the last U in UGU was accidentally replaced by an A- the sequence would read ... CAUCAUUGA
  • UGA is a stop- codon and would signal the end of translation and therefore shorten the protein

The nonsense mutation does not change the sequence of amino acids; it just means the resulting protein is incomplete

 

Check out this website: http://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/handbook/mutationsanddisorders/possiblemutations

Question: A patient is rushed into A&E with a suspected MI. An ECG shows a STEMI attack so it is decided to administer antiplatelet drug treatment. The STEMI is so severe that it is decided to use a drug that completely inhibits the glycoprotein 2b/3a complexes on platelets. Which of the following would be appropriate?
Explanation:
Streptokinase is an antithrombotic drug that acts on an already formed thrombus.

 

LMWH (Low Molecular Weight Heparin) is also an antithrombotic drug that acts to inhibit Factor ten from activating Thrombin.

 

Clopidogrel is an antiplatelet drug that inhibits the ADP from activating the glycoprotein complexes. This causes some inhibition but not complete inhibition since the glycoprotein complexes can also be activated by other substances e.g Thromboxane A2 to cause platelet aggregation.

 

Abciximab (CORRECT) completely inhibits the complexes.

 

Aspirin is an antiplatelet treatment that works by irreversibly inhibiting the COX domain of the PGHS enzymes needed to produce TxA2/prostaglandins that cause platelet activation.
Tags: Drugs, Haemostasis, Cardiology, Cardiovascular System, case 4

Question: A patient presents to the GP surgery where you are on placement. He has lost a lot of weight, and has jaundiced, itchy skin. He has dark urine and pale stools. The GP sends for some blood tests, which come back with very raised ALP and GGT, but normal AST and Albumin. He asks you what type of jaundice you think this. You say ...
Explanation:
The raised ALP and GGT suggest that this is obstructive jaundice.

This is also indicated in the presence of dark urine and pale stools.

The dark stools are because no conjugated bilirubin can reach the large intestine via the bile ducts, so it doesn't get converted to urobilinogen by bacteria, and then to urobilin which gives faeces their brown colour.

The dark urine is due to conjugated bilirubin leaking out of the hepatocytes, and getting absorbed into the blood stream and filtered by the kidneys. 

Raised ALT and AST would be a sign of hepatocellular jaundice, ie in viral or toxic hepatitis.

Normal LFTs but decreased haemoglobin would indicate haemolytic jaundice.

Question: What is meant by the term "slipped disc"?
OptionB: Herniation of the dura mater and arachnoid
Explanation:
The inter vertebral disc absorbs shocks and has two layers. The outer annulus fibrosus which is fibrocartilaginous and the inner nucleus pulposis which is jelly-like. 

Disc herniations are normally a further development of a previously existing disc "protrusion", a condition in which the outermost layers of the annulus fibrosus are still intact, but can bulge when the disc is under pressure.

 

BTW Arachnoid cysts are cerebrospinal fluid covered by arachnoidal cells and collagen that may develop between the surface of the brain and the cranial base or on the arachnoid membrane, one of the three membranes that cover the brain and the spinal cord. Arachnoid cysts are a congenital disorder, and most cases begin during infancy; however, onset may be delayed until adolescence.- don't worry I didn't know this before writing the question, I just found another answer on wikipedia!

Question: A 65-year-old male arrives in A&E with a recent history of chest pain radiating into his jaw and left arm. The 'normal' ECG results suggest there is no ST elevation, however the raised troponin levels indicate a degree of myocardial ischaemia has occurred, so it is most likely a NSTEMI rather than unstable angina.

Question: You are a 4th year medical student on placement in the cath lab in UHW. Suddenly a patient is rushed into the theatre with a suspected STEMI. Percutaneous coronary intervention reveals a blockage in one of the main coronary arteries. Which coronary vessel is most likely to be occluded?

Question: Bob is walking down the street and suddenly he spots the most attractive woman in the world. His sympathetic nervous system kicks into overdrive and his heart starts beating like crazy. He starts thinking about how his sympathetic nervous system can increase his heart rate, (and realises that thinking about science at moments like this, is probably the reason he is still single in the first place). Which of the below is INCORRECT about the sympathetic stimulation of the heart.
OptionC: It lowers the voltage at which funny channels can be activated.
Explanation:
A. It shows chronotropic changes- increases heart rate

and inotropic changes- increases strength of contraction

B. diastolic interval is decreased as action potentials are increased in frequency

D. Calcium uptake is increased as both T type Ca2+ channels and ryanodine Ca2+ channels (in the sarcoplasmic reticulum) are phosphorylated by PKA
E. There are lots of beta 1 receptors on the heart. They are Gs receptors therefore increase CAMP and then PKA.

C. This is a tricky one (sorry) as it isn't correct. Funny channels (which are Na+ channels) are triggered by hyperpolarisation. So instead of decreasing the threshold at which an action potential can be triggered, the sympathetic system increases the voltage at which the funny channels can open. Therefore they open at a lesser level of hyperpolarisation to increase heart rate.

Question: A woman comes into a GP surgery complaining of a continuous bloated feeling and loss of appetite after just a few mouthfuls of food. Intramural is the most common type of fibroid which is a a benign tumour of muscular and fibrous tissues, typically developing in the wall of the womb.

Question:
Big Carl is a very violent drunk. After a standard night at the SU with his crew he finds himself in a spot of bother with a lowly pedestrian. After landing a few critical hits, big Carl knocks the lowly pedestrian to the pavement. 

He swaggers back to his posse, but when going to high-5 big Steve he finds he cannot open his index and middle finger (2nd and 3rd digit), hence failing the High-5, leaving Big Steve hangin'.

 

Which nerve has Big Carl damaged?
Explanation:
Radial Nerve- This can be damaged by fracturing the BODY of the humerus and causes wrist drop.

Median Nerve- Damage to this nerve can result in distal median claw hand (what happens to carl) thenar atrophy and loss of thumb opposition. 

Musculocutaneous Nerve- Injury to this nerve results in the inability to flex at the elbow. Just remember musculocutaneous injury=cant flex muscles. 

Ulnar nerve- injury to this means you cannot extent the 4TH AND 5TH digits of hand. (also cannot abduct of adduct fingers)

Axillary Nerve- Injury to this nerve, most commonly caused by fracture of the surgical NECK of the humerus, results in the inability to abduct the arm from 15 to 90 degrees.

 

p.s. good luck with exams chaps :)

Question: A lab cytochrome P1A1 and P2E1 knockout mouse is given a low dose of paracetamol. What will happen?
OptionC: The paracetamol cannot be metabolised at all- overdose toxicity
OptionD: An angry animal rights protester storms the laboratory and frees the mice. We will never know what happens.
Explanation:
The CYP1A1 and CYP2E1 cytochromes are only active in metabolising paracetamol during overdose, when the UGT enzymes are saturated. At a low dose, therefore, there will be no effect and the paracetamol will be normally metabolised.

 

If the mouse was given a high dose of paracetamol, the UGTs would be saturated but there would be no alternative pathway for metabolism, so circulating paracetamol would be very high and there would be damage to cells.

Question:
An elderly man comes into A&E feeling extremely lethargic, with very red skin, and pain along the upper right quadrant of the abdomen.

OptionA: The symptoms are due to his arthritis. Although white blood cell count may be low due to his diet, accounting for his new symptoms
OptionD: Rickets, with low levels of vitamin D.

B - the lethargy, red skin or abdominal pain does not match with symptoms of rickets.

C - Haemochromatosis is the correct diagnosis, but levels of ferritin are usually only measured in anaemia, and would probably be, if anything, high in people with haemochromatosis.

D - Same as B

E - Correct diagnosis. Haemochromatosis is an overload of iron in the body, probably due to the patient's high red meat diet. It caused all the symptoms listed (the abdominal pain could be liver failure) as well as erectile dysfunction in men and absent periods in women. Hepcidin levels are used as a clinical tool to diagnose haemochromatosis

Question: A pregnant woman is diagnosed with hepatitis B from a heroin drug habit. Her local hospital begins discussing vaccination programs for the unborn child upon birth. What is the most likely vaccination plan for both the mother and the unborn child?
OptionA: Infant vaccinated at 3 dose of HBsAg vaccine scheduled from birth and  vaccination for the mother via passive immunisation with a single dose of HNIG if mother is negative HBeAg
OptionB: Infant vaccinated at 3 dose schedule of HBsAg vaccine at birth and mother also given active immunisation via HBsAg vaccine of 3 doses
OptionC: Infant vaccinated at 3 dose schedule of HBsAg vaccine at birth and no vaccination for the mother
OptionD: Infant vaccinated at 3 dose schedule of HBsAg vaccine at birth and vaccination for the mother via passive immunisation with a single dose of HBIG if mother is positive HBeAg
OptionE: Infant vaccinated at 3 dose schedule of HBsAg vaccine at birth and vaccination for the mother via passive immunisation with a single dose of HBIG if mother is negative HBeAg
Explanation: D is the most likely plan to be implemented; infants tend to have a 3 dose active immunisation from birth while the mother is vaccinated via passive immunisation if she is HBeAg positive; HBeAg is a viral core component of the vaccine detected usually in chronic infection (as opposed to HBsAg, which is usually detected first when the virus is present in the body). HBIG is used for passive immunisation (HNIG is used for HAV passive immunisation). The mother would also receive antiviral treatment during pregnancy to reduce her viral load.

Question: After ovulation the follicle is turned into the corpus leuteum, which cells in the corpus leuteum secrete progesterone?

Question: Which is true for Type 1 respiratory failure?
Explanation:
Type I  : Oxygenation failure --> increased A-a gradient. Could be caused by:

  • Shunt
  • Low PiO2 in high altitude
  • Diffusion impairment
  • V:Q mismatch

Type II : Ventilation failure. PaO2 < 8kPa & PCO2 > 6kPa. Caused by alveolar hypoventilation. --> low PaO2 with normal A-a gradient.

Since  

 

Alveolar Ventilation = Minute Ventilation - Dead space ventilation

= (Tidal volume x resp rate) - (Dead space volume x resp rate)

 

So, this ventilation failure could happen if:

  • Tidal volume decreases (in restrictive lung disease)
  • Dead space volume increases (in COPD)
  • Respiratory rate decreases (e.g. opiate overdose)

Question: What is the respiratory burst?
OptionA: The moment during exercise that the body shifts from aerobic to anaerobic respiration
OptionB: The increased O2 uptake by phagocytes when they perform phagocytosis
OptionC: The rapid increase in breathing rate when the central chemoreceptors sense a drop in pH
OptionD: The increased O2 uptake by bacteria when they begin proliferating
OptionE: The increase in respiration in preparation for exercise
Explanation:
A- this is the anaerobic threshold when the exercising body shifts from metabolising glucose to metabolising fatty acids, causing an increase in lactate production and muscle fatigue. Causes the RER to drop

B- correct- activated phagocytes (macrophages and neutrophils) experience an increase in O2 uptake during phagocytosis to help them convert O2 to superoxide (O2-) and then to hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) using superoxide dismutase. Hydrogen peroxide then gives off many ROS which damage and kill the pathogen or infected cell.

C- I don't think there's a name for this

D- I suppose this would happen with aerobic bacteria but it isn't the respiratory burst

C- There isn't a name for this but it is phase 1 of the central command of exercise. Before or when exercise starts, the heart rate increases and there is a positive inotropic effect, due to vagal withdrawal and increased sympathetic activity and circulating catecholamines. This is due to signals from higher levels of the brain, synapsing on brainstem areas including the vagus nerve.
Tags: Metabolic pathways, Blood Cells, PCS 3, Immunology, Inflammation

Question:
Hydrostatic pressure has great influence in pulmonary blood flow. 

Which is true about Zone 1 in the pulmonary circulation?
Explanation:
From plenary slides:

The concept is as follows: Alveolar pressure (PA) at end expiration is equal to atmospheric pressure (0 cm H20 differential pressure, at zero flow), plus or minus 2 cm H2O (1.5 mmHg) throughout the lung. On the other hand gravity causes a gradient in blood pressure between the top and bottom of the lung of 20 mmHg in the erect position (roughly half of that in the supine position). Overall, mean pulmonary venous pressure is ~5 mmHg. Local venous pressure falls to -5 at the apexes and rises to +15 mmHg at the bases, again for the erect lung. Pulmonary blood pressure is typically in the range 25 - 10 mmHg with a mean pressure of 15 mmHg. Regional arterial blood pressure is typically in the range 5 mmHg near the apex of the lung to 25 mmHg at the base.
Zone 1 is not observed in the normal healthy human lung. In normal health pulmonary arterial pressure exceeds alveolar pressure in all parts of the lung. It is generally only observed when a person is ventilated with positive pressure. In these circumstances, blood vessels can become completely collapsed by alveolar pressure and blood does not flow through these regions. They become alveolar dead space.
Zone 2 is the part of the lungs about 3 cm above the heart. In this region blood flows in pulses. At first there is no flow because of obstruction at the venous end of the capillary bed. Pressure from the arterial side builds up until it exceeds alveolar pressure and flow resumes. This dissipates the capillary pressure and returns to the start of the cycle.
Zone 3 comprises the majority of the lungs in health. There is no external resistance to blood flow and blood flow is continuous throughout the cardiac cycle.
The ventilation/perfusion ratio is higher in zone #1 (the apex of lung) when a person is standing than it is in zone #3 (the base of lung.)

Question: A young boy is told by his geneticist that he has a genetic disorder; he is told that he requires regular physiotherapy and that he will likely have recurrent lung infections throughout his life. Question: A baby born recently is found to have a genetic abnormality, with the geneticist telling the parents it is a trisomy condition. The baby has notable arthrogryposis. a prominent calcaneous and a cleft lip. What is the most likely karyotype of this baby?
Explanation:
The findings are most consistent with the criteria for Edward's Syndrome, caused by trisomy 18. These include severe developmental delay, seizures, structural abnormalities of the heart, eye, craniofacial area with a possible cleft lip/palate,  and the possibility of urogenital and skeletal defects.

Arthrogryposis (multiple joint contractures) and Clenched hands with the index and 5th fingers overriding the 3rd and 4th fingers is also likely present with a rocker-bottom foot with prominent calcaneus.

Question: A young female discusses her menstrual period cycle with her GP; she is worried that because she is having her period a certain number of days apart that something is wrong with her menstrual cycle. The GP reassures her that this might be normal, and slightly above the average number of days is usually okay in most females.  Out of the following number of days, what is the most likely number of days between periods in this female?
Explanation: A female's menstrual cycle can vary in length due to natural variation and can range from 28 to 35 days in general. 40 or 56 days would be considered abnormal. 28 is the average.

Question: Gwenyth Jones comes into your valleys-based GP practice for her annual flu jab. As you absentmindedly inject her and send her on her way, you revise some cheeky virology in your head. Influenza is in class 5 of the Baltimore classification, so has negative, single stranded RNA; what is characteristic of these viruses?
OptionA: Their genetic matter is identical to mRNA so can be directly transcripted by the host cell's ribosomes
OptionB: Bind to nicotinic acetylcholine receptors to induce entry into muscle cells
OptionD: Contain a reverse transcriptase complex with RNA-dependent DNA polymerase activity
Explanation:
A- This answer would apply to POSITIVE single stranded RNA, ie class 4 viruses eg togavirus, hepatitis A and C, poliovirus

B- This is the receptor that rabies viruses bind to

C- The RNA-dependent RNA polymerase, RNA transcriptase, is needed to convert the negative RNA into positive RNA (mRNA) in the nucleus; the mRNA can then be translated by the cell's ribosomes

D- This enzyme is characteristic of retroviruses (Baltimore class 6)

E- Only viruses that do not have animal/environmental reservoirs are candidates for eradication (eg polio). Influenza has a reservoir in birds.

Question: You invite Britney Spears into your London-based GP surgery for her new baby's 6-week check, during which you discuss her child's upcoming vaccinations. Ms Spears tells you that, as a supporter of the anti-vac movement, she is reluctant to give her child any vaccines but would feel more comfortable with the more traditional whole-cell pertussis vaccine than the "new-fangled" subunit vaccine. What do you tell her?

B- this is why the subunit vaccine is used instead (correct)- due to the absence of other antigens and pathogen components

C- there is only a very low risk of these side effects and the vaccine is still used in the developing world, so this is not true

D- the subunit vaccine gives a poorer immune response despite being absorbed onto adjuvants

E- maybe true but a bit harsh to poor Britney, she's had a tough time

 

From case group 35 xo

Question: Platelets have receptors which help them to avoid adhering to normal endothelium. Which of the following is false about the receptors on platelets?
OptionB: Ib/IX complex, receptor for vWF and thrombin
OptionD: IIb/ IIIa, receptor for fibrinogen and vWF
Explanation:
When activated (exposed to collagen from tunica media), platelets swell, become irregualrly-shaped with protrusions.

They rearrange membrane phospholipids, shed vesicles from surface --> reveal binding sites for coagulation proteins --> create coagulation complexes, accelerate Xa, thrombin formation.

 

(Haemostasis Plenary)

Question: Which of the following syndromes are associated with a higher risk of dementia?
Explanation: There is an increased risk of developing dementia in Down's Syndrome due to the possibility of a mutation in the APP gene on chromosome 21. Trisomy 21 exaggerates the chance of a mutation being present.

Question: On placement in a neurology clinic, you see a patient who has new onset seizures and features of raised intracranial pressure, which have slowly gotten worse over the past year. The consultant says he suspects a brain tumor and asks you what type you think is most likely?
Explanation:
Astrocytomas are slow growing tumors presenting with epilepsy. There is epilepsy as there is impaired regulation of extracellular ion levels, which is a normal function of astrocytes.

Ependyomas are benign but space occupying- there could be hydrocephalus and raised ICP.
Microgliomas occur mostly in immunocompromised patients and present as raised ICP.
Neuromas are rare- that is because glial cells vastly outnumber neurones and they also lack the capacity to replicate.

Oligodendrocytomas occur mostly in the frontal lobe at a mean age of 34.

Question: You see a patient on placement who has recently started taking beta-blockers. You know that these decrease contractility of the heart (as well as heart rate). By what mechanism does beta adrenergic stimulation normally increase contractility?
OptionA: Activate β1 receptors ->Gαs activated-> increased cAMP -> increased Ca2+ release
OptionB: Activate β1 receptors ->Gαi activated-> increased cAMP -> increased Ca2+ release
OptionC: Activate β1 receptors ->Gαq activated-> increased PLC -> increased Ca2+ release
OptionD: Activate β2 receptors ->Gαs activated-> increased cAMP -> increased Ca2+ release
OptionE: Activate β2 receptors ->Gαi activated-> increased cAMP -> increased Ca2+ release
Explanation:
This is the correct mechanism.

β2 receptors are found in the lungs.
Gαi inhibits cAMP formation.
Gαq does increase PLC but this is not used in the heart.

Question: What is the effect of tetracaine on the eye?
OptionC: Dilation of the pupil and loss of the corneal reflex
OptionE: Loss of the corneal reflex and constriction of the pupil
Explanation: Tetracaine is a local anaesthetic which blocks Na+ channels in nerve axons, causing loss of the corneal reflex.

Question: What is the effect of tropicamide on the eye?
OptionB: Constriction of the pupil and loss of the corneal reflex
OptionC: Dilation of the pupil and loss of the accommodation reflex
Explanation: Tropicamide is an mACh receptor antagonist blocks parasympathetic muscles, which paralyses the pupil constrictor response, leading to unopposed action of the radial pupillary dilator muscle, and ciliary muscle (which means the eye can't accomodate). Cycloplegia = paralysis of the ciliary muscle.
